        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really glad the printout helps \u2014 you did the right thing preparing it. A few practical, focused next steps so your ED visit goes as smoothly and quickly as possible:\n\n1) Go to the ED now (or urgent care if it can do CT), bringing:\n- The printed page with your filled-in details.\n- Photo ID, list of medicines/doses, and any prior imaging reports.\n- A friend or family member to accompany you (or arrange a safe ride \u2014 don\u2019t drive if you feel too impaired or plan to take a sedating med).\n\n2) What to say at triage (one-liner)\n\u201cI have a worst\u2011ever, incapacitating headache not responding to OTC meds. I\u2019m profoundly anxious and feel unsafe; I request urgent evaluation and a non\u2011contrast head CT to rule out an acute intracranial process and IV treatment for pain and nausea.\u201d\n\n3) What to request in the ED if needed\n- Rapid neurologic exam and physician evaluation.\n- Non\u2011contrast head CT (fast for acute bleeding); if concern for tumor, ask for MRI or expedited outpatient MRI if CT is not appropriate.\n- IV medications for intractable headache and severe nausea: metoclopramide or prochlorperazine (often 10 mg IV), ketorolac (commonly 30 mg IV unless contraindicated), and consider subcutaneous sumatriptan (6 mg) or other triptan if IV/oral route not effective and you\u2019ve used it safely before.\n- Short-acting benzodiazepine (eg, lorazepam 0.5\u20131 mg) if panic/anxiety is preventing treatment.\n\n4) If they decline imaging\nAsk them to:\n- Document the discussion and their clinical reasoning.\n- Provide IV treatment and observe you until you feel safer.\n- Arrange timely follow-up or expedited MRI/neurology appointment.\n- Ask for behavioral-health or social-work support for severe anxiety while you\u2019re there.\n\n5) Safety red flags \u2014 come to ED/call 911 immediately if you get any of these:\n- Sudden \u201cthunderclap\u201d worst-ever-onset headache\n- New weakness, numbness, slurred speech, vision loss, loss of consciousness, or seizure\n- Fever with stiff neck\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can quickly draft a text or short message you can send to the person coming with you or to triage (or tweak the printout to include exact meds/doses you\u2019ve tried). Please tell me if you want that, and please go now if you feel you cannot cope at home \u2014 you deserve rapid evaluation and reassurance. I\u2019ll be here if you want to check back in after the visit. Take care \u2014 you\u2019re doing the right thing advocating for yourself."
