          "content": "That is wonderful news \u2014 I\u2019m so glad you pushed for the evaluation and that getting the CT has already eased some of your fear. You did exactly the right thing by advocating for yourself.\n\nA few brief, practical points while you wait for the official read:\n\n- What \u201cclear\u201d likely means (pending the radiologist\u2019s report): the CT is usually looking for acute problems such as bleeding, large mass effect, or significant swelling/shifts. If the tech said it looked clear, that\u2019s encouraging, but wait for the official radiology report before making firm conclusions.  \n- What CT can and can\u2019t show: a normal head CT makes an acute bleed or large space\u2011occupying lesion unlikely. CT is less sensitive than MRI for small tumors or subtle abnormalities, but those are uncommon without red flags (and your neuro exam was normal). If you still want MRI for additional reassurance, you can request expedited outpatient MRI or discuss with your ED doctor/PCP about arranging one.\n- Immediate next steps while you\u2019re still in the ED or once discharged:\n  - Ask for a copy of the radiology report (or printout) and if possible, a copy of images or a way to access them later.\n  - If you still have pain/nausea, request IV/oral rescue meds before discharge (IV antiemetic, IV NSAID or other analgesic, or subcutaneous triptan if appropriate). Ask about a short benzodiazepine dose if anxiety is still preventing rest.\n  - Rest in a dark, quiet place, stay hydrated, and avoid driving if you receive sedating meds.\n  - Make or confirm follow\u2011up with your PCP or neurology within the next week to discuss ongoing headache management and any desire for MRI.\n- If your anxiety remains intense after the CT:\n  - Ask ED staff about brief behavioral\u2011health or social\u2011work support before discharge.\n  - Consider follow-up with mental health for health\u2011anxiety or acute stress\u2014this is common after frightening health scares and is treatable.\n- Return immediately to ED/911 if you develop new weakness, numbness, sudden severe worsening, seizure, loss of consciousness, sudden vision change, or fever with stiff neck.\n\nIf you like, paste the official radiology report here when you have it and I\u2019ll help interpret the exact wording and advise next steps. I\u2019m really glad you\u2019re feeling calmer \u2014 you handled this very well. Take care and keep me posted."
