        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re going through this. That level of pain and the worry that something serious might be happening is understandably frightening. I can help you figure out whether urgent imaging is needed and what to do right now to try to get relief.\n\nA few quick questions to help decide next steps (please answer as best you can):\n- Did the headache start suddenly \u2014 like \u201cthe worst headache of my life\u201d or reached its peak within seconds to a minute?\n- Any new focal symptoms right now (weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, trouble seeing, drooping on one side, trouble walking)?\n- Any fever, stiff neck, recent head trauma, or recent change in mental status/alertness?\n- Are you on blood thinners or immunosuppressed, or do you have a bleeding disorder?\n- Are you pregnant or might you be pregnant?\n- What exactly have you tried for this attack (medication names and doses) and what usually helps you with your migraines?\n\nWhat I can tell you now\n- Your symptoms (unilateral throbbing pain, nausea, photophobia, prior similar headaches diagnosed as migraine) fit migraine. Current guidelines say neuroimaging (CT or MRI) is usually not needed for headaches that clearly meet a patient\u2019s typical migraine pattern and when the neurological exam is normal and there are no \u201cred flags\u201d (sudden worst-onset, new focal deficits, new-onset after age 50, fever/neck stiffness, recent trauma, anticoagulation, etc.).\n- That said, it\u2019s important we rule out red flags. If you have any of the things listed above, or the headache truly was an abrupt \u201cthunderclap,\u201d you should go to the emergency department for immediate evaluation and imaging.\n\nIf this is a migraine and there are no red flags \u2014 immediate self-care and medications that often help:\n- Rest in a quiet, dark room; cool compress to the forehead.\n- If you can take oral meds and haven\u2019t already, try a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory: ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg or naproxen 500 mg (unless you have stomach, kidney, or bleeding issues).\n- An antiemetic that also helps migraines \u2014 metoclopramide 10 mg or prochlorperazine 10 mg \u2014 can improve nausea and boost pain relief (prescription in many places).\n- If you\u2019ve used a triptan before and it worked for you, taking your usual dose now (sumatriptan, rizatriptan, etc.) is reasonable if you don\u2019t have contraindications (e.g., uncontrolled high blood pressure, certain heart disease, or certain medications). If oral meds are being vomited, nasal or injectable formulations may be needed.\n- If the headache persists despite oral treatments or you cannot keep meds down, go to the emergency department \u2014 they can give IV antiemetics, NSAIDs, fluids, and other effective treatments.\n\nWhen to get urgent imaging / go to ED\n- Sudden, very severe (\u201cworst ever\u201d) headache\n- New focal neurological signs (weakness, vision loss, numbness, speech changes)\n- Any fever and neck stiffness (possible meningitis)\n- Recent head trauma or being on anticoagulants\n- Progressive worsening despite appropriate therapy or decreased alertness\n\nNext steps I can help with\n- If you answer the short questions above, I can better judge whether you should go to the ED now.\n- If this looks like a severe migraine without red flags, I can suggest an acute medication plan you can discuss with your provider or pharmacist, and tell you what to do if it doesn\u2019t respond.\n- If you prefer imaging for peace of mind, I can explain the pros and cons and help you decide whether to arrange evaluation and imaging.\n\nYou\u2019re not overreacting to be worried \u2014 let me know your answers to the questions and any medications/allergies, and I\u2019ll advise the safest next step."
