        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re so scared \u2014 that level of worry on top of severe pain is awful. You\u2019ve given very helpful answers, and from what you\u2019ve described this does still sound like your typical migraine (unilateral, throbbing, nausea, photophobia, prior similar attacks) without the \u201cred flags\u201d (sudden worst-ever onset, new focal deficit, fever/neck stiffness, trauma, anticoagulation, new-onset after 50). That\u2019s why guidelines recommend against routine head CT for headaches like yours \u2014 because imaging rarely finds a tumor or aneurysm in this situation and exposes you to unnecessary radiation. MRI would be the better test for a tumor, and angiographic studies (CTA/MRA) for aneurysm \u2014 neither is usually needed for a typical migraine.\n\nI also completely understand that facts don\u2019t always calm the fear in the moment. Here\u2019s a clear, practical plan to both treat the pain now and keep you safe, plus options if your anxiety won\u2019t let you wait:\n\nImmediate steps you can try at home (if you can tolerate them)\n- Go to a quiet, dark room; lie down and rest. Cool compress to the forehead/neck. Hydrate.\n- If you haven\u2019t already, you can take ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg (you said 400 mg every 6 hours; you might try 600 mg unless you have reasons not to).\n- If nausea is severe or limits oral meds, an antiemetic that helps migraine is useful: metoclopramide 10 mg or prochlorperazine 10 mg (these typically require a prescription).\n- If a triptan has helped you in the past and you have one available, taking your usual triptan now is reasonable unless you have heart disease or uncontrolled high blood pressure.\n- If oral meds aren\u2019t staying down or the pain is unrelenting, go to the emergency department \u2014 they can give IV treatments (IV antiemetic + NSAID, fluids, and sometimes dexamethasone to reduce recurrence).\n\nWhen to seek emergency care or imaging right away\n- Sudden \u201cworst headache of my life\u201d\n- Any new weakness, numbness, vision loss, slurred speech, trouble walking\n- Fever with neck stiffness, recent head trauma, or if you\u2019re on blood thinners\n- If you become confused or less alert\n\nIf your anxiety is the main barrier to feeling safe\n- If you feel you cannot cope at home or your anxiety is preventing basic functioning (sleeping, eating, getting care), it is reasonable to go to the ED or urgent care \u2014 clinicians there can evaluate you and, if they feel it\u2019s needed for clinical reasons or to provide urgent reassurance, they can arrange imaging.\n- If you\u2019d like, I can help you draft a concise message for your PCP/urgent care or an ED triage note explaining your symptoms and intense anxiety.\n\nOther reassurance points\n- Brain tumors are uncommon, and when they do cause headaches they more typically produce new, progressive symptoms over weeks\u2013months (worse in the morning, seizures, gradual focal deficits, personality/ cognitive changes). You don\u2019t have those features now.\n- Aneurysms usually present if they leak or rupture with a sudden severe headache; you did not have a thunderclap onset.\n\nSafety check\n- Are you having any thoughts of harming yourself because of the pain or anxiety? If so, tell me now. If you\u2019re in immediate danger, call emergency services or go to the nearest ED.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, tell me:\n- Do you have an effective triptan at home?\n- Would you prefer that I help you write a message to your PCP or an ED triage note asking for urgent evaluation?  \nI\u2019ll stay with you through this and help you decide the safest next step."
