        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear you \u2014 that level of fear and pain is awful, and your request for a CT comes from a very real place of distress. I can\u2019t order tests directly here, but I\u2019ll be very direct about options and a clear plan so you can get the help and reassurance you need as quickly as possible.\n\nWhy I still think this looks like migraine\n- Your history (recurrent unilateral throbbing headaches with nausea and light sensitivity, gradual onset over days, normal neurological symptoms) fits migraine. Serious causes like tumors or ruptured aneurysms are much less likely with your presentation.\n- That said, your distress is important. We should treat the headache and your anxiety now and arrange clinical evaluation rapidly if you cannot feel safe without imaging.\n\nImmediate plan you can do right now\n1) Symptom control (if no contraindications/allergies):\n   - NSAID: naproxen 500 mg orally now (or ibuprofen 600 mg if that\u2019s what you prefer).\n   - If you have a triptan that has helped before, take your usual dose now (e.g., sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO). Don\u2019t take triptans if you have uncontrolled high blood pressure or certain heart disease.\n   - For nausea and to help oral meds work: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or prochlorperazine 10 mg) \u2014 these often help migraines and nausea.\n   - If anxiety is preventing you from resting or sleeping, a short-acting benzodiazepine can be helpful for immediate relief (e.g., lorazepam 0.5\u20131 mg PO once, repeat only if needed). Tell me if you are driving or need to be alert (don\u2019t drive after a benzodiazepine). If you prefer, I can suggest non-drug calming techniques too.\n\n2) Environment: lie in a quiet, dark room, cool compress, hydrate. Try paced breathing (4 sec in, 6\u20138 sec out) or grounding techniques for panic.\n\nHow to get imaging if you still feel you need it\n- If your anxiety is so severe that you cannot function or feel safe despite the measures above, go to the emergency department or urgent care for evaluation. Emergency clinicians can perform a focused exam and, if they think it\u2019s clinically indicated (or if you are extremely distressed), arrange CT or MRI. If you have ongoing vomiting or can\u2019t take oral meds, the ED can also give IV therapy that often gives much faster relief.\n- If you prefer outpatient imaging (MRI is better than CT for tumors and involves no radiation; CTA/MRA is for aneurysms), contact your primary care provider now and ask for an urgent appointment or an order for MRI brain (with/without contrast as advised) \u2014 expect some delay, but this is reasonable if you are clinically stable and prefer outpatient work-up.\n- If you want, I can help you draft a short message to your PCP or the ED triage that explains your symptoms and your urgent anxiety so you can present it quickly.\n\nWhen to go to the ED immediately (don\u2019t wait)\n- Sudden \u201cworst ever\u201d headache or headache that reached peak in seconds to a minute\n- Any new weakness, vision change, speech difficulty, balance trouble, confusion, or decreased alertness\n- Fever with neck stiffness or recent head trauma\n- If you have any suicidal or self-harm thoughts because of your anxiety/pain\n\nWould you like:\n- A short message I can help you write to send to your PCP/urgent care or for ED triage asking for urgent evaluation and possible imaging?\n- A brief prescription plan (I can suggest exact dosing for sumatriptan, metoclopramide, lorazepam if you want one), noting I can\u2019t prescribe here but can help you request it from your provider or ED?\n\nYou\u2019re not overreacting \u2014 your fear is real. If it were me, I\u2019d try the meds/environmental measures above and if still unable to calm down or get relief, I\u2019d go to the ED now so they can evaluate and, if needed, arrange imaging and give faster IV treatment. Tell me which option you prefer and whether you want that message drafted \u2014 I\u2019ll help you word