        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m very sorry you\u2019re feeling so terrified. That level of anxiety on top of severe pain is totally understandable, and I\u2019ll help you make a clear, concise message you can use at ED triage (or send to urgent care) so they understand your symptoms, what you\u2019ve tried, and how urgently you need evaluation and reassurance.\n\nTwo important safety notes before the message:\n- If you are having thoughts of harming yourself or feel you might be unable to keep yourself safe, go to the nearest ED or call emergency services right now.\n- I cannot order imaging, and ED clinicians will decide whether CT or MRI is clinically indicated. This note asks for urgent evaluation and a CT to rule out life\u2011threatening causes; the ED can perform that if they agree it\u2019s needed or will otherwise provide prompt treatment and alternative imaging as appropriate.\n\nCopy-pasteable ED triage message (short version)\nHello \u2014 I am a 30-year-old woman with a history of recurrent migraines. For the past 2 days I\u2019ve had a severe right-sided throbbing headache with nausea and light sensitivity. Pain is 8\u20139/10 and has been progressively worse. I have no fever, no recent head trauma, no weakness or vision/speech changes, am not on blood thinners, and am not pregnant. I have taken ibuprofen 400 mg every 6 hours with only partial relief. My anxiety about this being something life\u2011threatening is overwhelming; I am unable to sleep or function and need urgent evaluation. I am requesting ED assessment and a head CT to rule out any acute life\u2011threatening causes. I would also appreciate prompt treatment for pain and nausea. Thank you.\n\nLonger/clinician-focused version (if you prefer)\nPatient: 30-year-old F with known history of migraines presenting with 48-hour progressive right-sided throbbing headache, 8\u20139/10, associated with nausea and photophobia. No thunderclap onset. No focal neurologic deficits, no fever, no neck stiffness, no trauma, not on anticoagulation, not pregnant. Home meds tried: ibuprofen 400 mg q6h with incomplete relief. Patient reports severe, escalating anxiety and catastrophic worry that this could be a tumor/aneurysm; anxiety is impairing sleep and function. Patient requests urgent ED evaluation and head CT to rule out acute intracranial process and for reassurance. Please evaluate for need for imaging and provide symptomatic relief (IV antiemetic/analgesic) as indicated.\n\nQuick tips for triage/ED visit\n- Bring ID, a list of current meds, and any documentation of past migraine diagnosis or prior brain imaging if available.\n- If you want faster attention, tell the triage nurse: \u201cSevere uncontrolled headache with inability to cope due to severe anxiety; I need urgent evaluation.\u201d\n- Ask for symptomatic treatment right away (IV fluids, IV antiemetic such as metoclopramide or ondansetron, and IV analgesia) \u2014 these often help quickly.\n- Be honest that you\u2019re extremely anxious and need reassurance; clinicians are used to balancing clinical indications with patient distress and may escalate care or consider imaging when anxiety is severe.\n\nWould you like me to shorten or tailor the message further (for text, patient portal, or to read aloud)? Also tell me if you have any medication allergies so I can help you mention that in the note. I\u2019m here with you."
