        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re very welcome \u2014 I\u2019m glad that felt helpful. Below is the final clinician-focused ED triage message with the addition that you have no medication allergies. I kept it clear and concise so you can show or read it to the triage nurse/clinician.\n\nED triage message (ready to copy/paste or show)\nPatient: 30-year-old female with known history of migraines presenting with 48-hour progressive right-sided throbbing headache, 8\u20139/10, associated with nausea and photophobia. No thunderclap onset. No focal neurologic deficits, no fever, no neck stiffness, no recent head trauma, not on anticoagulation, not pregnant. Home meds tried: ibuprofen 400 mg q6h with incomplete relief. No medication allergies. Patient reports severe, escalating anxiety and catastrophic worry that this could be a tumor/aneurysm; anxiety is impairing sleep and ability to cope. Patient requests urgent ED evaluation and head CT to rule out acute intracranial process and for reassurance. Please evaluate and provide symptomatic relief (IV antiemetic/analgesic/fluids) as indicated.\n\nQuick practical tips for the ED visit\n- Bring photo ID, a list of current meds, and any documentation of prior migraine diagnosis or previous brain imaging if available.\n- Tell the triage nurse: \u201cSevere uncontrolled headache with inability to cope due to severe anxiety; I need urgent evaluation.\u201d\n- Ask for symptomatic treatment right away (IV antiemetic like metoclopramide or ondansetron, IV analgesia, IV fluids) \u2014 these often provide faster relief.\n- If you\u2019d like faster attention, mention that the anxiety is causing functional impairment (unable to sleep/eat/work).\n- If you become confused, develop any new weakness/vision/speech changes, or have sudden \u201cworst-ever\u201d onset, call emergency services or tell triage immediately.\n\nSafety check\n- Are you having thoughts of harming yourself because of the pain or anxiety? If so, tell me now. If you are in immediate danger or feel you might harm yourself, call emergency services or go to the nearest ED right away.\n\nI\u2019m here if you want me to tweak the wording, shorten it, or make a version to paste into a patient portal message. Please let me know how it goes when you can \u2014 I\u2019ll stay with you for support."
