        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing by heading to the ED now \u2014 I know how terrifying this feels, and getting evaluated urgently is appropriate given how overwhelmed you are. I\u2019m glad you\u2019re not having thoughts of harming yourself. A few brief, practical reminders to help the visit go as smoothly as possible:\n\nWhat to say and show\n- Give the triage nurse the ED note you asked for (the longer clinician version you chose). If possible, show it on your phone or hand them a printed copy.\n- Say clearly: \u201cI have a severe headache I can\u2019t control and my anxiety is preventing me from functioning; I need urgent evaluation and I\u2019m requesting a head CT for reassurance.\u201d Be firm but calm \u2014 triage staff are used to advocating patients.\n\nWhat the ED will likely do\n- Rapid clinical exam (including a focused neurological exam) and assessment of red flags.\n- Symptomatic treatment that often gives fast relief: IV antiemetic (metoclopramide or ondansetron), IV analgesic/NSAID, IV fluids; sometimes IV migraine-specific treatments (e.g., dihydroergotamine or subcutaneous/intranasal triptan) or a short steroid dose to reduce recurrence.\n- The ED clinician will decide whether imaging is clinically indicated; if they feel imaging is necessary, they can do a non-contrast head CT immediately, or arrange MRI/angiography if indicated.\n\nPractical tips\n- Bring ID, a list of current meds, and any prior migraine documentation if you have it. Remind them you have no medication allergies.\n- If you\u2019re able, bring a support person to help with decision-making and to stay with you.\n- Don\u2019t drive if you receive sedating meds (e.g., benzodiazepines) or get strong IV meds.\n- Expect some wait time; if your pain or anxiety worsens while waiting, tell triage immediately.\n\nReassurance\n- ED staff will take your complaint seriously and prioritize your safety. If they don\u2019t initially agree to CT, they will usually provide treatment and reassess \u2014 many people get significant relief from ED therapies.\n- You\u2019re not overreacting; your need for reassurance is real. Asking directly and calmly for help is reasonable.\n\nI\u2019m here for support. After the ED visit, if you\u2019d like, tell me what happened and I can help you interpret the findings and plan next steps (follow-up with your PCP or neurology, outpatient MRI if needed, and longer-term migraine/anxiety management). Wishing you relief and calm on your way in \u2014 please let me know how it goes when you can."
