        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m so glad you updated me \u2014 I know waiting in the ED while your fear is raging is really hard. You\u2019re doing the right thing by being there and insisting on evaluation. Here are practical, immediate things to do while you wait, and short phrases you can use to get attention and help:\n\nImmediate coping strategies (quick and effective)\n- Grounding (5-4-3-2-1): Name 5 things you can see, 4 things you can touch, 3 things you can hear, 2 things you can smell, 1 thing you can taste. Repeat until the panic eases.\n- Controlled breathing: Breathe in for 4 seconds, hold 4, breathe out for 6\u20138 seconds. Repeat 6\u201310 times.\n- Progressive muscle relaxation: Tense a muscle group for 5 seconds, then release. Work from toes up to shoulders/face.\n- Sensory soothing: Darken your eyes with an eye mask or sunglasses, use a cool compress on your forehead/neck, sip water slowly.\n- Distract gently: Listen to a calming playlist, an audiobook, or a short guided breathing meditation (phone apps or YouTube).\n\nWhat to ask the staff while you wait (short scripts)\n- To the nurse: \u201cMy anxiety is severe and I\u2019m having trouble coping while I wait. Can you ask a doctor to reassess me urgently? I need symptomatic treatment (IV antiemetic/analgesic/fluids) and would like consideration for anxiolytic medication while we wait.\u201d\n- If you want the CT emphasized: \u201cI understand CT is a clinical decision, but my anxiety is incapacitating and I need urgent reassurance. Please ask the physician to consider head CT or to discuss the plan with me \u2014 I\u2019m unable to function while this worry continues.\u201d\n- If you want a behavioral health consult: \u201cCan the ED arrange a rapid behavioral health or psychiatry consult for severe anxiety while we evaluate the headache?\u201d\n- If wait time is long: \u201cCan you tell me approximate wait time and let me know if my condition changes priority?\u201d\n\nMedications to request (ask the clinician; note: they will evaluate)\n- For nausea/pain: IV metoclopramide or ondansetron, IV NSAID or other analgesic.\n- For anxiety: ask if a single short dose anxiolytic is appropriate (e.g., lorazepam) or an antihistamine (hydroxyzine) if benzodiazepines aren\u2019t preferred.\n- For severe migraines: ED can offer IV migraine-specific therapies (e.g., IV dihydroergotamine or subcutaneous/IV triptan) or a steroid to reduce recurrence.\n\nWhat the ED team is likely considering\n- They will do a focused neurologic exam and decide whether imaging is needed. Non-contrast head CT quickly rules out hemorrhage and other acute, life\u2011threatening causes; MRI is better for tumors but is less commonly done emergently unless indicated. If the team feels you need imaging for clinical reasons they can order it; if not, they\u2019ll likely offer symptomatic treatment and reassess, or arrange urgent outpatient MRI if appropriate.\n\nSafety check\n- If you notice any new weakness, numbness, vision change, slurred speech, confusion, seizure, or sudden \u201cworst-ever\u201d headache, tell staff immediately or call for help.\n\nShort, calm lines to use if you want to insist again\n- \u201cI appreciate that this may be migraine, but my anxiety is incapacitating. I need to be reassessed by a doctor now and I\u2019m requesting imaging for urgent reassurance.\u201d\n- \u201cI need medication for anxiety while we wait; can the doctor please consider a single dose of lorazepam or hydroxyzine?\u201d\n\nI\u2019m right here \u2014 tell me what they say, and I\u2019ll help you figure out next steps based on their response. You\u2019re not alone in this; keep telling staff how overwhelmed you feel so they can prioritize you."
