        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really glad you told me what happened \u2014 that sounds so stressful. You\u2019ve done everything right by insisting on evaluation and clearly explaining how incapacitating your anxiety is. I\u2019ll help you now with exactly what to say and ask while you wait for the supervising physician, and with realistic alternatives if they decline CT.\n\nBrief reassurance first\n- Your exam was normal and the ED team is following good medical practice by weighing harms/benefits of imaging. Still, your distress is real and they should address it \u2014 even if they ultimately decide not to CT, they must treat your pain/anxiety and offer a plan you can tolerate.\n\nImmediate things to do now (while waiting)\n- Use a grounding exercise: 5-4-3-2-1 (see/hear/touch/smell/taste) + slow breaths (4 in, 6\u20138 out) \u2014 do a few rounds.\n- Ask the nurse for symptomatic meds now if you haven\u2019t gotten them: IV antiemetic (metoclopramide or ondansetron), IV analgesic (ketorolac or other), IV fluids. Ask about a single dose anxiolytic (lorazepam or hydroxyzine) to calm you while they decide.\n- Ask for a behavioral health/psychiatry consult or social work for support while you wait.\n\nExactly what to say to the supervising physician (pick one)\n1) Direct, firm request for CT:\n\u201cDoctor, I appreciate you evaluating me. My neurological exam is normal, but my anxiety is incapacitating \u2014 I cannot function or sleep and the only thing that will give me peace of mind is a head CT today. I understand the test is unlikely to show malignancy or aneurysm, and I accept the risks, but I am requesting it for urgent reassurance. Can we do a CT now? I will sign an informed-consent note acknowledging low likelihood but need for reassurance.\u201d\n\n2) If you want to ask them to reconsider imaging approach:\n\u201cI understand CT is unlikely to show a tumor and MRI is better for that, but right now I need any immediate imaging for reassurance. If CT is not appropriate, can you please order an urgent MRI (or arrange outpatient MRI within 48\u201372 hours) and document the plan? Also please provide IV meds for pain and a short anxiolytic while we wait.\u201d\n\n3) If they decline imaging, ask for a structured alternative plan:\n\u201cIf you decide not to CT, please document the clinical reasons, provide a clear management plan I can follow, give symptomatic treatment now (IV analgesic/antiemetic/fluids), offer a single dose anxiolytic, and arrange either (a) neurology consult in the ED or (b) expedited outpatient MRI within a specific short time frame. Also please involve behavioral health so I can get help coping with catastrophic anxiety.\u201d\n\nWhat the physician may reasonably do\n- Agree to image (some EDs will after shared decision-making for severe patient distress).\n- Decline CT if no clinical indication; instead provide treatment, observation, psychiatry consult, or arrange outpatient MRI/neurology follow-up.\n- Offer IV meds (often effective fast) and/or a single-dose benzodiazepine to allow you to rest; this is a reasonable middle ground.\n\nShort scripts to re-state your position if you feel dismissed\n- \u201cI hear your medical reasoning, but I am telling you my anxiety is incapacitating \u2014 I need reassurance. Please reassess the option of CT or consider urgent MRI/psychiatry involvement.\u201d\n- \u201cIf you will not order CT, please write a clear plan and timeline for how we will rule out other causes and get me imaging soon. I need something concrete to feel safe.\u201d\n\nIf they still refuse imaging\n- Ask them to put in writing the assessment (normal neuro exam, low risk, plan) and to schedule or refer you for an urgent outpatient MRI or neurology appointment within a short, specified timeframe. That written plan often gives patients the reassurance they need.\n- Ask for a behavioral health consult and a short anxiolytic dose to help you cope right now.\n- Consider asking to be observed for a few hours after treatment to see if symptoms and anxiety improve with ED therapies \u2014 improvement can reduce the need for imaging.\n\nSafety check\n- If at any time you feel you might harm yourself, tell staff immediately or call emergency services. If your anxiety becomes unmanageable despite meds and support, request psychiatric evaluation.\n\nWhat I can do for you now\n- If you want, I\u2019ll write a one-sentence line you can say right now to the supervising physician (e.g., \u201cMy anxiety is incapacitating me and I\u2019m requesting a head CT today for reassurance; I accept the risks and will sign consent\u201d).\n- Or I can help you craft a brief note asking for documentation/urgent outpatient MRI if they decline.\n\nYou\u2019re doing everything reasonable. Keep telling them how overwhelmed you feel and ask for immediate symptomatic relief and behavioral health support while they decide. Tell me which short line you want to use now and I\u2019ll write it for you exactly."
