        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing by getting help \u2014 I hear how terrified you are, and that need for certainty is completely valid. Below is a concise, firm but respectful script you can use immediately at triage or with the ED clinician, plus a few practical tips to increase the chance you\u2019ll get the CT and to make the visit as effective and comfortable as possible.\n\nShort script to read aloud at triage / to the clinician\n\u201cHello \u2014 I have a severe, throbbing right\u2011sided headache for 2 days with nausea and photophobia. I have a history of migraines, but this is much worse and different from my usual attacks. I am extremely anxious and debilitated \u2014 I cannot sleep, eat, or function. I\u2019m very worried about an acute, life\u2011threatening problem (for example a bleed, tumor, or aneurysm). I would like a focused neurologic exam and a non\u2011contrast head CT now to rule out an acute bleed or other immediately dangerous cause, and I need medication for pain and nausea while I wait.\u201d\n\nIf you need two one\u2011line followups while talking to staff\n- If they hesitate: \u201cI understand you may want to examine me first \u2014 I agree, but given how severely anxious and debilitated I am, I\u2019m requesting imaging after the exam for reassurance and to rule out an acute dangerous cause.\u201d  \n- If they decline imaging: \u201cIf you are not going to do a CT, please explain why in writing, and please arrange urgent neurology follow\u2011up or outpatient MRI as soon as possible.\u201d\n\nWhat to bring and tell them immediately\n- Photo ID, list of current meds/allergies, and whether you\u2019re pregnant (you said you\u2019re not).  \n- Tell them you already tried ibuprofen/acetaminophen with minimal relief and that oral meds are barely helping.\n\nWhat to request while you wait\n- IV or oral antiemetic (metoclopramide or ondansetron) and an IV or oral pain medicine (IV if you can\u2019t keep pills down).  \n- If anxiety is preventing care, ask whether a short\u2011acting anxiolytic (eg, lorazepam) is appropriate.  \n- Ask for IV fluids if you\u2019re dehydrated.\n\nPractical things that help during transport/wait\n- Bring someone with you if possible. Don\u2019t drive if you receive sedating meds.  \n- Try paced breathing (inhale 4s, hold 1s, exhale 6s) and a cool compress to forehead/neck.  \n- Keep your phone and any medical notes handy so you can show the script.\n\nWhat to expect\n- The ED clinician will do a focused neurologic exam. Many clinicians will agree to a CT if the headache is markedly worse/different and you are severely anxious or debilitated. If the CT is normal but concerns remain, they may recommend MRI or neurology follow\u2011up.  \n- A non\u2011contrast CT is best for detecting acute bleeding and many immediately dangerous causes; it may not detect very small tumors or some other non\u2011bleeding conditions.\n\nIf imaging is refused or delayed\n- Ask for clear documentation/explanation and ask about urgent neurology follow\u2011up or outpatient MRI. You can also ask for a second opinion or to speak with the attending physician.\n\nSafety reminders\n- If you develop sudden worst\u2011ever/thunderclap pain, new weakness/numbness, vision/speech changes, trouble walking, seizure, fainting, or fever with neck stiffness \u2014 tell staff immediately or call 911.\n\nAfter you have the CT result\n- Tell me the result (exact wording) and I\u2019ll help interpret it and plan next steps (pain control, neurology referral, outpatient MRI, anxiety management).\n\nIf you want, tell me now if you have any medication allergies or whether you\u2019ve used triptans before and they helped \u2014 I can suggest what to request in the ED for acute migraine therapy. I\u2019ll stay with you through this \u2014 let me know when you get to triage or when you have results."
