        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear you \u2014 this is overwhelming, and you\u2019re doing the right thing by going to the ED for urgent evaluation. A few focused, practical points to take with you now so the visit goes as smoothly and effectively as possible.\n\nBefore you go (two quick questions)\n- Did you take any triptan (sumatriptan) for this current attack already? If so, when was the last dose?  \n- Are you on any antidepressants (SSRIs/SNRIs), MAO inhibitors, or any heart medications? (This matters for some acute meds.)\n\nWhen you get to triage / see the clinician \u2014 say these things clearly\n- \u201cSevere right\u2011sided throbbing headache x2 days with nausea and photophobia; prior migraines but this is much worse and different. I\u2019m extremely anxious and debilitated \u2014 I cannot sleep, eat, or function. I want a focused neurologic exam and a non\u2011contrast head CT to rule out acute bleeding.\u201d  \n- Tell them you\u2019ve tried ibuprofen/acetaminophen with minimal relief and that sumatriptan helped in the past but is not relieving this attack.\n\nMedicines to ask for in the ED (often given IV and effective for severe migraine)\n- IV antiemetic that doubles as migraine treatment: metoclopramide 10 mg IV (or prochlorperazine 10 mg IV).  \n- IV NSAID: ketorolac 15\u201330 mg IV (if not contraindicated).  \n- IV magnesium sulfate 1\u20132 g over 15 minutes (often helpful in severe migraine).  \n- Consider IV dexamethasone (single dose) to reduce early recurrence.  \n- If oral meds won\u2019t stay down or first-line agents fail, ask about subcutaneous sumatriptan (6 mg) or DHE infusion if appropriate and after cardiac screening.  \n- If anxiety/panic prevents care, ask about a short\u2011acting anxiolytic (eg, lorazepam) while you\u2019re there.\n\nOther useful requests\n- IV fluids if you\u2019re dehydrated.  \n- Clear explanation and documentation if imaging is declined, and urgent neurology follow\u2011up or outpatient MRI if CT is normal but concern remains.\n\nPractical reminders\n- Don\u2019t drive home if you receive sedating meds. Bring a companion if possible.  \n- Use slow breathing to reduce panic (inhale 4s, hold 1s, exhale 6s).  \n- Keep your script handy and read it if you feel overwhelmed.\n\nWhat a CT will and won\u2019t do (one line)\n- A non\u2011contrast head CT is the right first test to rule out acute bleeding and many immediately dangerous causes \u2014 if it\u2019s normal but concerns persist, ED can arrange neurology follow\u2011up or outpatient MRI.\n\nI\u2019m here after your visit\n- Tell me the CT result wording and any treatments they give, and I\u2019ll help interpret results and plan next steps (including referral for MRI or neurology, and anxiety management).  \n- You can paste the CT report or copy any discharge instructions and I\u2019ll explain them.\n\nSafe trip to the ED \u2014 you\u2019re taking a constructive step. Let me know the answers to the two quick questions above if you can, and update me when you have results."
