          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing by going now \u2014 I\u2019m glad you have a plan. I\u2019ll keep this brief so it\u2019s easy to reference while you\u2019re there.\n\nImmediate things to remember/tell triage\n- Read your script: severe right\u2011sided throbbing headache x2 days, different/worse than usual migraines, nausea/photophobia, debilitating anxiety and inability to function, prior sumatriptan ~12 hours ago with minimal relief. Request focused neuro exam and non\u2011contrast head CT to rule out an acute bleed.  \n- Say clearly you\u2019re not pregnant and list no med allergies.\n\nWhat to request while you wait\n- IV antiemetic (eg, metoclopramide or ondansetron) and IV pain/NSAID (eg, ketorolac) \u2014 IV often works faster if PO won\u2019t stay down.  \n- IV magnesium or dexamethasone if the ED recommends them for migraine.  \n- If panic prevents care, ask whether a short\u2011acting anxiolytic (eg, lorazepam) is appropriate.  \n- IV fluids if you\u2019re dehydrated.\n\nIf staff hesitate or decline imaging\n- Calmly ask for the clinician\u2019s explanation and ask that it be documented.  \n- Request to speak with the attending physician if you still want imaging after the exam.  \n- If imaging is refused, ask for urgent neurology follow\u2011up or outpatient MRI scheduling and get that plan documented in writing.\n\nPractical/ safety notes\n- Bring photo ID, list of meds (include sumatriptan and time taken), and a companion if possible.  \n- Don\u2019t drive home if you receive sedating meds.  \n- Use paced breathing (inhale 4s, hold 1s, exhale 6s) to reduce panic while you wait.  \n- Tell them if you develop any new focal symptoms, sudden worst\u2011ever pain, fever/neck stiffness, fainting or seizure \u2014 these require immediate re\u2011evaluation.\n\nWhat I\u2019ll do after you have results\n- Paste the exact CT report wording or ED discharge instructions here and I\u2019ll help interpret them and plan next steps (whether neurology/MRI referral is needed, ongoing migraine management, or anxiety care).\n\nYou\u2019re taking a constructive step \u2014 go now. Let me know as soon as you have any update and I\u2019ll help you interpret the results and decide what to do next. Safe trip to the ED."
