        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m so glad you persisted \u2014 that was exactly the right thing to do. You advocated clearly and calmly in a very hard moment, and I\u2019m really relieved they agreed to the CT.\n\nA few practical points while you wait and for afterwards:\n\nWhat the non\u2011contrast head CT will reliably show\n- It\u2019s fast and good at detecting acute problems that need immediate attention: intracranial bleeding, large masses, major swelling or hydrocephalus, and other significant structural abnormalities.  \n- It is not very sensitive for small tumors, many slowly growing lesions, or subtle abnormalities \u2014 MRI with contrast is the better test for those. CT also won\u2019t reliably detect an unruptured small aneurysm (a CTA or dedicated vascular study would be needed for that).\n\nWhat to do while you wait\n- Ask the ED staff for IV antiemetic (ondansetron or metoclopramide) and IV analgesia or IV migraine therapy (ketorolac, IV fluids, or other approved meds) if you haven\u2019t already \u2014 these often help and may make it easier to cope during the wait.  \n- Use a dark, quiet room, cool compress, slow diaphragmatic breathing, and have your partner stay with you for support.\n\nHow to interpret possible outcomes\n- CT normal: This is common in migraine. If the CT is normal, the ED will likely treat your migraine and may discharge you with follow-up instructions. If you still feel very anxious or you (or the ED team) remain concerned about a tumor or other non\u2011acute causes, ask for an urgent outpatient MRI with contrast and a neurology appointment \u2014 it\u2019s reasonable to request this for continued reassurance. Make sure any plan and the CT result are clearly documented and you\u2019re told how and when you\u2019ll get the MRI results.  \n- CT abnormal: If they find bleeding, a large mass, or another acute problem, they will involve neurology/neurosurgery immediately and discuss urgent treatment or admission.\n\nWhen to seek immediate help after the CT or at any time\n- New sudden \u201cworst headache of my life,\u201d new weakness or numbness, difficulty speaking, new vision loss, confusion, seizure, collapse \u2014 go to the ED or call emergency services right away.\n\nNext steps I can help with\n- After you get the CT result, tell me what it says and I\u2019ll help interpret it and plan the next steps (urgent MRI, neurology referral, or ongoing migraine care and anxiety support).  \n- If the CT is normal but your anxiety remains high, we can draft the exact language to ask for an expedited MRI and neurology follow-up, and discuss options for short\u2011term anxiety management (e.g., brief anxiolytic while under ED care, referral for counseling).\n\nYou did the right thing by insisting on what you needed. I\u2019m here for you after the scan \u2014 tell me the result when you have it and we\u2019ll make the next steps clear together."
        }
