        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "I'm a 30-year-old woman, and for the past two days, I've had this incredibly severe, throbbing headache, specifically on the right side of my head. I'm also feeling really nauseous and super sensitive to light, which is awful. I don't have any visual issues or weakness or anything like that, but I've had similar headaches before, which were diagnosed as migraines. I've been taking some over-the-counter pain medicine, and it helps a little, but not completely.\n\nHonestly, I'm incredibly scared. This headache feels different, and I'm terrified it could be something much more serious than just a migraine, like a brain tumor or an aneurysm. I haven't slept properly because I'm just consumed with worry, and I can barely function. I'm so afraid that if we don't investigate this properly now, something terrible could happen. I really need a CT scan of my head to rule out anything life-threatening. I won't be able to rest until I know for sure."
        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re going through this. That sounds awful. I can help \u2014 first I want to make sure you\u2019re safe, then suggest a treatment plan and next steps.\n\nQuick summary of what I heard:\n- 30-year-old woman with severe right-sided throbbing headache for 2 days\n- Nausea and strong light sensitivity\n- History of similar headaches diagnosed as migraine\n- No visual loss, weakness, or other new focal symptoms\n- OTC pain medicine helps a little but not completely\n- You\u2019re worried this could be something more serious and want a CT scan\n\nA few quick questions (will change recommendations):\n1. How did the headache start \u2014 suddenly to its worst intensity within seconds/minutes (a \u201cthunderclap\u201d)? Or did it come on gradually like your usual migraines?\n2. Is this headache similar to your prior migraines in location, quality, and associated symptoms, or is it clearly different?\n3. Any fever, neck stiffness, confusion, numbness, weakness, slurred speech, difficulty speaking, seizures, fainting, recent head trauma, or new visual loss?\n4. Any history of high blood pressure, heart disease, stroke, blood clotting disorder, cancer, or are you on blood thinners?\n5. Are you pregnant or breastfeeding?\n6. What OTC did you take (drug and dose) and when? Have you ever used prescription migraine meds (triptans, dihydroergotamine) before?\n\nImmediate reassurance and reasoning\n- Given your history of migraine and the symptoms you describe (unilateral throbbing, nausea, photophobia) with no focal deficits, this most likely is a migraine. Current neurology guidelines recommend against routine brain imaging for headaches that meet migraine criteria and have a normal neurologic exam, because imaging rarely finds a dangerous cause in that situation.\n- That said, I take your concern seriously. If any of the red-flag features above (sudden thunderclap onset, new focal neurological deficits, fever/neck stiffness, recent head trauma, new persistent progressive headache pattern, new-onset after age 50, on anticoagulants, or known cancer/immunosuppression) are present, you should get urgent evaluation and imaging.\n\nTreatment options now\nIf there are no red flags and no contraindications, reasonable immediate steps are:\n- Try a high-dose NSAID (ibuprofen 400\u2013800 mg or naproxen 500 mg), unless you cannot take NSAIDs.\n- If you\u2019ve used triptans before and had them work, a triptan (sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg, rizatriptan 10 mg, etc.) can be taken as soon as possible; combining a triptan with an NSAID (or using a combo product) often improves relief.\n- For nausea, metoclopramide 10 mg or prochlorperazine 10 mg (oral or injectable) can help and improve absorption of oral meds.\n- Rest in a dark, quiet room, cool compress, and hydration often help.\nIf oral meds are ineffective and you\u2019re vomiting or can\u2019t tolerate oral therapy, the ED can give IV antiemetics, IV NSAID (ketorolac), or IV/or IM anti-migraine meds.\n\nWhen to get imaging / urgent care\n- Go to the emergency department (or call emergency services) now if you develop sudden severe \u201cworst-ever\u201d headache, loss of vision, weakness, numbness, slurred speech, confusion, fainting, fever with neck stiffness, or a seizure.\n- If your neurologic exam is normal and this feels like your usual migraine, we normally treat first and reassess. If the headache is not improving after appropriate acute treatment or the pattern remains atypical/progressive over days to weeks, then MRI (preferred) or CT (if immediate) can be considered.\n\nNext steps I can help with right away\n- If you want, I can prescribe an acute migraine regimen (triptan + NSAID and an antiemetic) if there are no contraindications. For that I need to know about pregnancy, cardiovascular disease, and current meds.\n- I can arrange an urgent video/office visit for a quick neurologic exam today; if that exam is normal and you prefer to avoid imaging, we treat and re-evaluate in 48\u201372 hours.\n- If you remain extremely anxious and unable to rest despite treatment, I can help you get an urgent in-person evaluation or direct you to the ED.\n\nI know this is frightening. If you answer the questions above (especially whether the onset was sudden and whether you have any focal neuro symptoms or medical conditions), I\u2019ll give a specific treatment plan and, if appropriate, write a prescription right away."
