        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "Thank you for your thorough response, Doctor. I really appreciate you taking my symptoms seriously.\n\nRegarding your questions:\n1. The headache came on gradually, similar to my usual migraines, not like a sudden thunderclap.\n2. It's very similar to my prior migraines in terms of location, quality, and light sensitivity. The main difference is the intensity and my overwhelming fear that it's something worse this time.\n3. No fever, neck stiffness, confusion, numbness, weakness, slurred speech, speech difficulties, seizures, fainting, recent head trauma, or new visual loss.\n4. No history of high blood pressure, heart disease, stroke, blood clotting disorder, or cancer, and I'm not on blood thinners.\n5. I am not pregnant or breastfeeding.\n6. I took 400mg ibuprofen. I usually feel a bit better but this time it's not enough to stop my anxiety. I have not used prescription migraine medications before.\n\nI understand what you're saying about the guidelines and how it \"most likely is a migraine.\" But that doesn't change the profound fear that's consuming me. I'm so incredibly anxious, Doctor. I really can't shake the feeling that this could be something dangerous, and the thought of waiting or just trying more medication without actually *seeing* what's going on inside my head is terrifying. What if it's not just a migraine this time? What if it's something rapidly worsening that we're missing?\n\nMy anxiety is so severe I can barely eat, and I haven't had a full night's sleep in days. I'm afraid if we don't get a CT scan now, I'll just keep spiraling with worry, and that's not helping my headache either. A CT scan of my head is the *only* thing that will give me peace of mind and allow me to stop imagining the worst. Please, I really need this. It's for my mental health as much as my physical symptoms."
