        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re feeling so frightened and exhausted \u2014 that sounds awful. Thank you for telling me more; that helps me understand what\u2019s going on.\n\nSummary of what you\u2019ve told me\n- Gradual-onset headache over 2 days that feels like your usual migraines (right-sided, throbbing, nausea, photophobia)\n- No new focal neurologic symptoms, no fever/neck stiffness, no trauma, not on blood thinners, not pregnant\n- Took ibuprofen 400 mg with only partial relief\n- Severe anxiety about a dangerous cause (tumor/aneurysm) is making it hard to sleep or function\n\nWhat\u2019s most likely and why\n- Based on what you\u2019ve described and current guidelines, this most likely is a migraine. There are no red flags right now (sudden \u201cthunderclap\u201d onset, new neurologic deficit, fever/neck stiffness, trauma, age >50, anticoagulation, etc.) that would usually prompt immediate CT or other neuroimaging.\n- That said, I take your anxiety and inability to rest very seriously. I want to address both the headache and the anxiety so you can start to recover tonight.\n\nImmediate options I recommend (we can start these right away)\n1) Acute migraine meds\n   - A triptan is an effective next step if you have no cardiovascular disease or contraindications and have not had atypical auras. If you\u2019re comfortable trying it, sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO now (repeat once after 2 hours if partial response, max 200 mg/24 hr) is reasonable.\n   - An antiemetic often helps nausea and improves absorption of oral meds: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or ondansetron if needed) is helpful.\n   - If you prefer combining with an NSAID, naproxen 500 mg can be very effective together with a triptan; you did take ibuprofen 400 mg \u2014 avoid taking additional NSAIDs too frequently. If you take naproxen now, try not to redose other NSAIDs for the day.\n\n2) Help with sleep and acute anxiety\n   - A short-acting benzodiazepine (lorazepam 0.5\u20131 mg at bedtime) can be prescribed for 1\u20132 nights to help you sleep and reduce the anxiety that is fueling the headache \u2014 only if you have no history of substance misuse, severe respiratory disease, or other contraindications. This often breaks the cycle of anxiety and worsening headache.\n\n3) Nonmedication measures\n   - Recline in a dark, quiet room, cool compress, sip fluids, and avoid screens.\n   - Deep breathing or a short guided relaxation/meditation can help some people reduce the acute panic.\n\nSafety checks I need before prescribing\n- Any allergies (meds)? Any history of heart disease, chest pain with exertion, uncontrolled high blood pressure, or fainting? Any history of substance use disorder? If none, I can send a prescription now.\n\nAbout CT and imaging\n- I completely understand wanting to \u201csee inside\u201d for reassurance. Two things to consider:\n   - The chance that a CT will find a life-threatening cause given your normal exam and typical migraine features is extremely low.\n   - CT uses ionizing radiation and often won\u2019t show many abnormalities that MRI could \u2014 but MRI isn\u2019t usually urgent and isn\u2019t always available immediately.\n- Practical plan: If you\u2019d like, we can arrange an urgent in-person or telemedicine neurologic exam today. If the exam is normal and you still feel you need imaging for peace of mind, I will discuss and can help arrange MRI (preferred for non-urgent evaluation) or CT if you prefer. If you\u2019d rather not wait for a clinic visit and your anxiety is overwhelming or your symptoms change (new weakness, vision loss, sudden very severe pain), go to the emergency department right away \u2014 they can do immediate imaging and IV treatment.\n\nMy suggested immediate plan (concise)\n1. If you want me to, I can prescribe:\n   - Sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO now\n   - Metoclopramide 10 mg PO now\n   - Lorazepam 0.5\u20131 mg at bedtime PRN for severe anxiety/sleep (1\u20132 nights)\n2. Reassess in 24\u201348 hours (or sooner) \u2014 if this doesn\u2019t help, or if the headache pattern changes or you develop any red-flag symptoms, come to the ED or we\u2019ll arrange urgent imaging.\n3. If you prefer imaging now despite low likelihood of finding an emergency, tell me and I\u2019ll help arrange same-day evaluation/imaging pathway \u2014 but I\u2019d still recommend a brief in-person exam first.\n\nWhat I need from you now\n- Do you want me to send the prescriptions I listed? If so, confirm no allergies and that you don\u2019t have heart problems, fainting, substance use issues, or severe breathing problems. Also confirm the timing of the ibuprofen you took (approx what time).\n- Or would you prefer an urgent in-person visit or ED referral right now for imaging?\n\nI\u2019m on your side \u2014 I want to relieve both your pain and your fear. Tell me how you\u2019d like to proceed and I\u2019ll take care of the next steps."
