        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing by getting this evaluated in person \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re going through such terrifying anxiety about this. Below is a short, clear triage note you can show or read to staff when you arrive at the emergency department, plus practical instructions on what to bring and what to expect. I\u2019ve also included a few safety reminders.\n\nTriage note to give to ED staff\n(You can copy/paste or read this to triage)\n\nChief complaint: 30-year-old woman with severe right-sided throbbing headache x 2 days with nausea and photophobia. History of prior migraines with similar features.\n\nHistory of present illness:\n- Headache began gradually and is similar in location and quality to prior migraines, but much more severe and not responding sufficiently to ibuprofen. I took ibuprofen 400 mg at ~10:00 AM today.\n- Associated with nausea and photophobia. No visual loss, limb weakness, numbness, slurred speech, confusion, fever, neck stiffness, recent head trauma, or syncope.\n- No anticoagulants, no history of cancer, no prior stroke or heart disease. Not pregnant.\n- Anxiety about possibility of intracranial pathology is severe and preventing sleep/function; patient requests urgent head CT for reassurance.\n- No allergies to medications reported.\n\nRequest: urgent clinical evaluation and consideration of non-contrast head CT given severe persistent headache and patient distress; please evaluate and treat for acute migraine and significant anxiety as appropriate.\n\nWhat to bring and do when you go\n- Bring photo ID, insurance card (if available), a list of current medications, and any contact info for a family member or friend.\n- Bring someone with you if possible (helps with travel and support).\n- If you decide to take lorazepam for anxiety/sleep before leaving, do not drive \u2014 arrange transport or have someone else drive. If you feel too unwell to travel, call emergency services.\n- If you\u2019ve taken any other meds since the ibuprofen (trip\u00adtan, opioids), tell triage.\n\nWhat the ED will likely do\n- Triage and vitals, focused neurologic exam by ED clinician\n- If clinically indicated, a non-contrast head CT (fast and available same day) or urgent MRI if warranted\n- IV or oral medications for headache (antiemetic, NSAID, or stronger analgesic), and medication to help anxiety/sleep as needed\n- Observation and discharge instructions or admission if something concerning is found\n\nWhen to go to the ED immediately (even if you\u2019re still deciding)\n- Sudden worst-ever headache, sudden very severe pain, any new weakness, numbness, slurred speech, vision loss, confusion, fainting, seizure, fever with stiff neck.\n\nReassurance and next steps\n- I\u2019ll be here to help after your ED visit \u2014 if you\u2019d like, come back and tell me what they found and I\u2019ll help interpret the results and plan next steps (neurology referral, MRI, or outpatient follow-up).\n- If you\u2019d like, I can also prepare a brief note for your primary care or neurology clinic summarizing the ED visit for follow-up.\n\nIf you want, I can also send the prescriptions I previously mentioned (sumatriptan, metoclopramide, short lorazepam) to a pharmacy \u2014 but since you\u2019re going to the ED now, you can wait and get medications in the ED so that they can do the exam and imaging first.\n\nYou\u2019re not alone in this \u2014 I know how frightening it feels. If you want, tell me which ED/medical center you plan to go to and I can give you the closest high-volume ED address or any local suggestions. Safe travels \u2014 go now if you feel you cannot wait."
