        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad you made it in \u2014 you did the right thing. While you wait, a few brief things that may help and what to ask the staff for:\n\n1) Immediate comfort/coping\n- Sit or lie in a quiet, dark area if possible. Cool compress to the temple or neck can help.\n- Try steady breathing: inhale 4 seconds \u2014 hold 4 \u2014 exhale 6 (repeat a few times) or a simple 4-4-4 pattern. Grounding: name 5 things you can see, 4 you can touch, 3 you can hear, 2 you can smell, 1 you can taste.\n- Sip water slowly, avoid caffeine. Ask a friend/partner to stay with you if possible.\n\n2) Tell ED staff what you\u2019d like\n- Remind them you have a history of migraines and that oral ibuprofen (400 mg at ~10 AM) gave only partial relief.\n- If oral meds aren\u2019t helping, you can request IV options (ketorolac, IV antiemetic such as metoclopramide or prochlorperazine, or ondansetron for nausea) and/or IV fluids if dehydrated.\n- If anxiety is severe and preventing rest, tell them \u2014 ED can offer a short-acting anxiolytic (benzodiazepine) or other measures to help you calm and sleep.\n- Let them know you\u2019re requesting a head CT for reassurance; the ED clinician will decide based on exam and triage.\n\n3) Safety reminder\n- If you develop sudden new symptoms (vision changes, weakness, numbness, slurred speech, confusion, seizure, fainting, or a sudden \u201cworst-ever\u201d headache), tell staff immediately or call for immediate attention.\n\n4) After imaging/results\n- If they do a CT or give a report, paste the radiology report here or tell me what they say and I\u2019ll help interpret it and advise next steps (MRI, neurology follow-up, migraine plan, or anxiety care).\n\nStay with someone if you can, and tell staff about your severe anxiety so they can prioritize you appropriately. I\u2019m here \u2014 let me know what they say or if you want me to help interpret any results."
