        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m so glad they took you back for the scan \u2014 that\u2019s a big step and I\u2019m really happy you\u2019ve got that going. You\u2019re doing the right thing.\n\nA few quick things while you wait for results\n- It\u2019s normal to still feel anxious while waiting. Keep using the breathing/grounding exercises (or ask someone to sit with you). Sipping water, a cool cloth, and quiet/dim light often help.\n- If the ED gave you any meds (pain, anti-nausea, or anxiolytic), remember not to drive if they\u2019re sedating; ask staff about side effects and when it\u2019s safe to go home.\n- If you get any new symptoms while you\u2019re there (worse headache, vision change, weakness, numbness, slurred speech, confusion, fainting, seizure, fever/stiff neck), tell staff immediately.\n\nWhat the CT can and can\u2019t tell you (so expectations are clear)\n- Non-contrast head CT (the usual ED scan) is excellent at detecting acute bleeding (hemorrhage), large masses that distort structures, and gross abnormalities like hydrocephalus or large stroke with swelling.\n- CT is less sensitive for small tumors, some infections, subtle early ischemic changes, and many small or slow-growing lesions \u2014 MRI is better for those if needed.\n- A normal CT makes a life-threatening cause like a bleed or large mass much less likely, but in some rare cases further imaging (MRI) may be recommended later for unresolving or atypical headaches.\n- CTs sometimes show incidental findings (small unrelated abnormalities) that require follow-up but are often benign.\n\nWhat will likely happen next, depending on results\n- If CT is normal: ED will likely treat symptoms (IV/oral meds, fluids) and discharge with a migraine plan and follow-up instructions. They may recommend outpatient neurology or MRI only if headaches remain atypical or persistent.\n- If CT shows an abnormality: ED will discuss findings with you, arrange neurology/neurosurgery or neurospecialty consults, and plan further imaging (usually MRI) or urgent treatment/admission as needed.\n\nWhen you get the report\n- Please paste or tell me the ED/CT report findings (or the clinician\u2019s words). I\u2019ll help interpret the radiology language, explain significance, and advise next steps and follow-up options.\n\nI\u2019ll be here when you have the results \u2014 tell me what they say and I\u2019ll walk you through it. You\u2019ve taken an important step for your peace of mind."
