        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m so glad to hear the CT was normal \u2014 that\u2019s terrific news and I\u2019m really relieved for you. It makes perfect sense that your anxiety and pain would ease now that you\u2019ve got that reassurance.\n\nA few practical points and next steps now that you\u2019re home\n\n1) What \u201cCT normal\u201d means\n- A normal non-contrast head CT in your situation makes a life\u2011threatening cause (bleed, large mass, major structural problem) very unlikely.  \n- CT is less sensitive than MRI for small or subtle findings, but given your typical migraine history and a normal neuro exam, further urgent imaging is not usually needed unless things change.\n\n2) Your prescriptions and how to use them\n- Sumatriptan (typical dosing): 50\u2013100 mg PO now; you may repeat once after 2 hours if partial response (max 200 mg in 24 hours). If you were given a different formulation (nasal or injectable), follow the ED instructions.  \n- Antiemetic (e.g., metoclopramide or ondansetron): take as prescribed for nausea \u2014 this can also help oral migraine meds work better.  \n- Important safety notes: don\u2019t take an ergotamine (or another triptan) within 24 hours of this triptan. If you ever are started on MAO inhibitors or have new heart-related symptoms, tell your clinician before taking triptans. Common side effects of triptans include chest or throat pressure, flushing, dizziness, or tingling \u2014 if you get chest pain, severe shortness of breath, or concerning symptoms, seek immediate care.\n\n3) Avoid medication-overuse headache\n- Try to limit use of triptans to fewer than about 10 days per month, and limit simple analgesics (NSAIDs/acetaminophen) to fewer than about 15 days per month. If you need acute treatment that often, speak with your PCP or a neurologist about preventive therapy.\n\n4) Self-care that helps\n- Rest in a dark, quiet room, cool compress, good hydration, and regular sleep. Addressing stress and poor sleep will help reduce migraine frequency.\n- Keep a brief headache diary (triggers, timing, meds used, response) \u2014 that helps guide future treatment.\n\n5) Follow-up and prevention\n- Follow up with your primary care doctor as instructed. If migraines are frequent, severe, or changing, consider a neurology referral to discuss preventive medications or procedures (e.g., beta blockers, topiramate, CGRP inhibitors, Botox) and nonpharmacologic options (biofeedback, CBT).\n- If your anxiety about health remains high, talking with a mental health professional can help manage that ongoing fear so it doesn\u2019t fuel more headaches.\n\n6) When to return to ED or call immediately\n- New or worsening neurological signs (weakness, numbness, slurred speech, new vision loss), sudden \u201cworst-ever\u201d or thunderclap headache, fever with neck stiffness, fainting, or seizure \u2014 go to the ED immediately.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can:\n- Help review the ED discharge instructions or the radiology report if you want to paste them here.\n- Help you arrange follow-up with your PCP or a neurologist, or discuss preventive options if you\u2019re having frequent migraines.\n- Provide techniques/resources for anxiety management if that\u2019s still troubling you.\n\nYou handled this very well. Rest now if you can, use your meds as directed, and check back in with the discharge paperwork or any questions \u2014 I\u2019m here to help."
