        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re so frightened \u2014 that\u2019s understandable given what you\u2019ve seen happen to people you know. I can\u2019t order the scan, but I can give you concrete, practical steps and exact words that make it much more likely an ED/urgent\u2011care clinician will agree to a head CT, and what to do if they decline.\n\nWhat increases the chance clinicians will order a CT\n- Go to the ED rather than urgent care if you want imaging today \u2014 EDs have 24/7 CT and are more likely to image for severe, refractory headaches.  \n- Emphasize objective, concrete items clinicians rely on: severity (pain scale), duration, failure of specific medications/doses, functional impairment (unable to work/move), and that this attack is different from prior migraines.  \n- Ask for an in\u2011person neurological exam; clinicians are more likely to image after examining you and documenting persistent severe symptoms.  \n- Request shared decision\u2011making and be explicit about tradeoffs (you know about radiation but prefer imaging for reassurance). Clinicians are often willing to honor an informed, persistent patient request.  \n- If the first clinician declines, politely request a second opinion or to speak to the attending physician or supervising clinician.  \n- Bring prior records (prior imaging, prior diagnoses) and a concise list of meds/doses taken \u2014 saves time and establishes credibility.  \n- If you can self\u2011pay for an outpatient CT at a radiology center, ask the ED/PCP whether they will place an order you can take to imaging (some centers allow this), but many centers require a clinician order.\n\nExactly what to say \u2014 pick a short line for triage and a slightly longer request for the clinician\n\nTriage (very brief \u2014 say this first):\n\u201cI have a 48\u2011hour right\u2011sided headache that is much worse than my usual migraines, 9/10 pain, nausea, photophobia, and ibuprofen hasn\u2019t helped. I want an urgent clinician evaluation and I\u2019d like a non\u2011contrast head CT today to rule out a secondary cause.\u201d\n\nAt the clinician evaluation (use this as the core script):\n\u201cI\u2019m a 30\u2011year\u2011old with a 48\u2011hour severe right\u2011sided throbbing headache that\u2019s different and much worse than my prior migraines. I\u2019ve taken ibuprofen 400 mg every 6 hours with negligible relief and I\u2019m nearly unable to function. I understand CT has downsides, but given the severity, duration, lack of response to treatment, and my anxiety (a friend with similar symptoms had an important finding), I would like a non\u2011contrast head CT today to exclude an acute structural cause. If you think imaging isn\u2019t clinically indicated, please explain your reasoning and I\u2019d like a second opinion or to speak with the supervising physician.\u201d\n\nIf the clinician resists, phrases to escalate politely:\n- \u201cCould you please document the exam and reasons for not imaging, and give me return precautions? I\u2019d still feel safer with a CT; could you discuss it with your supervising physician?\u201d  \n- \u201cIf imaging isn\u2019t done today, can we schedule an urgent outpatient CT or neurology appointment within 24\u201348 hours?\u201d\n\nWhat to expect and realistic outcomes\n- Many clinicians will respect a calm, informed patient request and order the CT after exam documentation of severe, refractory symptoms.  \n- Some clinicians will decline if exam is normal and no red flags exist; they should explain why and give explicit return precautions. If that happens and you still feel unsafe, you can request a second opinion or go to a different ED.  \n- ED is most reliable for getting imaging same day. Urgent cares vary \u2014 many will refer to ED for CT.\n\nOther tips\n- Be concise, firm, and factual \u2014 clinicians respond better to specific details than emotional appeals alone. (\u201c9/10 pain,\u201d \u201c48 hours,\u201d exact meds/doses).  \n- If vomiting prevents oral meds, mention that \u2014 it increases likelihood of ED care and IV therapy/imaging.  \n- Bring someone with you if possible to help advocate and remain calm.\n\nWould you like me to draft a one\u2011sentence message you can paste into an urgent care or ED online check\u2011in, or a slightly longer portal message to your PCP right now? If so, tell me which setting (ED triage, urgent care, PCP portal) and I\u2019ll write it word\u2011for\u2011word for you. And if at any point you develop weakness, vision loss, slurred speech, confusion, or sudden extremely severe pain, go to the ED immediately."
