          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m so glad you got the CT and that it was normal \u2014 that must be a huge relief. Well done advocating for yourself.\n\nA few brief points to keep in mind now:\n\n1) What \u201cnormal CT\u201d generally means  \n- It\u2019s reassuring for acute, life\u2011threatening causes \u2014 no obvious bleed, large mass, or major shift was seen.  \n- Limitations: CT is less sensitive for very early ischemia, small posterior\u2011fossa lesions, subtle tumors, or meningitis. If you develop new focal signs or anything new/worse neurologically, you should return to ED or get an MRI as indicated.\n\n2) Short\u2011term care for your migraine (if not already treated in the ED)  \n- For acute attacks (if no contraindications): a triptan (e.g., sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg or rizatriptan 10 mg) can be very effective; repeat per label if partial relief.  \n- Antiemetic that helps headache absorption: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or IV if in clinic/ED) or prochlorperazine 10 mg (often with diphenhydramine to prevent rare movement side effects).  \n- NSAID option: naproxen 500 mg or ibuprofen 400\u2013800 mg if tolerated.  \n- If oral meds don\u2019t work or you\u2019re vomiting, get IV therapy (ED/urgent care). Avoid opioids if possible \u2014 they can worsen headaches long term.\n\n3) Follow up and prevention  \n- See your primary care physician or a neurologist/ headache specialist if: headaches are more frequent, more severe than before, you need frequent rescue meds, or this episode recurs.  \n- Preventive treatment is considered when headaches significantly affect life or occur >4 days/month (options include beta\u2011blockers, topiramate, amitriptyline, or CGRP inhibitors for suitable patients). Your clinician can discuss risks/benefits.\n\n4) Avoid medication overuse  \n- Limit simple analgesics to <15 days/month and triptans/combination analgesics to <10 days/month to reduce risk of rebound headaches.\n\n5) Red flags \u2014 return to ED immediately if any occur  \n- Sudden \u201cworst headache\u201d or sudden worsening, new weakness/numbness, slurred speech, new vision changes, difficulty walking, new confusion, seizure, high fever with stiff neck, fainting, or uncontrolled vomiting.\n\n6) If you want help interpreting the CT report  \n- Paste the radiology report here and I\u2019ll explain what each line means and whether any follow\u2011up imaging is suggested.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can also:  \n- Suggest a specific acute regimen tailored to any other medical conditions or meds you take, or  \n- Draft a short message for your PCP/neurology appointment summarizing this ED visit and your concern about recurrence.\n\nTake care, rest in a dark quiet room, stay hydrated, and reach out if anything changes or you want help with next steps."
