        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear you \u2014 your worry about missing something is completely understandable given what you\u2019ve seen happen to people you know. I want to help you get the imaging you want while keeping you safe. A few important points up front:\n\n- I can\u2019t directly place an order or schedule a CT from here. I can, however, do a quick guided neurologic exam with you now by chat, and then draft a concise clinical note/requisition you can give to your primary care doctor, an urgent care clinician, or the imaging center to request a non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance. Many centers will accept that; some may still want to see you in person first. I\u2019ll also explain what to expect and what to do while you wait.\n\nIf that sounds good, please confirm and then we\u2019ll do the quick neurologic check now. Please only do maneuvers that feel safe for you; don\u2019t try anything if you feel faint or unsteady.\n\nGuided neurologic exam \u2014 please perform and report what you see/feel:\n1) Alertness & orientation: Tell me the current date (or day), your full name, and where you are right now.\n2) Speech: Read aloud a short sentence (or type whether your speech is normal). Any slurring or trouble finding words?\n3) Vision & eyes:\n   - Any new loss of vision or double vision (beyond light sensitivity)? (You already said no.)\n   - If you have a small flashlight or your phone flashlight, briefly shine it into each eye and tell me if pupils look equal in size and react to light (smaller when light is shone). If not comfortable, skip.\n   - Follow my finger (or your phone) left to right and up and down \u2014 any double vision or inability to track?\n4) Face: Smile widely, show your teeth, and raise your eyebrows. Does one side look weaker?\n5) Arm strength: Hold both arms straight out in front of you, palms up, with eyes closed for 10 seconds. Do either of your hands drift down or feel weaker? Then squeeze your own hand strongly with the opposite hand \u2014 any asymmetry?\n6) Leg strength (only if you feel safe standing): While seated, lift one leg a few inches and then the other \u2014 any weakness? If standing, try marching in place a few steps \u2014 any imbalance or weakness? (Skip if dizzy.)\n7) Sensation: Do you have any numbness or tingling anywhere on your face, arms, or legs?\n8) Coordination: Touch your nose with your right index finger, then your left, a few times. Any trouble coordinating?\n9) Gait (only if safe): Walk a short distance (or walk in place) \u2014 any unsteadiness or difficulty?\n\nAfter you send the findings, I will:\n- Draft a brief clinical note/requisition that documents your history, the exam findings you report, and the request for a non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance. You can copy/paste or print it and present to your PCP, urgent care, or the imaging center.\n- Give practical next steps (where to go, what the CT involves, radiation & costs, what results mean).\n- Provide immediate self-care measures and medication options you can request from a clinician (or go to ED/urgent care for IV treatment if symptoms worsen or oral meds aren\u2019t effective).\n\nIf you\u2019d rather not do the exam here, tell me and I\u2019ll draft the requisition anyway, but many centers prefer documentation of a recent neuro exam before scheduling.\n\nAre you ready to do the neurologic check now? If so, start with item 1 (orientation). If you feel too symptomatic to do it, tell me and we\u2019ll instead prepare the requisition and the best next place to go."
