        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thank you \u2014 you did great with the exam. Below is a concise clinical note/requisition you can print or copy and present to your primary care clinician, urgent care, or the imaging center to request a non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance. I\u2019ve included the relevant history, the tele\u2011exam findings you reported, and the rationale for the request. I\u2019ve also added brief practical next steps and safety advice.\n\nPlease note: I cannot place the order myself. This document is for you to present to a clinician/imaging center so they have the required documentation to order the scan. Some centers may still require an in\u2011person clinician visit or clinician signature before scheduling.\n\nClinical note / Imaging request (please fill in the patient details and date)\n\nPatient name: _______________________  DOB: _______________  Date: ______________\n\nClinical history:\n- 30\u2011year\u2011old woman with 2 days of severe, throbbing, right\u2011sided headache with associated nausea and photophobia. She has a prior history of migraine with similar headaches, but reports this episode is more intense and not responding well to OTC analgesics.\n- No sudden onset (\u201cworst headache of life\u201d), no recent head trauma, no fever or neck stiffness. No history of stroke, cardiovascular disease, hypertension, anticoagulant use, or pregnancy.\n- Patient is notably anxious and requests imaging for reassurance given personal/family experiences.\n\nFocused neurologic exam (patient\u2011reported via telemedicine):\n- Alert and oriented to person/place/day.\n- Speech normal (no dysarthria or aphasia).\n- Pupils equal and reactive to light; extraocular movements intact; no diplopia.\n- Cranial nerve/face: symmetric facial movement; no facial droop.\n- Motor: symmetric strength in upper and lower extremities, no drift.\n- Sensation: no focal numbness/tingling.\n- Coordination: finger\u2011to\u2011nose intact.\n- Gait: steady.\n- No focal neurologic deficits elicited on the tele\u2011exam.\n\nAssessment:\n- Presentation most consistent with migraine without focal neurologic deficit. No red flag features on current history or tele\u2011exam. However, patient requests a non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance (shared decision\u2011making).\n\nRequest:\n- Please consider ordering a non\u2011contrast CT head at the patient\u2019s request for reassurance. The patient understands the low pre\u2011test probability of acute intracranial pathology given the normal neurologic exam, and is seeking imaging to reduce anxiety and proceed with treatment.\n\nRecommended logistics/notes for imaging center:\n- Non\u2011contrast CT head (routine), outpatient scheduling as soon as practical per patient preference.\n- If the imaging center requires clinician signature/authorization, please provide clinician contact information or advise patient on next steps.\n- Advise patient to seek ED evaluation if any new red\u2011flag symptoms develop (sudden severe/worst headache, new focal deficit, vision loss, slurred speech, new weakness/numbness, seizure, loss of consciousness, fever with neck stiffness).\n\nSigned (for patient use / clinician review):\n- Prepared by: [Patient name] (telemedicine exam performed and reported by patient) \u2014 please document and sign/authorize as needed.\n- Clinician to sign/authorize ordering: ___________________________  (name/title/contact)\n\nPractical next steps and advice\n- Where to go: Contact your PCP or an urgent care to present this note and request the CT. Many outpatient imaging centers will schedule with a clinician order; if they require clinician authorization, urgent care can typically provide it quickly. If you want the CT the same day and are unable to obtain an outpatient order, ED can do it but will evaluate and may provide IV treatment if needed.\n- What the CT involves: Non\u2011contrast head CT is quick (~5\u201310 minutes scan time), does not require IV contrast, and exposes you to approximately 2\u20134 mSv of radiation (small but real exposure).\n- Results: Radiology will issue a report. If an acute abnormality is found, the imaging center will typically contact you and/or the clinician; if you develop worsening/new symptoms, go to the ED immediately.\n- While waiting for imaging: If you wish to try acute migraine treatment now (can be done even if imaging is scheduled), suggested options to discuss with a prescribing clinician include:\n  - Sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO (start 50 mg if first time), may repeat once after 2 hours (max 200 mg/24 h) \u2014 contraindicated in known cardiovascular disease/uncontrolled hypertension/pregnancy.\n  - Naproxen 500 mg PO (if not contraindicated).\n  - Metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or IM/IV if vomiting or if in urgent care/ED) for nausea and adjunctive headache relief.\n  - Dark, quiet room, cold compress.\n- Urgent care/ED: Go immediately if you develop sudden severe (\u201cthunderclap\u201d) headache, new weakness/numbness, slurred speech, vision loss, seizures, loss of consciousness, or fever/neck stiffness.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can:\n- Tailor this note with your full legal name, DOB, and the current date/time filled in so it\u2019s ready to print.\n- Draft a short message you can send to your PCP or an urgent care to request they sign/authorize the CT and/or prescribe acute medications.\n\nWould you like me to fill in your name/DOB/date in the note now and produce a ready\u2011to\u2011print version? Also tell me whether you want a suggested message to send to your PCP/urgent care requesting the CT and an acute-medication prescription."
