        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re going through such a bad headache. I can help you figure out whether imaging is needed and suggest next steps to get relief.\n\nBrief answer up front: because you\u2019re 30 and have a history of similar migraines with nausea and photophobia, neuroimaging (CT) is usually not necessary if your neurological exam is normal and there are no \u201cred flag\u201d features. However, if any red flags are present I will advise imaging or urgent evaluation right away.\n\nA few quick questions so I can advise safely:\n- Was the onset sudden (like \u201cthe worst headache of my life\u201d or thunderclap) or did it come on gradually?\n- Is this headache different in pattern, severity, or location from your usual migraines?\n- Any new neurological symptoms now or earlier in this attack: weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, slurred speech, vision loss or double vision, difficulty walking, confusion, or fainting?\n- Any fever, neck stiffness, head trauma, or recent infection?\n- Are you on blood thinners, immunosuppressed, or pregnant / breastfeeding?\n- What have you already tried for this attack (specific OTC drugs, migraine prescription meds such as triptans or antiemetics) and did any help before?\n- Do you have a history of stroke, heart disease, or uncontrolled high blood pressure?\n\nWhat I\u2019d recommend next (depending on answers)\n- If you have no red flags and a normal neuro exam: reassure that imaging is not usually needed. For treatment now you can try (unless contraindicated):\n  - An antiemetic such as metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or prochlorperazine) for nausea and to increase absorption of oral meds.\n  - A migraine-specific abortive if previously effective (sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO if you\u2019ve used it before and have no cardiovascular disease or uncontrolled HTN).\n  - A higher-dose NSAID (naproxen 500 mg or ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg) if not already taken and no contraindication.\n  - Rest in a dark, quiet room, cold compress to the painful area, and stay hydrated.\n  - If oral meds are vomiting/not absorbed or this is refractory, urgent care or the emergency department can provide IV therapy (metoclopramide/prochlorperazine, ketorolac, fluids) which often helps quickly.\n- If any red flag is present (sudden worst headache, new focal neuro deficit, changing pattern of headaches, fever/neck stiffness, head trauma, anticoagulant use, new-onset after age 50, loss of consciousness, severe progressive worsening) \u2014 go to the emergency department or I will arrange immediate neuroimaging (CT head urgently; MRI or CT angiography as indicated).\n\nIf you want, answer the questions above and I\u2019ll tell you whether I\u2019d recommend immediate ED/imaging vs a treatment plan you can try now and when to seek urgent care. If you prefer, I can also draft language you can give to an urgent care or ED to expedite evaluation."
