        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thank you \u2014 I hear you: this is frightening and overwhelming, and you want definite reassurance now. I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re suffering so much. I\u2019ll be direct and clear.\n\nWhy I\u2019m reluctant to order a CT for you today\n- Evidence-based guidance (and most neurologists) recommend against routine neuroimaging for people with a known history of migraine who have a typical migraine pattern, a normal neurological exam, and no \u201cred flag\u201d features. You\u2019ve told me you meet those conditions.\n- A head CT in this situation is unlikely to find a dangerous cause (very low diagnostic yield), so it won\u2019t usually change management.\n- Potential harms: radiation exposure (especially relevant in younger adults), false-positive or incidental findings that often lead to anxiety and more tests (MRI, angiography, sometimes invasive procedures), unnecessary cost, and delays in getting effective treatment for the migraine.\n\nThat said \u2014 I respect your concerns and want to help you get safe care and relieve your anxiety\n- If you still strongly prefer imaging for peace of mind, the fastest way to get a CT today is to go to an emergency department or urgent care and ask for evaluation; they can order imaging and provide immediate IV treatment if needed. I can help you with exact wording to say to the ED/urgent care clinician, or draft a short note you can send to your primary care office requesting imaging now.\n- If you want my medical opinion as your treating clinician: I would not recommend CT based on what you\u2019ve described, but I will support you in whichever reasonable choice you make.\n\nImmediate practical options (pick what you want)\n- If you prefer imaging now: go to ED/urgent care and ask for a head CT for \u201csevere, prolonged migraine that is worse than usual \u2014 patient requests imaging for reassurance.\u201d Tell them you have no focal neuro symptoms but the pain is incapacitating. If you want, I can write that sentence for you to show the clinician.\n- If you prefer to avoid ED but want help with symptom control: an evidence-based acute option that often works when OTCs fail is a triptan (e.g., sumatriptan) if you have used it safely before and have no heart disease or uncontrolled hypertension. An antiemetic (metoclopramide or prochlorperazine) improves nausea and helps absorption of oral meds. If oral meds aren\u2019t tolerated or this is truly refractory, ED can give IV meds (metoclopramide, ketorolac, fluids, sometimes dihydroergotamine). I can guide you through dosing and contraindications if you\u2019d like.\n- Safety-net: go to the ED immediately if you develop sudden severe worsening (\u201cworst headache\u201d), any new weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision loss, confusion, fainting, fever and neck stiffness, or seizure.\n\nWhat I can do right now for you\n- Draft a short message/line you can use with ED, urgent care, or your PCP to request a CT.\n- Help you decide whether a triptan or ED visit for IV therapy is suitable.\n- Stay with you through next steps \u2014 tell me which option you prefer.\n\nWhich would you like: (A) I write a brief script you can use for ED/urgent care to request CT now, (B) I help you with an acute treatment plan (triptan/antiemetic) to try first, or (C) I draft a message to your PCP asking them to order imaging?"
