        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re going through this \u2014 I hear how terrified and overwhelmed you are, and that you want definitive reassurance now. I want to help you get that as quickly and safely as possible.\n\nFirst, an important limitation: I can\u2019t directly order tests or schedule imaging. I can, however, tell you exactly how to get a CT done right now and help you communicate what to say to the clinician who can place the order, or help you contact a telemedicine or urgent care provider who can evaluate you and order imaging immediately.\n\nPractical options to get a head CT today\n1) Emergency department \u2014 fastest, most direct route\n- Go to the ED and say something like this (you can read it aloud):  \n  \u201cI have a history of migraines. For 48 hours I\u2019ve had a severe, throbbing right\u2011sided headache with nausea and light sensitivity. It got much worse over a few hours and is far worse than usual and is incapacitating. I have no new weakness, numbness, vision change, speech disturbance, fever, or neck stiffness. I\u2019m extremely anxious and would like a non-contrast head CT to rule out an acute intracranial problem and for reassurance.\u201d  \n- ED can both order imaging immediately and give IV treatments for pain/nausea while you wait.\n\n2) Same\u2011day urgent care or walk\u2011in clinic / telemedicine visit\n- Many urgent cares and urgent telemedicine services can evaluate and arrange imaging or transfer you to the ED for immediate CT if they feel it\u2019s appropriate. If you prefer to avoid the ED, call a local urgent care or a telehealth service and use the same script above.\n\n3) Ask your PCP for an urgent same\u2011day appointment or an immediate imaging order\n- If you have good access to your PCP and they can see you today, they could order imaging \u2014 but many clinics cannot get an urgent CT same\u2011day without sending you to the hospital or imaging center with an order.\n\nWhat to expect and brief facts (so you can weigh your decision)\n- A non\u2011contrast head CT is the usual first test to look for major acute problems (bleed, large mass, hydrocephalus). It\u2019s quick and widely available. Typical radiation dose for a head CT is small (~1\u20132 mSv), but not zero.\n- In people with a typical migraine pattern and a normal neurologic exam, CT is very unlikely to show a dangerous cause. If the scan is normal, it may or may not reduce your anxiety \u2014 some people feel relief, others continue to worry despite a normal result.\n- A CT can also detect incidental findings that may lead to more tests and anxiety.\n- If your neurologic exam is normal and you have no red flags, many clinicians prefer treating the migraine first. But if you want imaging for reassurance, ED/urgent care can provide it.\n\nSafety net \u2014 go to ED immediately if any of these happen\n- Sudden \u201cworst headache of my life\u201d or thunderclap onset  \n- Any new weakness, numbness, slurred speech, vision loss, confusion, fainting, or seizure  \n- Fever with neck stiffness or worsening altered mental status\n\nHow I can help right now\n- I can draft a short two\u2011sentence script you can show or read to ED/urgent care staff (I included one above already).  \n- I can draft a message you can send to your PCP or a telemedicine clinician requesting same\u2011day evaluation and CT order.  \n- If you change your mind and want immediate, safe medication guidance to try now while arranging imaging, I can give that too.\n\nWhich would you like me to do for you now \u2014 (A) a short message you can use with ED/urgent care (I can refine it to your exact words), (B) a message to send to your PCP or telemedicine service asking for a same\u2011day CT, or (C) information/dosing for medications you can try right away?"
