        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m Dr. Smith. I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re going through such a painful attack. Thank you for the clear details. I can help you figure out the safest next steps and treatment options.\n\nWhat I\u2019m hearing\n- You\u2019re a 30\u2011year\u2011old with a sudden, very severe right\u2011sided throbbing headache for 2 days with nausea and light sensitivity.\n- You have a history of migraine and no weakness, numbness, speech problems, or visual changes this time.\n\nHow I interpret this\n- Your symptoms (unilateral, throbbing, nausea, photophobia, history of migraine) sound most consistent with a migraine. That said, it\u2019s understandably frightening when an attack is worse than usual.\n- Current guidelines say that if someone has a history of migraine, a normal neurological exam, and no \u201cred flags,\u201d routine head CT or MRI is not usually needed. The main red flags that would prompt urgent neuroimaging or an ED evaluation are: sudden \u201cworst-ever/thunderclap\u201d onset, new focal neurological deficits, fever/stiff neck (possible meningitis), new headache after age 50, recent head trauma, seizure, progressive worsening over days to weeks, or concerning change in consciousness.\n\nPractical next steps I recommend now\n1. Try evidence\u2011based acute migraine treatments (unless you have contraindications):\n   - If you\u2019ve used triptans before and they worked and you have no heart disease, uncontrolled hypertension, or pregnancy, you can try sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO (repeat once after 2 hours if needed; max 200 mg/day). \n   - Consider combining with an NSAID such as naproxen 500 mg PO (can reduce recurrence).\n   - For nausea: metoclopramide 10 mg PO or prochlorperazine 10 mg can help and improve absorption of oral meds.\n   - Nonpharmacologic: lie in a dark, quiet room, use a cold compress, sip fluids.\n   - If you cannot keep pills down or oral meds don\u2019t help, ED treatment (IV fluids, IV antiemetic, IV dihydroergotamine or IV triptan) may be needed.\n\n2. When to go to the emergency department or get imaging now\n   - If this was a thunderclap (sudden onset to worst intensity within seconds/minutes).\n   - If you develop new focal weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, confusion, seizure, fever with stiff neck, or progressive deterioration.\n   - If your headache is not improving despite trying appropriate acute treatments, or if you\u2019ve had continuous severe headache for >72 hours (status migrainosum), you should go to ED.\n\nA few quick questions so I can be more specific\n- Have you tried triptans or prescription migraine meds before for your migraines? If yes, which ones and did they help?\n- Do you have high blood pressure, heart disease, stroke, or smoking history, or are you pregnant/planning pregnancy?\n- What OTC meds have you tried (drug and dose) and when did you take them?\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can suggest a specific medication plan based on your answers, and advise whether a phone/urgent visit with your primary care provider or a trip to urgent care/ED is best. If you feel very anxious and want imaging for reassurance despite no red flags, I can explain what a CT vs MRI would show and their limitations \u2014 but medically, imaging is usually not necessary in this situation."
