        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thank you \u2014 I hear you. I\u2019m really sorry this headache is so brutal and that it feels different and far worse than usual. Your worry and desire for certainty are completely understandable.\n\nA few important points I want to be clear about\n- I\u2019m not trying to minimize how awful you feel or to tell you your concerns aren\u2019t real. You know your body and your migraines, and your distress matters.\n- I also want to be honest about what a head CT will and won\u2019t do for you right now and the usual medical reasons we reserve it for certain situations.\n\nWhy doctors don\u2019t routinely order CT for migraine-like headaches without red flags\n- CT scans find acute bleeding/injury very well, but for someone with a typical migraine picture (unilateral throbbing, nausea, photophobia) and a normal neurologic exam, the chance that CT will show a dangerous problem is extremely low. That\u2019s why guidelines recommend against routine imaging in these situations.\n- Harms and downsides of an unnecessary CT: exposure to ionizing radiation (small but real increase in lifetime cancer risk), possible false positives that lead to more tests and anxiety, costs, and potential delays in getting effective migraine treatment. Ordering tests primarily for reassurance can sometimes make things worse if they yield ambiguous results.\n\nThat said \u2014 your preferences matter\n- If after hearing the reasons you still strongly prefer imaging for peace of mind, it\u2019s reasonable to discuss this with an in-person clinician (your PCP, urgent care, or ED). Many clinics will consider imaging based on persistent patient concern and clinical judgment. I can help you prepare what to say to them if you\u2019d like.\n\nPractical steps I recommend right now (because relief is urgent)\n1) Try an evidence-based acute regimen unless you have a contraindication:\n   - Sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO once (can repeat once after 2 hours; max 200 mg/day) \u2014 you said you haven\u2019t tried triptans recently and you have no heart disease or uncontrolled HTN, so this is a reasonable next step.\n   - Add naproxen 500 mg PO (one dose) with the triptan if tolerated \u2014 this combination reduces recurrence.\n   - For nausea: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or prochlorperazine 10 mg) helps nausea and improves absorption of oral meds. Note metoclopramide can cause restlessness (akathisia) \u2014 an antihistamine like diphenhydramine can reduce that if needed.\n   - Non-drug measures: dark, quiet room, cold compress, sip fluids.\n\n2) When to go to the emergency department / get urgent imaging now\n   - If this headache was thunderclap (sudden worst-ever reaching peak in seconds/minutes).\n   - If you develop new focal weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, confusion, seizure, fever with stiff neck, loss of consciousness, or progressive worsening or altered mental status.\n   - If you can\u2019t control pain or vomiting at home despite the above therapies, or if the severe headache has been essentially continuous >72 hours (status migrainosum), go to the ED \u2014 they can give IV rescue meds and will image if clinically indicated.\n\nIf you\u2019d like I can:\n- Give you a short, specific medication plan to try now (doses and what to expect).\n- Help you script a brief message you can send to urgent care/PCP/ED explaining your symptoms and asking for imaging if they agree.\n- Walk through pros/cons of CT vs MRI if you want more details.\n\nWhich would you prefer right now \u2014 a specific medication plan to try at home, or help preparing to ask a clinic/ED for a CT? If you\u2019re getting worse or develop any of the emergency symptoms above, please go to the ED or call emergency services right away."
