          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re in so much pain and feeling so frightened \u2014 that sounds awful. I hear you: you want definitive reassurance right now, and a CT scan feels like the clearest way to get that. I want to be direct, honest, and respectful of your wishes.\n\nTwo upfront facts\n- I can\u2019t order a CT for you directly through this chat. I can, however, tell you exactly what to ask for and how to get it (ED, urgent care, or your clinician), and give a clear, immediate treatment plan you can try while arranging that.\n- I also won\u2019t dismiss your concern \u2014 your distress is real and important. My job is to balance that with what is medically appropriate and safest for you.\n\nWhy clinicians hesitate to order CTs for migraine-like headaches\n- CT scans are good at detecting acute bleeding or large structural problems, but in people with a typical migraine picture and a normal neurologic exam the chance of finding a dangerous problem is extremely low. That\u2019s why guidelines recommend against routine imaging in this situation.\n- Ordering an unnecessary CT isn\u2019t harmless:\n  - Radiation exposure (head CT gives a small but real dose of ionizing radiation).\n  - Incidental findings that are unrelated to your pain but can trigger more tests, procedures, anxiety, and cost.\n  - False reassurance: a normal CT doesn\u2019t change treatment and can\u2019t \u201ctreat\u201d the pain you\u2019re in.\n  - Cost and time, and potential delays to getting effective acute treatment (which is what will actually relieve you).\n\nSo what actually happens for you if you \u201cjust\u201d get a CT?\n- Possible outcomes:\n  - Normal CT \u2192 no dangerous bleeding or mass seen; you may feel reassured, but your headache still needs treatment.\n  - Abnormal CT (unlikely given your presentation) \u2192 triggers urgent follow-up, more tests, possible admission or interventions \u2014 which may be necessary, but also may be stressful.\n  - Incidental benign finding \u2192 additional investigations and anxiety that were avoidable.\n- The radiation risk from a single head CT is small in absolute terms, but not zero.\n\nGiven what you told me (30 years old, known migraines, no focal neuro symptoms, no cardiac disease or pregnancy), here are practical options you can choose from right now\n\nOption A \u2014 try an evidence\u2011based rescue regimen at home (many people get substantial relief from this):\n- Sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO once now (can repeat one dose after 2 hours; max 200 mg/day). If you\u2019ve never taken it before, start with 50 mg.\n- Naproxen 500 mg PO once with the triptan (helps reduce recurrence).\n- For nausea: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or prochlorperazine 10 mg) \u2014 helps nausea and absorption of oral meds. Note possible side effects (restlessness); diphenhydramine can help if that occurs.\n- Non\u2011drug: dark, quiet room and cold compress, sip clear fluids.\n- If pills won\u2019t stay down or oral meds fail, go to ED for IV rescue (IV antiemetic + IV triptan or IV dihydroergotamine) which often relieves status migrainosum.\n\nOption B \u2014 pursue imaging now for reassurance\n- Go to your local emergency department or urgent care and request a \u201cnon\u2011contrast head CT\u201d to evaluate for acute intracranial hemorrhage or other gross abnormalities. ED clinicians commonly will do this if your pain is unbearable and you want immediate reassurance, and they can provide IV pain relief while you\u2019re there.\n- If you prefer outpatient imaging, MRI is more sensitive for many structural problems but takes longer and may not be immediately available; ED is the fastest route.\n\nWhen you should go to the ED urgently (regardless of CT decision)\n- If the headache was a thunderclap (sudden worst-ever in seconds/minutes).\n- If you develop new weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, confusion, seizures, fever with stiff neck, loss of consciousness, or progressive deterioration.\n- If severe pain and vomiting cannot be controlled at home despite the rescue meds above, or if it\u2019s lasted essentially continuously >72 hours.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Walk you step\u2011by\u2011step through the rescue meds (dosing, what to expect, side effects).\n- Draft a one\u2011sentence line you can say to ED/urgent care staff (\u201cI have a severe migraine different from usual, very severe pain and nausea; I\u2019d like a non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance and IV treatment if needed\u201d).\n- Help you decide between trying meds now or going straight to ED.\n\nWhich would you like to do right now \u2014 try the rescue meds at home, or head to the ED for a CT and IV treatment? I\u2019m here and will support whatever you choose."
