        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad you made it in \u2014 you\u2019re doing the right thing to get evaluated. Quick, simple reminders you can use now at triage and with the ED doctor, plus what to expect:\n\nWhat to say at triage (very brief)\n\u201cHi, I\u2019m a 30\u2011year\u2011old with a history of migraines. I\u2019ve had a severe right\u2011sided throbbing headache for 2 days with nausea and photophobia that isn\u2019t responding to OTC meds. I\u2019d like urgent evaluation and a non\u2011contrast head CT today for reassurance. I\u2019m not on blood thinners and I\u2019m not pregnant.\u201d\n\nWhat to say to the ED physician\n\u201cI have a long history of migraines. This is the worst I\u2019ve had in a while \u2014 same type but much worse and not responding to ibuprofen. No new weakness, numbness, speech or vision changes, no fever, and no recent trauma. I\u2019m very anxious and would feel reassured by a non\u2011contrast head CT today. While you\u2019re evaluating me, I\u2019d appreciate IV antiemetic and analgesia if appropriate.\u201d\n\nPractical checklist for you now\n- Give them a list of current medications, allergies, and any prior imaging or reports (or CD) if you have them.  \n- Expect a urine pregnancy test (standard before CT in people of childbearing potential).  \n- Ask for IV antiemetic (e.g., metoclopramide/prochlorperazine) and IV analgesic/NSAID (e.g., ketorolac) while you wait.  \n- Ask them to document a focused neurologic exam. That exam often determines whether CT is performed.  \n- If they agree to image, ask for a non\u2011contrast head CT and request a copy of the report and images or instructions on how to get them.\n\nWhat the ED may do and why\n- The ED may treat you first and then decide on CT based on the exam and response to treatment. They can, however, order CT same day if they think it\u2019s appropriate or if your anxiety and symptoms justify it. If CT is normal but symptoms persist, they may consider MRI later or specialist follow\u2011up.\n\nAfter the CT/result\n- If you\u2019d like, message me the ED discharge summary or CT report (or a photo of the report) and I\u2019ll help explain the findings and advise on next steps and follow\u2011up.\n\nIf anything changes on the way or while you\u2019re there (new weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, sudden vision change, sudden \u201cworst\u2011ever\u201d pain, fainting, seizure, fever with stiff neck), tell triage/clinician immediately or call for help.\n\nI\u2019ll be here to help interpret whatever the ED provides and to help plan follow\u2011up. Wishing you a fast evaluation and relief."
