          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re still in so much pain. A few quick, practical things while you wait that will help get you assessed and (if appropriate) imaged quickly \u2014 and keep you safer and more comfortable:\n\nWhat to ask for at triage/when you\u2019re seen\n- Use your script: state history, say you want urgent evaluation and a non\u2011contrast head CT today for reassurance.  \n- Ask for IV antiemetic (metoclopramide or prochlorperazine) and IV analgesic/NSAID (e.g., ketorolac) while you wait.  \n- Expect a urine pregnancy test (standard for CT in people of childbearing potential).  \n- Give them a med/allergy list and any prior imaging reports/CD.\n\nIf the team says CT isn\u2019t indicated right away\n- Ask for a focused neurologic exam and the attending physician\u2019s opinion. You can calmly request a second opinion if you remain very concerned.  \n- If CT is declined after exam, ask for clear documentation and for a plan for symptom relief and outpatient follow\u2011up (neurology or MRI if needed). Try to stay flexible but persistent about wanting an explanation.\n\nComfort measures while waiting\n- Rest in a dark, quiet area; use sunglasses or an eye mask and a cool compress to the head/neck.  \n- Sip water slowly; try slow deep breathing and minimize screens/smells.  \n- If you can tolerate oral antiemetic (metoclopramide 10 mg) and an NSAID (naproxen 500 mg) and haven\u2019t taken them in the last few hours, consider them only if the triage nurse/clinician approves.\n\nSafety net \u2014 tell staff immediately or call for help if you develop any of:\n- New weakness or numbness, slurred speech, difficulty seeing, fainting, seizure, sudden \u201cworst\u2011ever\u201d headache, or fever with neck stiffness.\n\nAfter imaging or evaluation\n- If you have the CT report or discharge notes, snap a photo or copy the text and I can help interpret it and advise next steps (MRI, neurology follow\u2011up, preventive therapy).  \n\nI\u2019ll be here if you want me to help word anything to the ED staff or to review results when you get them. Wishing you rapid assessment and relief \u2014 please update me when you can."
