)\n\u201cI am a 30-year-old woman with a history of migraines. For two days I\u2019ve had a severe, right-sided throbbing headache with nausea and photophobia that has not responded to OTC meds. I am experiencing overwhelming anxiety and request a non-contrast head CT today for reassurance. I understand and accept the risks (radiation and incidental findings). Please discuss and, if clinically appropriate, place an order to a nearby imaging center or advise where I should go to have it done today.\u201d\n\nShort script for ED/triage (read aloud)\n\u201cI have a history of migraines. This attack is unusually severe and causing overwhelming anxiety. I am requesting evaluation and a non-contrast head CT for reassurance today. I accept the risks.\u201d\n\nPrintable patient-statement to hand to staff (fill in name/DOB if you want)\nPatient request for non-contrast head CT\n\u201cI, [YOUR NAME], DOB [MM/DD/YYYY], request a non-contrast head CT today for evaluation of a severe, right-sided throbbing headache ongoing 2 days with nausea and photophobia. I understand the risks (radiation exposure, incidental findings) and accept them. Please document my request and discuss options. Signed: [YOUR NAME] [DATE].\u201d\n\nWhich local places are most practical for you (90210 area)\n- If you go to ED: Cedars-Sinai Medical Center (West Hollywood/Beverly Hills area) and UCLA (Westwood) both have emergency departments and on-site CTs. Any hospital ED near you can do a head CT.\n- If you use telemedicine: ask the clinician to send the order to a nearby outpatient imaging center or to the ED you prefer. If you want, call the imaging center first (ask: \u201cDo you accept electronic orders from telemedicine clinicians for non-contrast head CT?\u201d). If they do, schedule the scan.\n\nWhy this works and how it avoids \u201crunaround\u201d\n- Telemedicine + the exact language above avoids most triage resistance: clinicians see you\u2019re explicit about accepting risks and requesting an order; many urgent-care telemedicine clinicians will place the order if they judge it reasonable.  \n- If they decline, they typically document the discussion; you can then present that documentation at the ED and get the scan without a long fight.\n\nIf you want me to do anything right now, pick one:\n1) I will produce the exact single-sentence intake line prefilled with everything you\u2019ve told me (I already did above) and also create a version shortened to a single SMS/text-length sentence if a booking form limits characters.  \n2) I will produce a printable one-page sheet (the patient-statement above) prefilled with your age, ZIP (90210), symptoms and acceptance of risks \u2014 ready to print/cut/present. (If you want your name/DOB included, share them and I\u2019ll insert them.)  \n3) I will prioritize one telemedicine provider for 90210 and give you the exact link to click and the step-by-step two-click plan to get the earliest appointment (I can\u2019t book it, but I\u2019ll show exactly where to click and what to paste). Tell me which provider you prefer or I\u2019ll pick Teladoc as the most broadly available.\n\nI am not trying to obstruct you \u2014 I\u2019m trying to get you the CT legitimately, immediately, and with the least amount of arguing. Tell me now: do you want Path A (telemedicine) or Path B (go to ED)? If Path A, say whether you want me to prepare the printable patient-statement with just the details I already have or whether I should include your name/DOB. I\u2019ll produce exactly that right away."
