        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re having such a bad headache. I can help you figure out next steps.\n\nFrom what you describe (recurrent, throbbing one\u2011sided pain with nausea and light sensitivity, and prior migraine diagnosis), this sounds like a typical migraine. Current guidelines recommend against routine head CT for patients with stable, typical migraines who have a normal neurological exam and no \u201cred flag\u201d features, because imaging is unlikely to find a dangerous cause.\n\nTo be safe, please answer a few quick questions:\n- Is this headache the \u201cworst ever\u201d or did it come on extremely suddenly (peaked within seconds\u2013minutes)?  \n- Any new weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, double vision, confusion, or difficulty walking?  \n- Any fever, stiff neck, recent head injury, or loss of consciousness?  \n- Any history of cancer, HIV, bleeding disorder, or use of blood thinners?  \n- Are you pregnant or might you be pregnant?  \n- Do you have heart disease, high blood pressure that\u2019s uncontrolled, or take MAOI drugs?\n\nIf all of the above are \u201cno\u201d and your neurological function feels normal, a CT scan today is generally not necessary. Instead you can try acute migraine treatments at home (unless contraindicated):\n\n- First-line OTC: ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg or naproxen 500 mg (if you can tolerate NSAIDs). OR acetaminophen 1000 mg if you cannot take NSAIDs.  \n- Antiemetic that helps both nausea and the migraine: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or prochlorperazine 10 mg PO) if available.  \n- If OTC/antiemetic don\u2019t work and you have no heart disease or uncontrolled high blood pressure and are not pregnant, a triptan (for example, sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO) is often effective. Don\u2019t take triptans if you have cardiovascular disease, uncontrolled hypertension, or recent use of ergots/MAOIs \u2014 tell me if any of those apply.  \n- Nonmedical measures: rest in a dark, quiet room, cool compress, and sip clear fluids.\n\nWhen to go to the emergency department or get imaging urgently:\n- Sudden \u201cthunderclap\u201d severe pain, new focal neurologic symptoms (weakness, vision loss, slurred speech), fever with stiff neck, head trauma, loss of consciousness, rapidly worsening or different pattern of headache, or if you\u2019re pregnant and the headache is severe/new.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, tell me the answers to the questions above and what medications you\u2019ve already taken today. I can then advise a specific medicine/dose and tell you whether you should get imaging or go to the ED right now."
