        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand \u2014 that worry can feel overwhelming. Going to the ED is a reasonable way to get same\u2011day imaging and rapid reassurance. Below are short, truthful phrases you can use at triage and with the ED clinician, plus practical tips on what to expect.\n\nWhat to say at triage (short version)\n- \u201cI have a severe headache that\u2019s different from my usual migraines, started 2 days ago, is not responding to my usual medicines, and I\u2019m very concerned. I\u2019d like to be evaluated in the ED and request a head CT today for reassurance.\u201d\n\nIf the triage nurse asks for more detail (one\u2011sentence additions)\n- \u201cIt\u2019s a throbbing right\u2011sided pain with nausea and light sensitivity; I have a history of migraine but this pain feels different and is persistent despite OTC meds.\u201d\n- \u201cI don\u2019t have fever, weakness, vision change, or recent head injury, and I\u2019m not pregnant.\u201d\n\nWhat to say to the ED clinician/provider\n- \u201cThank you for evaluating me. I have a known history of migraines, but this headache is different from my usual attacks, is severe, and hasn\u2019t responded to OTC treatment. I\u2019m anxious that something serious could be missed and would like a head CT today for reassurance. Could you please consider a noncontrast head CT as part of the workup?\u201d\n- If they recommend treatment first: \u201cI understand \u2014 I\u2019m happy to try IV meds or an antiemetic while you reassess, but I\u2019d still like imaging if you remain concerned.\u201d\n\nIf imaging is declined and you still want it\n- Ask the clinician to explain the decision and to document your concern in the chart. You can say: \u201cI understand your clinical judgment \u2014 can you please document my persistent symptoms and my request for imaging? If my symptoms don\u2019t improve or change, I will return.\u201d\n\nPractical tips to bring and say\n- Bring a photo ID, list of current meds/allergies, and any records or prior imaging reports if you have them.  \n- Women of childbearing potential should be prepared for a rapid pregnancy test before CT.  \n- Be calm and concise; triage assigns acuity based on severity and instability, so emphasize persistent severe pain, failure of home meds, and that it\u2019s different from prior attacks.\n\nWhat to expect in the ED\n- Triage \u2192 clinician assessment \u2192 pain/antiemetic meds. If indicated, a noncontrast CT head is typically ordered first to evaluate for acute hemorrhage or other urgent findings. If imaging is not indicated, ED may offer IV migraine therapies and outpatient follow\u2011up.  \n- If you develop new neurologic symptoms (weakness, numbness, trouble speaking/seeing, sudden severe \u201cworst-ever\u201d pain), call 911 or tell staff immediately.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can write a short text you can copy/paste into your phone for triage. Do you want that?"
