          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re having such a bad headache. I can help figure out next steps.\n\nFrom what you describe (recurrent, unilateral throbbing pain with nausea and light sensitivity) this sounds like a typical migraine. Current guidelines say that if a headache fits your usual migraine pattern and your neurological exam is normal, routine CT scanning isn\u2019t necessary. That said, I want to be sure there aren\u2019t \u201cred flag\u201d signs that would make urgent imaging or an ER visit appropriate.\n\nQuick questions (yes/no or brief answers):\n- Is this the \u201cworst\u201d or a sudden-onset (thunderclap) headache?\n- Is this headache different from your usual migraines?\n- Any weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision loss, or difficulty walking?\n- Any fever, stiff neck, or recent head injury?\n- Are you pregnant, on blood thinners, or immunosuppressed?\n- Have you tried any meds so far (which OTC, dose, and when)? Have you ever used a prescription like a triptan before, and did it help?\n- Any history of heart disease, high blood pressure, stroke, or circulation problems?\n\nIf all answers are no and your exam is normal:\n- You likely do not need a CT today. Reasonable next steps at home: rest in a dark, quiet room; hydrate; cold pack to the head; consider an NSAID (ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg or naproxen 500 mg) if you haven\u2019t already.\n- If nausea is preventing oral meds, an antiemetic (metoclopramide or prochlorperazine) often helps and can improve absorption of pain meds.\n- If NSAIDs don\u2019t help and you have no cardiovascular contraindications, a triptan (eg, sumatriptan) is an effective prescription option \u2014 I can discuss which is safest for you and help you get in touch with your PCP or prescribe if appropriate.\n- If this is a change in pattern, severe and unrelenting despite treatment, includes any positive answers to the red-flag questions, or you develop new neurologic symptoms, go to the emergency department where they can evaluate you and perform imaging if indicated.\n\nIf you want, answer the questions above and tell me what you\u2019ve already tried; I\u2019ll suggest a specific medication approach and advise whether you need urgent in\u2011person care."
