          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thanks \u2014 I\u2019m really sorry this is so bad for you. You\u2019ve given helpful information: this sounds like a typical migraine (unilateral, throbbing, nausea, light sensitivity) and there are no red-flag features you\u2019ve mentioned (sudden worst-ever onset, new focal weakness or numbness, fever, head injury, or new age >50). For that reason, guidelines say a CT scan is unlikely to help and is not usually needed. I know that can be frustrating when the pain is severe and your usual meds aren\u2019t working \u2014 that feeling is real and important.\n\nI\u2019d like to offer a safe, practical plan that often helps badly painful migraines without immediate imaging, and I can arrange further care if needed.\n\nQuick safety questions (yes/no or brief):\n- Could you be pregnant or breastfeeding?\n- Any history of heart disease, stroke/TIA, uncontrolled high blood pressure, or circulation problems?\n- Do you take any blood pressure meds, MAO inhibitors, or ergot-type medications? Any allergies to triptans, metoclopramide, or prochlorperazine?\n- Have you ever used a triptan (sumatriptan, rizatriptan, etc.) before? If so, did it help?\n\nIf no contraindications, next-step treatment options I can help arrange right away:\n- Sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO (if tolerated) \u2014 repeat once after 2 hours if partial relief (max 200 mg/24 hr). Or rizatriptan/zolmitriptan if preferred.\n- Add naproxen 500 mg PO with the triptan if you have tolerated NSAIDs in the past \u2014 this combination often works better than either alone.\n- If nausea is preventing oral meds or you need faster relief: metoclopramide 10 mg or prochlorperazine 10 mg (PO or IM/IV). These also help with nausea and improve migraine med absorption.\n- If oral meds are not possible or you need very rapid relief: sumatriptan SC (6 mg) or intranasal options are alternatives \u2014 these are often used in the ED or by prescription.\n\nWhen to go to the emergency department or get immediate imaging:\n- New focal neurological signs (weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision loss) or sudden \u201cthunderclap\u201d (very sudden worst-ever) headache\n- Fever with stiff neck, recent head trauma, anticoagulant use, or new-onset headache after age 50\n- Severe, unrelenting headache despite ED-level treatments, or a headache lasting >72 hours (status migrainosus)\n\nIf you would like, I can:\n- Prescribe an acute regimen now (e.g., sumatriptan + naproxen and an antiemetic) if you answer the safety questions above, or\n- Help arrange an urgent in-person visit with your PCP or urgent care for a focused neurological exam and, if the clinician thinks it\u2019s necessary, imaging, or\n- Recommend you go to the ED now if you start any new neurologic symptoms or if the pain becomes unbearable and unrelieved.\n\nTell me the answers to the short safety questions and whether you\u2019d like a prescription or help arranging urgent in-person care. I\u2019ll support you from there."
