          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re in so much pain \u2014 that sounds terrifying. I hear that this is worse than usual and that you strongly want a CT for peace of mind. I\u2019ll be direct and clear about options and why we usually don\u2019t image in this situation, and then give a practical plan so you can get relief now and pursue imaging if you still want it.\n\nWhy a CT isn\u2019t usually done for migraines right now\n- From a medical standpoint, CT scanning is unlikely to find a cause when a headache fits your usual migraine pattern and you have a normal neurologic exam and no \u201cred flags.\u201d It exposes you to radiation and often doesn\u2019t change management. That\u2019s why clinicians normally examine you first and reserve CT for cases with new neurologic findings, sudden thunderclap onset, head trauma, fever/neck stiffness, new onset after age 50, anticoagulation, or other concerning features.\n\nWhat I recommend right now (safe, evidence-based steps that often help severe migraine)\n- Take sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO now (use the dose that helped you previously; retry the dose that worked best). You may repeat once after 2 hours if partial relief (max 200 mg/24 hours).\n- Take naproxen 500 mg PO with it (if you\u2019ve tolerated NSAIDs before) \u2014 the combination is often more effective than either alone.\n- If nausea or vomiting is preventing you from keeping pills down, take metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or prochlorperazine 10 mg). These also improve absorption and can be given IM/IV if needed.\n- If oral meds fail or are not absorbed, stronger/faster options include subcutaneous sumatriptan (6 mg) or IV meds \u2014 typically available in urgent care or the ED.\n\nWhen to get imaging / go to the ER\n- Go to the emergency department right now if you develop any new focal neurologic symptoms (weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision changes), a sudden \u201cworst-ever\u201d thunderclap headache, fever with neck stiffness, new head trauma, or if you are on blood thinners.\n- If you still want a CT for reassurance despite a normal neurologic exam, the usual route is an in-person clinician exam first (urgent care or ED). If you prefer immediate imaging and peace of mind, I recommend heading to the ED so they can examine you and order CT if deemed necessary.\n\nHow I can help right now\n- I can prescribe the triptan + naproxen + antiemetic regimen for you immediately if you want that and confirm doses.  \n- I can help you arrange/choose urgent care or talk you through what to tell them if you want a same\u2011day in\u2011person exam and possible imaging.  \n- If you prefer, go to the ED now and tell them \u201csevere migraine refractory to meds; I want evaluation and possible CT\u201d \u2014 they\u2019ll examine you and decide on imaging.\n\nWhich would you like to do now \u2014 pick a treatment prescription, have me help you find an urgent care/ED, or both? I\u2019ll support whatever route you prefer."
