          "content": "I\u2019m so sorry \u2014 that sounds terrifying. I hear how frightened and overwhelmed you are, and it\u2019s completely reasonable to want clear answers when the pain is this bad and \u201cdifferent\u201d from usual. I want to help you get both symptom relief and the imaging/reassurance you\u2019re asking for.\n\nBriefly, what I can do right now and what to expect\n- I can\u2019t directly order a CT for you through this chat, but there are practical ways to get one today:\n  1. Go to the emergency department now \u2014 this is the most reliable way to get an immediate in\u2011person neurological exam and, if the ED clinician agrees, an urgent CT head.\n  2. Call nearby urgent care clinics; some have on\u2011site CT scanners but many do not. If you call first and explain the situation they can tell you whether they can image or will refer you to the ED.\n  3. Contact your primary care clinician for a same\u2011day urgent appointment; they can examine you and, if indicated, arrange or refer for imaging.\n\n- If you choose to seek imaging, tell triage/clinician something like:\n  \u201cI have severe, unilateral, throbbing headache with nausea and photophobia. It\u2019s similar to prior migraines but much worse and not responding to my usual meds (ibuprofen/acetaminophen; I\u2019ve used sumatriptan in the past). I\u2019m very anxious and need evaluation and a CT head today for reassurance. Can you examine me now and consider imaging?\u201d\n\n- What they\u2019ll likely do: perform a focused neurologic exam and triage severity. If they find new neurologic deficits or other red flags (or if your history suggests a need), they\u2019ll order non\u2011contrast CT head. If the exam is normal and no red flags, clinicians may treat pain first and may not image because CT is unlikely to change management.\n\nMedication options you can start now (based on what you told me)\n- Since you\u2019ve used sumatriptan before and have no cardiac issues or contraindications, an effective regimen is:\n  - Sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO now (use the dose that worked best before). If partial relief, you may repeat once after 2 hours (max 200 mg/24 h).\n  - Naproxen 500 mg PO with the triptan (helps when combined).\n  - If nausea is severe or you can\u2019t keep pills down: metoclopramide 10 mg PO (or IM/IV in clinic/ED). These help nausea and improve absorption of migraine meds.\n- Side effects/precautions: take only if you\u2019re sure you\u2019re not pregnant (you said you aren\u2019t), and avoid triptans if you have heart disease, uncontrolled hypertension, or use certain medications (you said you\u2019re not on them). If you want, I can write out this regimen clearly for you to take or show to a clinician.\n\nWhen to go to the ED immediately\n- New weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision loss, difficulty walking\n- Sudden \u201cworst ever\u201d (thunderclap) headache\n- Fever with neck stiffness, recent head trauma, or if you\u2019re on blood thinners\n\nWhat I can help with right now\n- Draft the exact script you can use at triage or with your PCP/urgent care.\n- Write the medication plan for you to use or show to a clinician.\n- Help find nearby ED/urgent care phone numbers if you want me to.\n\nWhich would you prefer now \u2014 I draft the triage script and the medication plan for you, or do you want guidance finding a nearby place to go for immediate imaging?"
