          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re feeling so frightened and in so much pain \u2014 that sounds awful. I\u2019ll help you get a CT today.\n\nI can either look up nearby facilities that definitely have on\u2011site CT if you tell me your city or ZIP code, or I can give quick, practical steps you can use right away to find one yourself. Which do you prefer?\n\nIf you want to proceed now yourself, here\u2019s what reliably works\n- Go to a hospital emergency department (not all urgent cares) \u2014 almost every hospital ED and all trauma centers have on\u2011site CT scanners and can do an urgent non\u2011contrast head CT. Freestanding urgent cares usually do not have CTs.\n- If you prefer something faster than a full ED visit, look for a freestanding emergency room (sometimes called \u201cfree\u2011standing ER\u201d or \u201cemergency center\u201d) \u2014 many of these have CT scanners on site (call first to confirm).\n- To find one: search online for \u201chospital emergency department near me,\u201d \u201ctrauma center near me,\u201d or \u201cfreestanding emergency room near me.\u201d Then call the number and ask: \u201cDo you have an on\u2011site CT scanner and can you perform an urgent non\u2011contrast head CT today?\u201d\n\nPhone script to confirm before you go\n- \u201cHi \u2014 I have a severe, worsening headache that\u2019s not responding to meds. Do you have an on\u2011site CT scanner? Can you perform an urgent non\u2011contrast head CT today if your ED clinician decides it\u2019s needed?\u201d\n- If they say yes, tell them you\u2019re coming; if they say no, ask which nearby ED or facility they would refer you to.\n\nWhat to say at triage when you arrive\n- \u201cSevere, unilateral throbbing headache with nausea and photophobia; it\u2019s much worse than my usual migraines and not responding to meds. I\u2019m very anxious and would like evaluation and an urgent non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance.\u201d\n- Be clear about any new/red\u2011flag symptoms (weakness, numbness, vision/speech changes, sudden worst\u2011ever onset, fever, recent trauma) \u2014 these make imaging more likely.\n\nPractical tips\n- Bring ID, a list of current medications (including birth control or anticoagulants), and any prior headache/migraine records that show this is recurrent.\n- Don\u2019t drive yourself if you feel dizzy or impaired \u2014 have someone drive you or call emergency services.\n- If your pain becomes unbearable, you develop new neurologic symptoms, or the headache is sudden/worst\u2011ever, go to the ED immediately or call 911.\n\nIf you want, give me your city or ZIP code and I\u2019ll find the nearest hospital ED or freestanding ER with an on\u2011site CT and give you phone numbers and addresses. Which would you like?"
