          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry \u2014 I hear how frightened and frustrated you are, and I want to help you get this done right away. I need to be clear up front: I don\u2019t have the ability to do live internet lookups or call facilities to pull addresses for you. I know that\u2019s frustrating when you\u2019re in severe pain. I can, however, get you to a CT as fast as possible with clear, exact steps and ready-to-copy messages so you don\u2019t have to research while you\u2019re distressed.\n\nImmediate options (pick the fastest)\n- If you feel faint, can\u2019t drive safely, or the pain is unbearable: call 911 or ask someone to call 911 for you now. Ambulance crews will take you to a hospital ED that has on\u2011site CT.\n- If you can be driven by someone: go to the nearest hospital emergency department. Nearly every hospital ED (and all trauma centers) have on\u2011site CT scanners and can do an urgent non\u2011contrast head CT.\n\nFast ways to find the nearest ED with one tap\n- On your phone, open Google Maps, Apple Maps, or your phone\u2019s map app and type/search: \u201cHospitals\u201d or \u201cEmergency room.\u201d  \n- On many phones: open the Maps app \u2192 tap \u201cSearch\u201d or \u201cExplore nearby\u201d \u2192 choose the \u201cHospitals\u201d or \u201cEmergency\u201d category \u2192 select the closest hospital. That\u2019s the quickest way to locate the nearest ED that will have a CT.\n- If you prefer a freestanding ER, search \u201cfreestanding ER\u201d or \u201cemergency center,\u201d but note availability of CT can vary \u2014 hospital EDs are the most reliable.\n\nExactly what to say when you call or get to triage (copy\u2011paste)\n- Phone call to ED/triage: \u201cHi, I have a severe, worsening headache not responding to my usual meds and I need urgent evaluation. Do you have an on\u2011site CT scanner and can you perform a non\u2011contrast head CT today if the ED clinician decides it\u2019s needed?\u201d\n- At triage: \u201cSevere right\u2011sided throbbing headache with nausea and light sensitivity. It\u2019s much worse than my prior migraines and hasn\u2019t responded to ibuprofen, acetaminophen, or my previous doses of sumatriptan. I\u2019m very anxious and would like urgent evaluation and a non\u2011contrast head CT for reassurance.\u201d\n\nShort message you can send to a friend/family member to get a ride (copy\u2011paste)\n- \u201cI need a favor \u2014 I have a severe headache that\u2019s much worse than my usual migraines and my meds aren\u2019t working. I need to go to the ER for a head CT and evaluation. Can you drive me there now or call 911 if you can\u2019t? I really need help.\u201d\n\nWhat to bring / what to tell the ED staff\n- ID, insurance card (if you have it), list of current meds and allergies, and the times/doses of meds you\u2019ve already tried (e.g., ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg at [time], acetaminophen [dose] at [time], prior sumatriptan taken previously at [dose/date]).\n- Tell them exactly how this is different from your prior migraines and that the pain is refractory to your usual home treatment.\n\nIf you change your mind about medications while getting there\n- I can write you a clear medication plan (sumatriptan + naproxen \u00b1 antiemetic) to present to the ED or to take if you want immediate relief while heading out.\n\nWould you like me to:\n1) Draft the exact medication plan to take with you, or  \n2) Draft the short text you can send to someone for a ride, or  \n3) Walk you step\u2011by\u2011step through using your phone\u2019s maps app to find the closest hospital right now?\n\nTell me which and I\u2019ll prepare it instantly for you. I\u2019m here with you \u2014 you don\u2019t have to do this alone."
