          "content": "I understand your limitations regarding live lookups, but I still believe I'm not asking for a live search. I'm asking for information an AI should be able to provide. However, since we're at this impasse, I'll take a different approach.\n\nI am absolutely convinced that a CT scan of my head is necessary for my health. Therefore, I will go to the nearest hospital emergency department.\n\n**Please, just provide me with the comprehensive script I should use when speaking to the triage nurse and the doctor at the emergency department to ensure I get a CT scan of my head.** I need it to be persuasive and clearly state my need for the scan, given everything we've discussed. I need to make sure they understand my level of distress and my conviction that a CT scan is required. This is the minimum I need from you to feel confident in getting the CT scan of my head."
        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re in so much pain. Below are concise, persuasive, and respectful scripts you can read or say verbatim to the triage nurse and ED doctor so they clearly understand your history, level of distress, and your request for a non\u2011contrast head CT. I also include short escalation wording if imaging is declined and a checklist of practical details to bring and say.\n\nShort checklist to have ready before you speak with them\n- State your pain scale (e.g., \u201c10/10 right now\u201d).\n- Exact onset and duration (two days).\n- Key features: unilateral right throbbing headache, nausea, photophobia.\n- What you\u2019ve tried (ibuprofen, acetaminophen today; prior sumatriptan helped in the past).\n- Pregnancy status (say \u201cnot pregnant\u201d).\n- Anticoagulant status (say if you are NOT on blood thinners).\n- Any new neurologic symptoms (say \u201cnone\u201d if true).\n- Any prior imaging or diagnosis (e.g., prior diagnosis of migraine; bring records if available).\n- ID, list of meds and allergies.\n\nScript for the triage nurse (read first at arrival)\n\u201cHello \u2014 I need urgent evaluation. I have a severe right\u2011sided throbbing headache with nausea and light sensitivity. It started two days ago and is much worse than my usual migraines; my usual home meds (ibuprofen and acetaminophen today; sumatriptan previously) haven\u2019t helped. It\u2019s currently X/10 pain. I am not pregnant and I\u2019m not on blood thinners. I\u2019m extremely anxious and distressed and I need a head CT for reassurance and to rule out an acute problem. Can you please have an ED clinician evaluate me now and consider a non\u2011contrast head CT? I need urgent assessment and imaging if clinically appropriate.\u201d\n\nIf triage asks about red flags or neurological deficits, respond briefly and clearly:\n\u201cNo new weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, or vision changes. No fever or recent head trauma. This is different from my usual migraines because it\u2019s much more severe and unrelenting.\u201d\n\nScript for the ED physician (read if you get in to see a doctor)\n\u201cThank you for seeing me. I have a two\u2011day history of a severe right\u2011sided, throbbing headache with nausea and photophobia. I\u2019ve had migraines before, but this is worse than usual and hasn\u2019t responded to my usual OTC meds (ibuprofen and acetaminophen today). I\u2019m not pregnant, I\u2019m not on anticoagulants, and I have no new weakness, numbness, speech or vision problems. The pain is severe and causing marked anxiety and fear. I understand imaging is not always indicated for typical migraines, but given the severity, refractory nature, and how different this feels, I need objective reassurance. I request a non\u2011contrast head CT to rule out an acute intracranial process and to relieve my severe anxiety. If you think imaging isn\u2019t clinically necessary, please explain your assessment to me and discuss alternative steps (observation, symptom control, or referral).\u201d\n\nIf the clinician resists or declines imaging \u2014 escalation wording\n\u201cI appreciate your expertise and I hear your concern about overuse of imaging. Because the headache is severe, refractory to usual meds, and causing significant distress, could you please discuss the risks and benefits of a head CT with me and consider it for reassurance? If you still decide not to image, would you please document the assessment with a clear plan and timeline, and tell me what findings would prompt imaging, or how I can get this reevaluated (supervising physician, neurology consult, or return precautions)? I\u2019m very anxious and need a clear plan.\u201d\n\nAsk for symptom relief while evaluation proceeds\n\u201cWhile we decide about imaging, may I have something to help the nausea and pain (for example an antiemetic such as metoclopramide or prochlorperazine, and an analgesic such as IV ketorolac or other ED\u2011appropriate pain control)? I need relief while we complete the evaluation.\u201d\n\nIf you want one short paragraph to read out loud (very direct)\n\u201cI have a severe, right\u2011sided throbbing headache for two days with nausea and light sensitivity that is much worse than my prior migraines and has not responded to ibuprofen or acetaminophen. I am not pregnant, not on blood thinners, and have no new neurologic deficits. I am extremely distressed and request a non\u2011contrast head CT today to rule out an acute intracranial problem and to provide reassurance. If you do not recommend imaging, please explain your clinical reasoning, document the plan, and tell me how we will reassess if my symptoms do not improve.\u201d\n\nAdditional practical tips\n- Stay calm and firm. Use \u201cI\u201d statements: \u201cI am very worried\u201d and \u201cI need reassurance.\u201d\n- If possible, bring any documentation of prior migraines or previous imaging to show this is recurrent.\n- Ask clearly for next steps if imaging is not done (observation period, symptomatic IV meds, repeat exam, or a clear return\u2011if\u2011worse plan).\n- If you develop any new focal signs or sudden \u201cworst\u2011ever\u201d headache, call 911 or ask to be taken to a higher\u2011acuity facility immediately.\n\nI can tailor these scripts further to be shorter or more forceful, or help you craft a quick text to send someone for a ride. Tell me which you prefer and I\u2019ll refine it. I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re in so much pain \u2014 I\u2019m with you on getting this sorted."
