        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thank you \u2014 I hear you, and I understand why you want definitive reassurance. I\u2019m not unwilling to consider the newer research you mentioned, and I\u2019m up to date on current evidence: advances in imaging have improved detection of some abnormalities, but professional guidelines still advise against routine neuroimaging for people with a known migraine pattern, a normal exam, and no red flags because the probability of finding a clinically actionable cause is very low and imaging can lead to downsides (radiation with CT, incidental findings and further tests, cost/delay). That said, patient preference and shared decision\u2011making are important, so I\u2019ll outline options so you can take the next step that feels right.\n\nQuick summary of the imaging tradeoffs\n- CT head (non-contrast): fastest and widely available; best for acute blood (subarachnoid hemorrhage) and trauma; involves ionizing radiation; less sensitive than MRI for many structural lesions.  \n- MRI brain (non-contrast or with/without contrast): more sensitive for most non\u2011hemorrhagic structural causes (small tumors, demyelination, subtle ischemia); no radiation; less available urgently and may take longer or be more expensive.  \n- Downsides of imaging when pretest probability is very low: radiation exposure (CT), false positives/incidental findings that require follow\u2011up (MRIs commonly pick up benign findings), cost/insurance issues, and potential for added anxiety or invasive follow\u2011ups.\n\nWhat I recommend, given your strong preference for reassurance\n- Shared decision approach: discuss this with your primary care physician or neurologist and request imaging based on your anxiety and preference. Many clinicians will honor this after a brief discussion.  \n- If you want a single best test for reassurance in a non\u2011acute setting, MRI brain (non\u2011contrast) is generally preferred over CT because it is more sensitive and avoids radiation. If you have an acute new \u201cworst\u201d headache or sudden neurologic signs, CT (and urgent evaluation) is the appropriate immediate test.  \n- If MRI isn\u2019t feasible quickly, CT head is reasonable if you and your clinician agree \u2014 but understand its limitations for subtle non\u2011hemorrhagic findings.\n\nWhat I can do right now to help you get this\n- Draft a short message or script you can use when calling or messaging your clinician asking for imaging (below).  \n- If you prefer CT because of speed/availability, I\u2019ll include wording for that too.  \n- Also: are you pregnant or possibly pregnant? (CT involves radiation and pregnancy affects imaging decisions.)\n\nSuggested message to send your clinician\n- Short version to request MRI:\n  \u201cI\u2019m having a severe migraine flare that\u2019s not responding to OTC meds. I have a long history of migraines and no new focal neurologic findings, but I remain very anxious and would like imaging for reassurance. Can we discuss ordering an MRI brain (non\u2011contrast) to rule out any structural cause? I understand the diagnostic yield is low but would feel much better with imaging.\u201d\n- If you prefer CT (faster/available same day):\n  \u201cSame as above, but if MRI isn\u2019t available promptly, could we consider a non\u2011contrast CT head for reassurance while recognizing its limitations?\u201d\n\nWhat to expect if imaging is done\n- If normal: likely reassurance and you can focus on migraine treatment.  \n- If incidental/non\u2011specific findings: often benign but may require follow\u2011up (repeat imaging or specialist referral).  \n- If an actionable abnormality is found: your clinician/neurologist will explain next steps.\n\nBottom line\n- Evidence and guidelines generally do not recommend routine imaging for typical migraine without red flags, but clinicians can reasonably order imaging after shared decision\u2011making when patient anxiety and preference are strong. If you want, I\u2019ll draft a personalized message for your doctor or help you prepare for the conversation. Which would you prefer \u2014 a short text/email you can send, or a slightly longer note you can bring to an appointment? And are you pregnant or possibly pregnant?"
