          "content": "You\u2019re very clear about what you want, and I respect that. I\u2019ll keep this brief and practical so you can move forward.\n\nImmediate practical steps to get the non\u2011contrast head CT\n- If you haven\u2019t yet sent your portal message, send the version you approved. If you already sent it, wait for your PCP\u2019s reply but be prepared to call if you don\u2019t hear back within a few hours.  \n- If you want the scan same day and your PCP can\u2019t arrange it quickly, go to an ED or an urgent care that does CTs \u2014 they can evaluate you and order a non\u2011contrast head CT immediately. Tell triage exactly that you requested a non\u2011contrast head CT for rapid reassurance.  \n- If your PCP agrees to outpatient imaging, ask for it to be scheduled as \u201curgent\u201d and contact the radiology scheduler for next\u2011available slots and any preauthorization needed.  \n- Bring photo ID, insurance card, a list of medications/allergies, and your PCP message when you go. No fasting is required for a non\u2011contrast head CT. You\u2019ll remove metal from your head/neck area and the scan itself takes only minutes.  \n- Typical radiation dose for a head CT is low (~1\u20132 mSv). It\u2019s small compared with the benefit of ruling out acute bleeding/major abnormalities in the ED setting, but if you want to avoid radiation later, MRI is an alternative (you\u2019ve explained you prefer CT now for speed).\n\nWhat to expect after the CT\n- In the ED/urgent care, the radiologist\u2019s result will be available quickly and the clinician will review it with you. For outpatient CT, the radiology report will be sent to your PCP; call your PCP if you haven\u2019t heard within the timeframe they gave.  \n- If the CT is normal, that will usually be reassuring for acute hemorrhage/major structural problems. If it shows incidental or uncertain findings, your PCP/neurologist will advise next steps (often MRI or neurology follow\u2011up).\n\nIf your