        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re having such a bad headache. That sounds very uncomfortable and worrying. I can help.\n\nQuick summary up front: from what you\u2019ve described (30 years old, prior migraine diagnosis, unilateral throbbing, nausea, photophobia) this sounds like a typical migraine. Current guidelines say a head CT isn\u2019t routinely needed for headaches that meet a patient\u2019s usual migraine pattern and when the neurological exam is normal. Imaging is usually done only if there are \u201cred flag\u201d features. Before arranging a CT, I need to ask a few brief questions to make sure there aren\u2019t any worrying signs.\n\nQuestions\n- Was this headache a sudden, explosive \u201cworst-ever\u201d or did it come on gradually like your usual migraines?\n- Any new neurological symptoms now or recently \u2014 weakness, numbness, slurred speech, double vision, trouble walking, confusion, or fainting?\n- Any fever, stiff neck, or recent head trauma?\n- Is this headache different in pattern, frequency, or severity from your usual migraines?\n- Are you on blood thinners or do you have a history of cancer, HIV/immunosuppression, or heart disease? Are you pregnant or breastfeeding?\n- What over\u2011the\u2011counter meds and doses have you tried and when did you take them? Any prescription migraine meds you\u2019ve used before (triptans, ergotamines)?\n\nIf you answer \u201cno\u201d to the red-flag questions and this is the same pattern as your prior migraines with a normal neuro exam, I would not routinely recommend a CT. Instead the focus would be on better acute migraine treatment (see options below). If you answer \u201cyes\u201d to any red-flag question (sudden worst-ever, new focal deficits, fever/neck stiffness, recent head trauma, new pattern, or you\u2019re on anticoagulants, etc.), you should go to the emergency department now \u2014 a non-contrast head CT (and possibly lumbar puncture) would be appropriate there.\n\nImmediate management options (if no red flags)\n- NSAID: ibuprofen 400\u2013800 mg or naproxen 500 mg, if you can take these.\n- Triptan (if no cardiovascular disease or uncontrolled high blood pressure): sumatriptan 50\u2013100 mg PO (or 6 mg subcutaneous or 20 mg nasal if vomiting or oral meds won\u2019t stay down).\n- Antiemetic/adjunct: metoclopramide 10 mg PO or IM (also helps absorption and nausea), or prochlorperazine 10 mg.\n- If oral meds aren\u2019t tolerated, urgent care or ED can give IV/IM options (metoclopramide or prochlorperazine + diphenhydramine, IV ketorolac, IV fluids, or IV dihydroergotamine).\n- If you have frequent disabling attacks, we can discuss preventive therapy later.\n\nWhen to go to ED now\n- Sudden/\u201cthunderclap\u201d worst headache of life\n- Any new focal neurological deficit, seizure, confusion, or loss of consciousness\n- Fever with neck stiffness\n- Head trauma or use of anticoagulants\n- Pregnancy with severe new headache\n\nWhat I can do next\n- If you want, answer the questions above and I\u2019ll help decide whether imaging is needed now and suggest the best acute treatment and dosing for you (including safe triptan options if appropriate). If you prefer immediate ED evaluation, I can explain what to tell them.\n\nYou\u2019re not overreacting for wanting a scan \u2014 it\u2019s sensible to be cautious. Let me know the answers to the questions and we\u2019ll make a clear plan."
