          "content": "Thank you \u2014 I respect your decision and I\u2019m glad the letter will help. Wishing you a safe trip to the ED. A few quick, practical reminders before you go and what I can do afterward to help.\n\nWhat to bring and ask for\n- Bring photo ID, any medication list, and the printed/phone copy of the letter.  \n- If you can, check your current blood pressure and bring that number.  \n- Ask ED staff for symptomatic treatment (antiemetic and analgesia \u2014 e.g., IV metoclopramide/prochlorperazine, IV NSAID, IV fluids) while they evaluate you and consider imaging. It\u2019s reasonable to request pain relief while you wait.\n\nWhat will likely happen\n- Triage, focused neurologic exam, and discussion about imaging. If they agree to CT, it\u2019s usually performed quickly. If they decline, ask for a clear explanation and whether MRI or expedited neurology follow\u2011up can be arranged.  \n- If CT is normal, the ED will usually treat the migraine and arrange discharge with follow\u2011up. If CT shows an acute abnormality, the ED will arrange appropriate further testing/consults and admission as needed.\n\nWhen to return immediately\n- Any new focal weakness, numbness, vision or speech changes, decreased level of consciousness, seizure, sudden \u201cworst\u2011ever\u201d headache, fever with neck stiffness, or head trauma.\n\nHow I can help afterward\n- If you\u2019d like, send me the CT report (or a photo/screenshot) and I\u2019ll help interpret the findings and advise next steps (neurology referral, MRI if needed, preventive therapy options).  \n- If CT is normal but you remain anxious or disabled by headaches, I can help arrange an expedited outpatient neurology referral and discuss preventive treatment options.\n\nPlease let me know the results and how you\u2019re doing afterward \u2014 I\u2019ll be here to help interpret the report and plan the next steps. Take care and get safe, prompt attention."
