        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re welcome \u2014 I\u2019m glad that was helpful. I support your decision and want to make this as smooth and safe as possible.\n\nQuick practical checklist for the ED visit\n- Bring: photo ID, insurance card, current medication list (include SSRIs/SNRIs, MAOIs, triptan use, any cardiac meds), any prior imaging reports or discharge summaries if you have them.\n- At triage: use the script you chose and emphasize \u201csevere, different, treatment\u2011refractory right\u2011sided headache x48h; minimal relief from ibuprofen/paracetamol; not pregnant; not on blood thinners; no focal neurologic symptoms.\u201d\n- What to expect: rapid clinical assessment and neurologic exam, non\u2011contrast head CT (quick scan, done to look for acute bleed or large structural cause), IV rescue meds (antiemetic such as metoclopramide or prochlorperazine and IV NSAID or other analgesic). ED stay may take several hours depending on findings and treatments.\n- Possible next steps if CT is negative but concern remains: MRI brain, lumbar puncture (if suspicion for subarachnoid hemorrhage remains and CT is negative), or neurology consult.\n\nSafety reminders\n- If you develop new weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, vision changes, sudden \u201cworst\u2011ever\u201d or thunderclap headache, fever with neck stiffness, confusion, difficulty walking, or a seizure \u2014 go to the ED immediately or call emergency services.\n- If you take your sumatriptan before coming in, tell triage \u2014 also mention any antidepressants (SSRIs/SNRIs) so staff can assess rare serotonin\u2011related interactions.\n\nIf you want, after the CT you can share the report or tell me what the ED team says and I\u2019ll help interpret it and plan follow\u2011up (urgent neurology or outpatient MRI if needed). I hope you get fast relief and clear answers \u2014 please let me know how it goes or if you want me to tailor the message further."
