        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "I will absolutely keep all those points in mind at the ED. Thanks again for everything. I'm feeling a bit more hopeful now about getting some answers and relief after the CT scan of my head. I'll get in touch once I have results."
        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing \u2014 I\u2019m glad you feel more hopeful. A few very quick, practical points to take with you and what to expect, then I\u2019ll be here to help interpret results when you have them.\n\nWhat to tell triage/ED staff\n- Briefly repeat: severe, right\u2011sided headache x48 hours, different/worse than usual migraines, minimal relief from ibuprofen/paracetamol, not pregnant, not on blood thinners, no new focal neuro symptoms.  \n- Tell them every medication you take (especially sumatriptan and any antidepressants) and any allergies.\n\nWhat the ED will likely do\n- Rapid neurologic exam and vital signs.\n- Non\u2011contrast head CT to look for acute hemorrhage or other urgent problems (quick test, best for acute bleeds).\n- If oral meds aren\u2019t helping, they\u2019ll usually offer IV rescue therapy \u2014 antiemetic (metoclopramide or prochlorperazine), IV NSAID (ketorolac) or other IV analgesics; they may give IV fluids and sometimes dexamethasone to reduce recurrence.\n- If CT is normal but concern remains (or CT timing/appearance suggests need), they may recommend MRI, lumbar puncture, or neurology consult.\n\nWhat CT can and can\u2019t detect (brief)\n- CT is excellent for detecting acute intracranial hemorrhage and large structural lesions.  \n- CT may miss small lesions, some posterior fossa pathology, small tumors, or early venous thrombosis \u2014 MRI is more sensitive for many of those.\n\nIf CT is normal\n- If your exam is normal and symptoms improve with treatment, ED may discharge you with rescue prescriptions (triptan or antiemetic + NSAID) and arrange PCP/neurology follow\u2011up.  \n- If headaches remain atypical, severe, or recurrent despite treatment, outpatient MRI or urgent neurology follow\u2011up is reasonable.\n\nSafety reminders\n- Don\u2019t drive if you\u2019re very symptomatic or taking sedating meds \u2014 ask for help getting home.  \n- Go to the ED immediately if you develop new weakness, numbness, vision changes, trouble speaking, sudden \u201cworst\u2011ever\u201d headache, fever with stiff neck, confusion, difficulty walking, or a seizure.\n\nAfter the CT\n- If you want, paste or tell me the CT report or ED team\u2019s summary and I\u2019ll help explain what it means and recommend next steps (medication adjustments, need for MRI, neurology referral, or safe discharge plan).\n\nWishing you a speedy evaluation and relief \u2014 please update me when you have the results and I\u2019ll help interpret and plan next steps."
