        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re welcome \u2014 I\u2019m glad this is helping. Below are the exact, ready-to-use prescription wordings you can give to your PCP, an urgent care clinician, or paste into a portal, plus a short phone script and a list of major local imaging providers in Portland (97205) to contact. I can also help edit any message you want to send to your clinic.\n\nA. Exact prescription wording to give your clinician (copy/paste)\n\n1) Sumatriptan 50 mg tablets\n- Rx: Sumatriptan succinate 50 mg tablet\n- Sig: Take 1 tablet PO at onset of migraine. May repeat one dose after 2 hours if needed. Do not exceed 200 mg in 24 hours.\n- Qty: 6 tablets\n- Indication: Acute migraine headache (patient has prior migraine history; currently severe breakthrough attack).\n- Precautions/notes for prescriber: Confirm no history of ischemic heart disease, uncontrolled hypertension, stroke/TIA, peripheral vascular disease, or concomitant MAOI use; consider blood pressure check prior to dosing if clinically indicated.\n\n2) Metoclopramide 10 mg tablets\n- Rx: Metoclopramide 10 mg tablet\n- Sig: Take 1 tablet PO once for nausea. May repeat every 6\u20138 hours PRN. Do not exceed 40 mg/day.\n- Qty: 12 tablets\n- Indication: Nausea associated with migraine; improves absorption of oral migraine meds.\n- Precautions/notes for prescriber: Warn patient about possible drowsiness/dizziness and rare extrapyramidal reactions; avoid long-term use due to tardive dyskinesia risk. Not for use in Parkinson\u2019s disease.\n\nOptional parenteral wording (if patient unable to tolerate oral or for urgent care/ED use)\n- Metoclopramide 10 mg IM/IV once (may repeat per facility protocol) for acute nausea vomiting associated with migraine.\n\nICD-10 suggestions to include on the order/claim: G43.909 (Migraine, unspecified, not intractable) or R51 (Headache) \u2014 your clinician may choose the most appropriate code.\n\nB. Short phone / portal script to schedule an urgent outpatient CT (copy/paste)\n\"Hello \u2014 this is [Your name / DOB]. I have an urgent order for a non-contrast CT head for severe migraine headache and request a same-day or next-day outpatient appointment if available. Order/indication: Known migraine with 2 days of severe unilateral throbbing headache with nausea and photophobia; patient requests imaging for reassurance (no focal neuro deficits, no fever/trauma, not pregnant). Insurance: Blue Cross Blue Shield. Please advise earliest availability and any insurance/preauthorization requirements.\"\n\nC. Local imaging providers in Portland \u2014 how to use the list\nBelow are major imaging systems and hospital radiology departments in Portland that commonly perform outpatient CT heads. I cannot guarantee in-network status for your specific BCBS plan nor same-day availability; please call your insurer (member services number on your card) or use BCBS provider finder to confirm network status, then call the imaging center to schedule using the script above.\n\nSuggested places to contact (check network/availability):\n- OHSU Imaging Services (Oregon Health & Science University) \u2014 outpatient radiology at OHSU Hospital and satellite sites. (Search OHSU Radiology scheduling or call OHSU main switchboard for routing.)\n- Providence Imaging / Providence Portland Medical Center \u2014 Providence has multiple imaging locations throughout Portland. (Search Providence Imaging Portland scheduling for the nearest outpatient CT slot.)\n- Legacy Health Imaging (Legacy Emanuel Medical Center / Legacy Good Samaritan) \u2014 Legacy operates several imaging centers that often accept BCBS.\n- RadNet / Local outpatient imaging centers (independent imaging groups) \u2014 many outpatient centers offer urgent CT slots; confirm BCBS in-network status.\n- Local urgent care centers that can place an imaging order (e.g., urgent care clinics associated with Providence/Legacy or independent urgent cares) \u2014 they can evaluate and place an order for outpatient CT or, if needed, arrange ED imaging.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can:\n- Draft an exact message to paste into your PCP portal (I already gave a version you said you copied).\n- Draft a short phone script you can use when calling your insurer to confirm which imaging sites are in-network and available today/tomorrow.\n- Callouts: If an outpatient appointment isn't available within a timeframe you want, urgent care clinics often can place an order or provide immediate parenteral antiemetic/analgesic therapy; ED will do immediate CT if new red-flag symptoms appear.\n\nD. Practical notes & safety reminders\n- Bring your insurance card and photo ID to the imaging appointment. Outpatient CT is usually non-contrast for acute headache reassurance.\n- If you start the triptan and experience chest pressure, severe shortness of breath, leg pain, slurred speech, weakness, or any new focal deficit \u2014 go to the ED right away.\n- If your outpatient CT is delayed and you remain very symptomatic, consider urgent care (they can often help quickly) or ED if symptoms worsen.\n\nE. Would you like me to do any of the following now?\n- Draft the exact PCP portal message tailored with your name/DOB and the order text (I can format it).\n- Draft the short phone script for calling BCBS member services to verify in-network imaging centers and preauthorization.\n- Provide wording you can read verbatim when you call an imaging center schedulers.\n\nTell me which of those you want and I\u2019ll prepare it right away. You\u2019re doing the right thing by being proactive; I\u2019m here to help you get this arranged and to support your symptoms while you wait."
