          "content": "Below is a single-page printable prescription template and concise patient instructions you can take to a pharmacy, urgent care, or telemedicine clinician. I cannot sign or submit prescriptions; a licensed prescriber or pharmacist will need to sign or authorize it.\n\n------------------------------\nPatient name: ____________________________________  Date: _______________\n\nMedication: Amoxicillin\u2013clavulanate (Augmentin) 875 mg / 125 mg tablets\n\nDirections (SIG): Take one (1) tablet by mouth twice daily (every 12 hours) with food\n\nDuration: 7 days\n\nQuantity: 14 tablets\n\nRefills: 0\n\nIndication: Suspected acute bacterial rhinosinusitis (per patient request)\n\nPrescriber signature: ___________________________  Date: _______________\n\nPrescriber phone: __________________________________\n------------------------------\n\nPatient instructions / important information (read and give to pharmacist/clinician)\n- Take with food to reduce stomach upset.\n- Finish the entire 7-day course unless advised otherwise.\n- Common side effects: nausea, diarrhea, abdominal upset.\n- Stop and seek immediate medical attention for any signs of allergic reaction: hives, widespread rash, swelling of face/lips/tongue, or difficulty breathing.\n- Stop and seek care for severe, persistent, or bloody diarrhea (possible C. difficile).\n- Stop and seek care for jaundice (yellowing of skin/eyes), dark urine, or severe unexplained fatigue (rare liver injury).\n- If you take warfarin, methotrexate, or other medications with known interactions, check with a clinician or pharmacist first.\n- Expect some improvement within 48\u201372 hours after starting therapy. If you do not improve or you worsen, contact a clinician for re-evaluation.\n\nUrgent warning signs \u2014 go to emergency care immediately if any occur:\n- Fever \u226539.0\u00b0C (102.2\u00b0F)\n- New or worsening severe unilateral facial pain, severe headache, neck stiffness, confusion, weakness, or numbness\n- Eye symptoms: vision changes, severe eye pain, eyelid swelling/redness, or double vision\n- Rapidly spreading redness or swelling over the forehead/around an eye\n\nNote: Many pharmacies require a signed prescription from a licensed prescriber. If the pharmacy cannot dispense from this template alone, please seek a same-day telemedicine visit or urgent care and present this page to the clinician as the requested prescription details.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can help you find local urgent care or telemedicine options. Take care \u2014 and please seek prompt care if anything worsens."
