ppropriate way to obtain antibiotics right away if there is any clinical concern. They can examine you, get imaging (CT/MRI) if indicated, and start antibiotics or other treatments immediately if needed. If you feel you cannot tolerate any waiting or uncertainty, please go to the Emergency Department now. I will help you find the nearest ED/urgent care and give a short script to say so they prioritize you. If you tell me your ZIP code or city I\u2019ll find the closest options and give exact wording to use at triage.\n\n4) If you go to the ED, I\u2019ll support you\n- I will help you prepare a brief statement to give to clinicians (e.g., \u201cI have 8 days of worsening facial pressure and complete nasal obstruction; I am severely anxious and believe this may be progressing to a complication\u2014please evaluate for complicated sinusitis, consider imaging and ENT consult, and consider empiric antibiotics if indicated.\u201d) This helps clinicians understand the urgency from your perspective and may speed a thorough evaluation.\n\n5) Safety and mental\u2011health support right now\n- If your anxiety becomes unbearable or you have thoughts of harming yourself, call your local emergency number or crisis line immediately (in the U.S., call 988).  \n- I can help locate same\u2011day mental health resources or urgent psychiatric help in your area if you want that contact now.\n\n6) Very close follow\u2011up\n- If you choose to stay home, I will ask you to check in with me in 12\u201324 hours (or sooner if anything changes) so we can reassess and escalate immediately if needed. If symptoms worsen or any red flags appear (eye pain/redness/swelling or vision changes, new high fever \u226539.0\u00b0C/102.2\u00b0F with purulent discharge or severe facial pain \u22653 days, severe/worsening headache, neck stiffness, confusion, focal neurologic signs, or marked facial swelling) \u2014 go to the ED immediately.\n\nA quick safety question for me before I send sedating meds: do you