        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re feeling so miserable. That facial pressure and congestion can be really unpleasant. I can help \u2014 a few quick questions first so I can give the safest, most appropriate advice:\n\n1. When your symptoms began, did they get better at all and then worse again (a \u201cdouble sickening\u201d), or have they steadily gotten worse from the start?  \n2. Any fever at all (even low-grade)? Any colored (green/yellow) pus-y nasal discharge lately?  \n3. Any worsening vision, eye swelling/redness, severe one\u2011sided facial pain, neck stiffness, confusion, or decreased breathing?  \n4. Any allergies (especially penicillin), pregnancy, breastfeeding, or immune problems, or current medications?\n\nWhy I ask: current U.S. guidelines recommend antibiotics for acute bacterial sinusitis (ABRS) only when one of these is present:\n- symptoms persist without improvement for \u226510 days, OR\n- severe symptoms (fever \u226539\u00b0C plus purulent nasal discharge or facial pain) for \u22653 days, OR\n- symptoms worsen after an initial improvement (\u201cdouble sickening\u201d).\n\nFrom what you\u2019ve told me (8 days and getting worse but no fever and mostly clear/white discharge), that generally sounds more like a viral sinus infection at this point, and antibiotics are unlikely to help and can cause side effects. That\u2019s probably why I can\u2019t prescribe antibiotics automatically today.\n\nWhat I recommend now (to relieve symptoms and watch closely)\n- Nasal saline irrigation (neti pot or saline spray) several times daily.  \n- Intranasal steroid spray (fluticasone, budesonide) once daily \u2014 helpful for congestion/pressure.  \n- Oral analgesics for pain (acetaminophen or ibuprofen as appropriate).  \n- Short course topical nasal decongestant (oxymetazoline) up to 3 days only if severe congestion, or oral decongestant (pseudoephedrine) if you have no contraindications.  \n- Humidifier/steam, plenty of fluids and rest.\n\nWhen to start antibiotics or seek an in-person visit\n- If symptoms do not start improving by day 10, OR  \n- If you develop high fever (\u226539\u00b0C), new or purulent nasal discharge, or severe persistent facial pain for \u22653 days, OR  \n- If you had initial improvement and then got worse again (double sickening), OR  \n- If you develop any eye symptoms, swelling, vision changes, severe one\u2011sided pain, confusion \u2014 go to the ER.\n\nIf you meet criteria for ABRS later, first\u2011line antibiotic for most adults is amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate (unless you have a penicillin allergy). If you\u2019d like, tell me the answers to the questions above (especially whether you initially improved) and your allergy history, and I\u2019ll advise the next steps and can arrange a prescription if appropriate.\n\nI know you want quick relief \u2014 I\u2019ll help you manage symptoms now and make a clear plan for antibiotics only if they\u2019re likely to help."
