          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re feeling so uncomfortable. Thank you for the clear description. I can help.\n\nSummary of what you\u2019ve told me\n- 35 years old, 8 days of facial pressure/pain and congestion, gradually worse\n- No high fever, discharge is clear/whitish, no \u201cdouble sickening\u201d\n- You\u2019d like an antibiotic\n\nWhat I recommend and why\n- Current guidelines say antibiotics for acute bacterial rhinosinusitis (ABRS) only when symptoms last \u226510 days without improvement, are severe (high fever \u226539\u00b0C with purulent discharge or severe facial pain for \u22653 days), or worsen after initial improvement. Based on what you described, you do not yet meet those criteria, so antibiotics are unlikely to help and can cause side effects and antibiotic resistance.\n- Most cases like this are viral and improve with supportive care over 7\u201314 days. Because you\u2019re at day 8 and symptoms are not severe, a period of focused symptom treatment and watchful waiting is reasonable.\n\nSymptomatic treatments you can start now\n- Saline nasal irrigation (neti pot or squeeze bottle) 1\u20132 times daily with sterile/distilled or previously boiled/cooled water.\n- Intranasal steroid spray (helps reduce inflammation): e.g., fluticasone 50 mcg \u2014 2 sprays each nostril once daily (or mometasone 2 sprays each nostril once daily). Use for several days \u2014 benefits may take a few days.\n- Oral analgesics for pain: ibuprofen 200\u2013400 mg every 4\u20136 hours as needed (unless contraindicated) or acetaminophen as appropriate.\n- Oral decongestant (if you have no high blood pressure or other contraindications): pseudoephedrine 30\u201360 mg every 4\u20136 hours as needed (max 240 mg/day).\n- Short course of topical nasal decongestant (oxymetazoline) may help for up to 3 days only (risk of rebound congestion if used longer).\n\nWhen antibiotics may be needed (and what I can do)\n- If symptoms haven\u2019t improved by day 10, OR if you develop high fever (\u226539\u00b0C), purulent nasal discharge, severe facial pain for \u22653 days, OR if you get worse after initial improvement (\u201cdouble sickening\u201d), then antibiotics are appropriate.\n- If you prefer, I can either:\n  - Offer a delayed antibiotic prescription (fill only if no improvement in 48\u201372 hours or by day 10), or\n  - Schedule a short follow-up / telehealth check in 48\u201372 hours to reassess and decide.\n- If you\u2019d like an immediate antibiotic despite the above, tell me and I\u2019ll discuss options and any allergies first.\n\nRed flags \u2014 seek urgent care or ER if you have\n- Vision changes, swelling or redness around an eye, severe unilateral face swelling or severe headache, neck stiffness, confusion, high fever, or rapid worsening.\n\nA couple quick questions\n- Any allergies to penicillin, sulfa, or other antibiotics?\n- Pregnant or breastfeeding, high blood pressure, heart disease, glaucoma, thyroid disease, or other chronic conditions?\n- Any prior sinus surgery or recurrent sinus infections?\n- Have you already tried any treatments so far (nasal sprays, decongestants, antibiotics)?\n\nIf you want, I can write a delayed prescription now or we can plan a follow-up in 48\u201372 hours \u2014 what would you prefer?"
