        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re feeling so uncomfortable. I can help. A few quick questions first so I can advise safely: When did your symptoms start exactly (date)? Have you ever had facial swelling, eye pain or vision changes, dental pain, or been told you\u2019re immunocompromised? Any allergies to medications (especially penicillin)? Are you pregnant or breastfeeding?\n\nWhat I think right now\n- Your symptoms (facial pressure/pain and congestion for 8 days, getting worse but no fever or purulent drainage) sound most consistent with a viral (non\u2011bacterial) sinus infection. Antibiotics are recommended for acute bacterial rhinosinusitis only when symptoms persist without improvement for \u226510 days, are severe (high fever \u226539\u00b0C with purulent discharge or severe pain for \u22653 days), or worsen after initial improvement. At 8 days without the \u201csevere\u201d features or clear \u201cdouble sickening,\u201d the evidence generally favors supportive care rather than immediate antibiotics.\n\nWhat I recommend now\n1. Symptom relief measures (start these now):\n   - Saline nasal irrigation or spray 2\u20133 times daily (isotonic saline) to clear mucus.\n   - Intranasal steroid spray (e.g., fluticasone, 1\u20132 sprays each nostril once daily) can reduce inflammation and speed recovery.\n   - Oral analgesics for pain: ibuprofen 200\u2013400 mg every 4\u20136 hours as needed (or acetaminophen if you can\u2019t take NSAIDs).\n   - Short\u2011term nasal decongestant spray (oxymetazoline) can help but use \u22643 days to avoid rebound congestion; or oral pseudoephedrine as directed if you have no contraindications (high blood pressure, certain heart problems).\n   - Humidified air, warm compresses over the face, good hydration and rest.\n\n2. Watchful waiting / safety plan:\n   - If symptoms improve or are steadily getting better, continue the above.\n   - If symptoms get worse, new high fever (\u226539\u00b0C / 102.2\u00b0F), development of purulent (thick green/yellow) nasal discharge, worsening facial pain, or if you develop eye symptoms (swelling, redness, pain with eye movement, vision changes), seek urgent care \u2014 those could need antibiotics or immediate evaluation.\n   - If your symptoms haven\u2019t improved by day 10 from onset, or if you have \u201cdouble\u2011sickening\u201d (you improved then got markedly worse), then antibiotics are appropriate. At that point the usual first\u2011line adult choice is amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate (unless you have a penicillin allergy). If you want, I can arrange a delayed prescription to be filled only if you meet those criteria.\n\nIf you\u2019d like me to prescribe a delayed antibiotic now, tell me about medication allergies (especially to penicillin) and any medical conditions (pregnancy, kidney disease, immune suppression) so I can pick the appropriate option. If you prefer to wait, start the symptomatic measures and check back in 48\u201372 hours or sooner if you worsen.\n\nI know this is frustrating \u2014 I\u2019m happy to help you decide the best next step once you tell me about allergies/other medical issues and whether you want a delayed prescription."
