        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re feeling so uncomfortable. I can help. A few quick questions to help me decide the best plan:\n- Have your symptoms ever improved and then gotten worse again (a \u201cdouble sickening\u201d)?  \n- Any fever, chills, worsening headache, swelling around the eyes, vision changes, or dental pain?  \n- Any medical problems (diabetes, immune suppression), pregnancy, or allergies (especially penicillin)?\n\nWhat I can tell you now:\n- Current guidelines recommend antibiotics for acute bacterial sinusitis only if symptoms persist without improvement for \u226510 days, OR are severe (high fever \u226539\u00b0C plus purulent nasal discharge or facial pain for \u22653 days), OR worsen after initial improvement. From what you\u2019ve said (8 days, no fever, non\u2011purulent discharge), you do not yet meet those criteria, so antibiotics aren\u2019t routinely recommended right now.\n- Most cases at this stage are viral and improve with supportive care.\n\nPractical steps you can start today:\n- Saline nasal irrigation (isotonic saline rinse or spray) 1\u20133 times daily.  \n- Intranasal corticosteroid spray (e.g., fluticasone 1\u20132 sprays each nostril daily) can reduce inflammation and speed recovery.  \n- Pain relief: acetaminophen or ibuprofen as needed.  \n- Short\u2011term oral decongestant (pseudoephedrine) or topical oxymetazoline (max 3 days) can help congestion if no contraindications.  \n- Rest, fluids, steam/inhalation for symptom relief.\n\nWhen to start antibiotics or seek immediate care:\n- If symptoms persist without improvement through day 10, or become worse after initial improvement, or you develop high fever, marked facial swelling, vision changes, severe headache, confusion, or focal neurologic signs \u2014 contact me or urgent care immediately. At that point antibiotics (first\u2011line: amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate unless you have an allergy) would be appropriate.\n- If you\u2019d prefer, I can either arrange close follow\u2011up or give a delayed prescription to be filled only if you\u2019re not better by day 10 or if symptoms worsen sooner.\n\nIf you answer my brief questions above (especially about any allergic reactions to antibiotics), I\u2019ll give a more specific plan and can arrange follow-up or a prescription if needed. You\u2019re doing the right thing by checking in \u2014 we\u2019ll watch this closely and treat with antibiotics if and when the clinical criteria are met."
