        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m Dr. Smith. Thanks for telling me what\u2019s been going on; I can hear how uncomfortable and worried you are.\n\nBased on what you\u2019ve described (8 days of gradually worsening facial pain/pressure and nasal congestion, no high fever, no purulent nasal discharge and no \u201cdouble-sickening\u201d), this most likely represents viral acute rhinosinusitis rather than acute bacterial rhinosinusitis. Current guidelines recommend antibiotics only when symptoms last \u226510 days without improvement, are severe (fever \u226539\u00b0C with purulent nasal discharge or facial pain for \u22653 days), or worsen after initial improvement. So right now antibiotics are unlikely to help and are not recommended.\n\nWhat I suggest now (symptom-directed care)\n- Saline nasal irrigation or saline spray several times daily (Neti pot or isotonic saline spray) to help clear secretions.  \n- Intranasal steroid spray (OTC or prescription) can reduce inflammation and speed recovery \u2014 e.g., fluticasone (Flonase) 1\u20132 sprays each nostril once daily. I can recommend/prescribe one if you\u2019d like, but I\u2019ll check for allergies or pregnancy first.  \n- Short-term nasal decongestants if needed: oral pseudoephedrine (if you have no high blood pressure or other contraindications) or oxymetazoline nasal spray for up to 3 days only (to avoid rebound).  \n- Pain control: acetaminophen or ibuprofen as needed for facial pain.  \n- Home measures: warm compresses to the face, steam inhalation, stay well hydrated, and sleep with head elevated.\n\nWhen to consider antibiotics or urgent evaluation\n- If symptoms persist without improvement through day 10, or  \n- If you develop a high fever (\u226539\u00b0C), new purulent nasal discharge, worsening after initial improvement (\u201cdouble sickening\u201d), severe or asymmetric facial swelling, vision changes, severe headache, or neck stiffness \u2014 seek urgent care or contact me and we\u2019ll consider antibiotics or further evaluation.\n\nBefore I recommend or prescribe any medication, could you tell me:\n- Any drug allergies?  \n- Pregnancy or breastfeeding?  \n- High blood pressure, heart disease, or other chronic conditions, and any regular medications?  \n- How severe is the pain on a 1\u201310 scale and is it affecting sleep/work?\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can send a recommendation for an intranasal steroid and a plan for symptomatic meds now."
