        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 sorry you\u2019re feeling miserable. Based on what you describe (8 days of gradually worsening congestion, facial pressure, no fever and mostly clear discharge, and no \u201cdouble sickening\u201d), this most likely sounds like viral rhinosinusitis rather than acute bacterial sinusitis. Current guidelines recommend antibiotics only when symptoms last without improvement for 10 days or more, are severe (high fever \u226539\u00b0C with purulent discharge or facial pain for \u22653 days), or worsen after initial improvement. So right now antibiotics are not routinely recommended.\n\nHere\u2019s what I suggest to help you feel better now:\n- Start supportive care:\n  - Saline nasal irrigation (neti pot or squeeze bottle) or saline sprays several times daily.\n  - An intranasal steroid spray (fluticasone, budesonide, etc.) once or twice daily for up to 2 weeks \u2014 this can reduce inflammation and speed recovery.\n  - Oral analgesics (acetaminophen or ibuprofen) for pain/pressure.\n  - Consider a short course of oral decongestant (pseudoephedrine) or topical oxymetazoline \u2014 topical only for up to 3 days to avoid rebound congestion. Avoid decongestants if you have uncontrolled hypertension, certain heart conditions, or are pregnant without discussing first.\n  - Stay well hydrated, rest, humidify the air, and use warm compresses over the face.\n\nWhen to get antibiotics or come back:\n- If symptoms do not improve by day 10, or if they get worse after initial improvement, call back and we\u2019ll consider antibiotics (amoxicillin\u2013clavulanate is a usual first choice unless you have a penicillin allergy).\n- If you develop high fever (\u226539\u00b0C/102.2\u00b0F), thick green/yellow nasal discharge with worsening facial pain, severe unilateral facial swelling, vision changes, or severe headache/confusion \u2014 seek urgent care or emergency care.\n\nQuick questions so I can tailor advice:\n- Do you have any medication allergies (especially to penicillin)?\n- Any pregnancy, high blood pressure, heart disease, or immune problems?\n- Any recent dental work, facial swelling, vision changes, or worsening fever?\n\nIf you prefer, I can write a prescription now after we discuss allergies/medical history, but given guidelines I\u2019d generally recommend trying the supportive measures for up to 10 days unless red flags appear."
