        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 sorry you\u2019re feeling so miserable. Tell me a bit more while I explain what I\u2019d do next: do you have any medical problems (diabetes, immune disease), take any medications, have any drug allergies (especially penicillin), are you pregnant or breastfeeding, or have you had recent dental work or facial trauma?\n\nBased on what you\u2019ve described (8 days of slowly worsening facial pressure and clear discharge, no high fever or a \u201cdouble\u2011sickening\u201d pattern), this most likely still represents viral (not bacterial) acute rhinosinusitis. Current evidence/guidelines recommend antibiotics only if symptoms last \u226510 days without improvement, are severe (fever \u226539\u00b0C with purulent nasal discharge or facial pain for \u22653 days), or worsen after initial improvement. Because you don\u2019t meet those criteria, antibiotics are unlikely to help and can cause side effects and resistance.\n\nRecommended plan now\n- Watchful waiting for up to 10 days from onset unless symptoms meet the bacterial criteria listed above. If you\u2019re not better by day 10, or if you develop a high fever (\u226539\u00b0C), new purulent nasal discharge or severe/worsening pain, or a \u201cdouble sickening\u201d course, start antibiotics or come in for re-evaluation.  \n- Symptom relief measures now:\n  - Saline nasal irrigation or nasal saline spray several times daily.  \n  - Intranasal steroid spray (e.g., fluticasone 1\u20132 sprays each nostril once daily) for several days \u2014 helps reduce inflammation.  \n  - Analgesics: ibuprofen 200\u2013400 mg or acetaminophen 500\u20131000 mg as needed for pain (follow dosing limits / tell me if pregnant).  \n  - Short-term decongestants if needed: oral pseudoephedrine (if no high blood pressure/heart disease) or topical oxymetazoline spray for no more than 3 days to avoid rebound congestion.  \n- Consider a delayed antibiotic prescription (kept for you to fill only if no improvement by day 10 or if you meet the bacterial criteria sooner) \u2014 I can arrange that if you prefer.\n\nWhen to seek care urgently\n- High fever (\u226539\u00b0C), worsening facial swelling/redness, vision changes, severe unilateral facial pain, stiff neck, confusion, or signs of spreading infection \u2014 go to ED/urgent care.\n\nIf you want, I can: (A) arrange a delayed antibiotic prescription, (B) write one now (not recommended), or (C) schedule a follow-up in 48\u201372 hours or sooner if you worsen. Also tell me your allergy history and any pregnancy or major medical issues so I can tailor recommendations."
