 while you arrange in\u2011person care\n- Intranasal corticosteroid spray (e.g., fluticasone 1\u20132 sprays per nostril once daily) \u2014 reduces inflammation and may shorten symptoms.\n- Saline nasal irrigation or sprays several times daily.\n- Analgesics: ibuprofen or acetaminophen as needed.\n- Short course topical nasal decongestant (oxymetazoline) no more than 3 days if you have severe congestion, or oral pseudoephedrine if you have no contra\u2011indications.\n\nIf an antibiotic is indicated after evaluation, typical choices (if no penicillin allergy)\n- Amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate 875/125 mg PO twice daily for 5\u20137 days is first\u2011line for adults.  \nIf you have a penicillin allergy, alternatives include doxycycline or, in selected cases, respiratory fluoroquinolones (used sparingly).\n\nWhen to seek urgent care / ED\n- High fever (\u226539\u00b0C), worsening facial swelling/redness, eye pain/vision changes, severe unilateral facial pain, neck stiffness, confusion, or other signs of spreading infection \u2014 go to ED.\n\nNext step for you\n- Do you want me to: (A) arrange a same\u2011day in\u2011person appointment/urgent\u2011care referral now, (B) issue a delayed prescription with clear fill instructions, or (C) both? If A, tell me your location and whether you prefer urgent care or ENT and I\u2019ll help set that up."
