t or if you develop high fever (\u226539\u00b0C), new purulent drainage, or markedly worse pain \u2014 this is the best compromise between immediate access and safe, evidence\u2011based care.\n\n3) Immediate measures I can authorize now that often help and are safe:\n   - Prescription intranasal steroid (e.g., fluticasone spray) \u2014 reduces inflammation and can shorten symptoms.\n   - Short note you can show at urgent care saying: \u201c35\u2011y/o with 8 days of progressive facial pressure and nasal congestion, no fever, clear discharge. Patient requests urgent evaluation for possible ABRS and antibiotics if bacterial features are confirmed.\u201d\n\nIf antibiotics are prescribed after evaluation, the usual first\u2011line adult choice (if no penicillin allergy) is amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate 875/125 mg PO twice daily for 5\u20137 days.\n\nRed flags \u2014 come to ED or urgent care right away if you get:\n- High fever \u226539\u00b0C, worsening facial swelling/redness, eye pain or vision changes, severe unilateral facial pain, neck stiffness, confusion, or other signs of spreading infection.\n\nNext step \u2014 which would you prefer right now?\nA) I\u2019ll search for and help arrange a same\u2011day in\u2011person or video visit near you (tell me city/zip and whether you want urgent care, PCP, or ENT).  \nB) I\u2019ll prepare a delayed antibiotic prescription with clear fill criteria.  \nC) I\u2019ll prescribe an intranasal steroid and give symptom\u2011control recommendations.\n\nI want to get you better quickly \u2014 tell me which option you want and your location if you choose A and I\u2019ll act on it immediately."
