          "content": "Thanks \u2014 I\u2019ve got everything. I\u2019m sorry you\u2019ve been so uncomfortable, and I\u2019m glad the plan and commitment make you feel more secure.\n\nSummary and plan\n- Symptom start date: October 25 \u2192 Day 10 = November 2. I\u2019ll expect your check\u2011in then if there\u2019s no meaningful improvement, and I will issue an antibiotic prescription immediately at that time. If you worsen before then (see urgent signs below), contact me immediately and I will arrange antibiotics or urgent evaluation as needed.\n- You confirmed: no drug allergies, no medical problems, not pregnant/breastfeeding.\n\nPrescription text to give to your pharmacy or primary care clinician\n- Fluticasone propionate nasal spray 50 mcg/spray  \n  Rx: Fluticasone propionate nasal spray 50 mcg/spray  \n  Sig: 2 sprays each nostril once daily. Start today.  \n  Dispense: 1 bottle (120 sprays). Refills: 0\n\n- Pseudoephedrine 30 mg tablets  \n  Rx: Pseudoephedrine 30 mg tablets  \n  Sig: 1 tablet (30\u201360 mg) PO every 4\u20136 hours PRN for nasal congestion. Max 240 mg/day.  \n  Dispense: #30. Refills: 0\n\nHow to use them safely and effectively\n- Fluticasone: prime before first use. Aim slightly away from the septum, spray while gently inhaling. Use daily; expect benefit often within 48\u201372 hours but it may take several days. Possible mild nose irritation or occasional nosebleed \u2014 stop and contact me if bleeding is severe or persistent.\n- Pseudoephedrine: can raise heart rate or blood pressure, cause insomnia or jitteriness. You\u2019ll likely need ID at the pharmacy (often kept behind the counter). Stop and seek care if you get palpitations, chest pain, or severe headache.\n- Saline nasal irrigation: 1\u20132\u00d7 daily with distilled or boiled-and-cooled water; clean device after each use.\n- Analgesia: ibuprofen 200\u2013400 mg PO every 4\u20136 hrs PRN (follow label, typical OTC max 1,200 mg/day) or acetaminophen 500\u20131,000 mg every 4\u20136 hrs PRN (follow label limits).\n\nWhat \u201cmeaningful improvement\u201d means (for our Day\u201110 decision)\n- Noticeable reduction in facial pressure/pain and congestion, less drainage, better ability to breathe/sleep/perform normal activities. If symptoms are essentially the same or clearly worse on Nov 2, I will prescribe antibiotics that day.\n\nAntibiotic plan if criteria met on Nov 2 (or sooner if you meet criteria)\n- First\u2011line (typical adult): amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate 875/125 mg PO twice daily for ~5\u20137 days (duration individualized).  \n- If you report a true penicillin allergy then doxycycline 100 mg PO twice daily is a common alternative. I will adjust if pregnancy, immunosuppression, recent antibiotics, or other factors are present.\n\nUrgent warning signs \u2014 seek urgent care/ER immediately if any occur before Nov 2\n- Eye pain, redness, swelling, or vision changes  \n- Severe headache with neck stiffness, confusion, or altered mental status  \n- Rapidly spreading facial swelling or redness  \n- High fever (\u226539\u00b0C) with severe local symptoms\n\nFollow-up\n- You\u2019ll message or call on Nov 2 if no meaningful improvement and I will send the antibiotic prescription immediately. If you prefer, I can check in with you that day \u2014 tell me if you want me to initiate the check\u2011in or you\u2019ll contact me.\n\nIf you want help getting the meds now\n- I can draft a short message you can forward to your PCP/urgent\u2011care clinician to request they e\u2011prescribe these two items. Say the word and I\u2019ll prepare it.\n\nI\u2019m here if you need anything before Nov 2 \u2014 and I\u2019ll be ready to prescribe antibiotics promptly on Nov 2 if you haven\u2019t improved. Take care and try to rest, hydrate, and use the treatments above to get some relief."
