an understands the clinical facts and your preference immediately.\n   - Check for drug interactions if you list any current medications.\n   - Help you find and book a same-day telehealth or urgent-care option that can legally issue the held Rx.\n\nReady-to-use held-prescription text (copy/paste for a clinician)\n- Medication: Amoxicillin\u2013clavulanate 875 mg /125 mg tablets\n- Sig: 1 tablet PO twice daily with food\n- Dispense: #14 (7 days)\n- Refills: none\n- Clinical note to add: \u201c35yo with 8 days progressive facial pressure and nasal congestion, worsening trajectory despite symptomatic care; patient requests early access to antibiotic. Rx provided as a delayed/held prescription: do not fill unless symptoms fail to improve or worsen within 48 hours; patient advised on red flags and will follow up in 48\u201372 hours.\u201d\n\nAlternate (if penicillin allergy): Doxycycline 100 mg PO twice daily x7 days with same note.\n\nFast options to actually get that Rx signed today\n- Telehealth visits (same day; most can e-prescribe): Teladoc, Amwell, MDLIVE, Doctor on Demand, or your health system\u2019s telemedicine portal.\n- Urgent care or retail clinics (MinuteClinic, urgent care centers) \u2014 ask up front for a delayed/held prescription.\n- PCP portal: paste the message above and request a same-day phone/tele-visit to sign the Rx.\n\nHow I can help right now (choose one)\n- Draft the exact portal/telehealth message with your pharmacy name (I\u2019ll format it).\n- Role-play a short script you can use on the call so the clinician will issue the held Rx quickly.\n- Find nearby telehealth/urgent-care options with same-day e-prescribing (tell me your city/zip).\n- Check for interactions if you share any current medications.\n\nNext step suggestion (quickest path)\n- Pick a telehealth provider (or tell me your zip so I can suggest local urgent care) and I\u2019ll prepare the exact message and a 30\u2013second script you can use. If you give your pharmacy name and