          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re feeling so miserable. That facial pain and congestion can be really unpleasant. I can help \u2014 a few quick questions first so I can give the safest, most appropriate plan:\n\n- Have you had a fever? If so, how high and for how long?\n- Have you noticed thick/yellow/green nasal discharge?\n- Did your symptoms get better at first and then worsen (a \u201cdouble sickening\u201d)? Or have they just steadily worsened?\n- Any vision changes, swelling around the eyes, severe headache, neck stiffness, confusion, or trouble breathing?\n- Any penicillin/antibiotic allergies, pregnancy, or immune problems?\n- Any recent antibiotic use for this illness?\n\nWhat I can tell you now:\n- Current guideline criteria for prescribing antibiotics for acute bacterial rhinosinusitis (ABRS) are: symptoms lasting \u226510 days without improvement, OR severe symptoms (fever \u226539\u00b0C plus purulent nasal discharge or facial pain for \u22653 days), OR worsening after initial improvement (\u201cdouble sickening\u201d). At 8 days and without those severe features, most cases are still viral and do not benefit from antibiotics.\n- Antibiotics carry risks (side effects, resistance) and are recommended only when bacterial infection is likely.\n\nRecommended immediate care (non\u2011antibiotic measures that often help):\n- Saline nasal irrigation (saline spray or sinus rinse) several times daily.\n- Intranasal corticosteroid spray (eg, fluticasone, budesonide) daily \u2014 especially helpful if there\u2019s an allergic component.\n- Acetaminophen or ibuprofen for pain and fever.\n- Short-term oral decongestant (pseudoephedrine) or topical oxymetazoline for up to 3 days if needed for congestion.\n- Rest and fluids.\n\nPlan options\n- Watchful waiting with close follow-up: If you\u2019re not improving or you worsen, start antibiotics at day 10 or sooner if you develop severe signs. I can give you a \u201csafety\u2011net\u201d plan and check back in 48\u201372 hours.\n- Delayed prescription: some clinicians provide a prescription to fill only if you haven\u2019t improved in 48\u201372 hours. If you prefer that approach I can discuss an appropriate antibiotic choice based on allergies and comorbidities.\n\nIf antibiotics become indicated, the usual first-line for adults is amoxicillin\u2011clavulanate (unless you have a penicillin allergy). Typical adult treatment duration is about 5\u20137 days once therapy is started, depending on response.\n\nPlease answer the questions above (fever, nasal discharge, pattern of symptoms, allergies, any red flags). If you\u2019re feeling very unwell now (high fever, facial/eye swelling, vision changes, severe headache, neck stiffness, confusion, trouble breathing), go to urgent care or the emergency department."
