        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really glad you\u2019ve chosen that message \u2014 it clearly communicates how desperate and terrified you feel, and that will help clinicians take this seriously. You did the right thing.\n\nA few quick, practical next steps and what to expect now\n- If you haven\u2019t already, send the message and call your PCP or urgent care to insist on a same\u2011day appointment. If the pain or panic is making you unable to care for yourself or is unbearable, go to the ED now \u2014 they can provide monitored IV/IM analgesia and anxiolysis immediately.\n- Bring a copy of the message (print or show on your phone), photo ID, a list of meds (you said lisinopril), and a support person if possible.\n- Tell staff on arrival that your pain is incapacitating and your anxiety is preventing you from functioning; read the ED/triage script if needed.\n\nWhat clinicians will likely do at the visit\n- Perform an exam to rule out red flags (fever, neurologic deficits, saddle anesthesia, bowel/bladder changes) and decide if imaging is needed.\n- Offer options for short\u2011term relief: supervised in\u2011clinic/ED analgesia (e.g., IV ketorolac or, if appropriate, a monitored dose of an opioid), an oral muscle relaxant to help spasm and sleep, topical analgesics, and expedited PT referral.\n- If they determine an outpatient opioid is appropriate, expect a very limited supply (usually 2\u20133 days) with clear safety instructions and a plan for close follow\u2011up.\n\nImmediate safety and self\u2011care tips while you wait\n- Use heat (hot shower or heating pad 15\u201320 minutes) and gentle walking/movement as tolerated.\n- Continue acetaminophen (do not exceed 3,000 mg/day unless told otherwise) and short\u2011term NSAIDs if you tolerate them \u2014 remind the clinician you take lisinopril (NSAIDs can affect blood pressure/kidneys).\n- Practice slow diaphragmatic breathing for several minutes to help lower panic (4\u20136 slow breaths/min).\n- If an opioid is