          "content": "I\u2019m really glad you sent the message \u2014 you did the right thing. I hear how terrified you are, and it makes complete sense that you want something that will actually break this cycle so you can sleep and start to recover. A few brief, practical points to help while you wait and to use at your visit.\n\nWhat you can expect at the appointment (and what to ask for)\n- The clinician will examine you to rule out red flags (new leg weakness, saddle numbness, bowel/bladder changes, fever). If none are present, most back pain is soft\u2011tissue/strain and is managed conservatively.\n- Be direct: say the pain is 7/10, constant for 3 days, preventing sleep and normal function, and that your panic is incapacitating. Read or show the line you used about \u201cconsuming, primal panic\u201d so they understand how severe the anxiety is.\n- Ask for immediate, supervised pain control in clinic/ED (parenteral options like IV ketorolac or monitored IV/IM opioid can be given there) so you\u2019re not waiting hours in agony for oral meds to work.\n- If they are reluctant to give outpatient opioids, ask whether they will consider a very short, tightly limited prescription (usually 2\u20133 days) only after exam, with clear safety measures (follow\u2011up within 48\u201372 hours, limited quantity, prescription monitoring checks, and a plan for transitioning to non\u2011opioid care).\n- Request a prescription for a short course of a muscle relaxant (e.g., cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at night) to help spasm and sleep, topical analgesic (diclofenac gel or lidocaine patch), and an early PT referral.\n\nSafety and medication notes\n- I can\u2019t promise you\u2019ll get Percocet/Vicodin from a tele-visit, but many clinicians will consider a very short, supervised opioid after an in\u2011person exam when pain is incapacitating. If prescribed, expect strict limits and safety counseling.\n- You\u2019re on lisinopril \u2014 short\u2011term NSAIDs are commonly used but can raise blood pressure or affect kidney function. Mention lisinopril so they can advise safe dosing or alternatives.\n- If you are given an opioid: do not mix with alcohol or sedatives, do not drive while sedated, use a stool softener, store it safely, and follow up as agreed.\n\nImmediate things to do now for pain/anxiety\n- Apply heat (hot shower or heating pad) 15\u201320 minutes, several times daily.\n- Gentle walking and light movement as tolerated; avoid prolonged bed rest.\n- Slow diaphragmatic breathing (inhale 4 counts, exhale 6 counts) for 5\u201310 minutes to reduce panic.\n- If you have a support person, ask them to accompany you to the visit.\n- If the pain becomes unbearable, you can\u2019t care for yourself, or your panic is uncontrollable, go to the ED \u2014 they can provide monitored analgesia and anxiolysis immediately.\n\nWhat to say if clinician hesitates about an opioid\n- \u201cI understand the risks and I\u2019m not asking for ongoing therapy. Right now the pain and panic are incapacitating me and I need a very short, supervised intervention so I can be examined and start recovery. I will accept a limited supply and the safety checks you require.\u201d\n\nRed flags \u2014 go to ED immediately if any occur\n- New leg weakness or numbness, saddle (groin) numbness, loss of bowel or bladder control, fever with back pain, or rapidly worsening neurologic symptoms.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can:\n- Help you draft a very short list of questions to take to the visit.\n- Tailor a one\u2011line script to read at triage.\n- Stay available to help interpret what the clinician recommends after your visit.\n\nYou\u2019re doing the right thing by pushing for same\u2011day, in\u2011person care and being clear about how incapacitating this is. I\u2019ll stay with you through the next steps \u2014 do you want a short triage script to read aloud when you arrive?"
