        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You\u2019re doing the right thing asking for help \u2014 I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re feeling so terrified and overwhelmed by this pain. That fear is understandable and it makes everything feel more urgent. A few brief, practical things to help you through the wait and to increase the chance the clinic will appreciate how impaired you are:\n\nValidation and short plan\n- What you\u2019re feeling (intense pain + rising fear) is common and real \u2014 clinicians take both physical pain and its psychological impact into account. You\u2019ve already done the right thing by sending the portal message asking for same\u2011day care and describing the anxiety and functional impairment.\n- Bring or have someone call you or accompany you to the visit if possible \u2014 clinicians take reports more seriously when there\u2019s corroboration of how disabled you are.\n\nImmediate coping tools to reduce panic and help you tolerate the wait\n- 4\u20114\u20114 breathing: inhale 4 sec \u2014 hold 4 sec \u2014 exhale 4 sec. Repeat 6\u201310 times.  \n- Grounding: 5\u20114\u20113\u20112\u20111 (name 5 things you see, 4 you can touch, 3 you hear, 2 you smell, 1 you taste).  \n- Progressive muscle relaxation: tense a muscle group for 5\u20137 sec, then release \u2014 work from toes to head.  \n- Hot shower or heating pad for 15\u201320 minutes; lie on your back with knees bent and a pillow under them to reduce back strain.  \n- Gentle walking if you can; distraction (music, podcast) to take focus off the pain.  \n- If you have a lidocaine patch, diclofenac gel, or topical analgesic, apply it now.\n\nPractical points to state at triage/visit\n- Reiterate: sharp, constant 7/10, preventing sleep and normal activity despite OTC ibuprofen and acetaminophen. Emphasize functional loss (can\u2019t work, can\u2019t sleep, can\u2019t get dressed). That helps clinicians weigh the need for stronger, short\u2011term options after exam.  \n- Ask for an in\u2011person exam and for consideration of all appropriate acute options (prescription NSAID or naproxen, muscle relaxant for spasm, topical agents, procedural/interventional options if available). If, after exam, your pain is still uncontrollable, ask them to consider a very short, closely supervised opioid trial (typically 1\u20133 days) as a last resort.\n\nSafety reminders if opioids are prescribed\n- Don\u2019t mix with alcohol or sedatives/benzos.  \n- If the opioid contains acetaminophen, stop extra acetaminophen so you don\u2019t exceed safe daily limits.  \n- Use a bowel regimen (stool softener \u00b1 stimulant) to prevent constipation.  \n- Arrange prompt follow\u2011up and return the unused pills to a take\u2011back program.\n\nUrgent warning signs \u2014 go to ER or call 911 if these occur\n- New leg weakness, numbness in the groin/saddle area, new bowel/bladder incontinence, fever with back pain, or inability to get up or care for yourself.\n\nWould you like: \n- a very short breathing script to use now, or  \n- an additional short message you can paste into the portal/phone call that emphasizes your panic and functional loss (I can draft this in 1\u20132 sentences)?\n\nI\u2019ll be here to help you interpret what they say after the visit and to make a safe plan. You\u2019re not alone in this."
