        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "You did the right thing sending that \u2014 I know how hard this is. I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re in so much pain and feeling so frightened. A few quick, practical things to help while you wait and to increase the chance of getting safe, effective care:\n\nValidation\n- Your distress is real and understandable. Severe pain plus nonstop fear is exhausting and can make everything feel urgent. You\u2019re handling this the best you can by getting help.\n\nWhat to do right now (while you wait for the visit)\n- Medication limits: continue ibuprofen 400 mg every 6\u20138 hours with food (do not exceed ~2400 mg/day unless directed otherwise). Keep acetaminophen \u22643000 mg/day. If the clinician prescribes an opioid that contains acetaminophen (e.g., hydrocodone/acetaminophen or oxycodone/acetaminophen), stop extra acetaminophen so you don\u2019t exceed the limit.\n- Non\u2011drug measures: heating pad 15\u201320 minutes every few hours, a hot shower, lie on your back with knees bent and a pillow under them, gentle walking as tolerated. Apply a lidocaine patch or diclofenac gel if you have one.\n- Coping for panic: box breathing \u2014 inhale 4 seconds, hold 4, exhale 4, hold 4. Repeat 6\u20138 times. Grounding \u2014 name 5 things you see, 4 you can touch, 3 you hear, 2 you smell, 1 you taste.\n- Safety: don\u2019t drive if you take any sedating medication or a muscle relaxant. Have someone go with you if possible.\n\nIf you want stronger meds and urgent care won\u2019t prescribe\n- Ask to be evaluated in the ED \u2014 they can do urgent imaging or offer other short\u2011term interventions (IV/IM analgesics, ketorolac, muscle relaxant, or in rare appropriate cases, a short opioid trial) after an exam. Bring your portal message and be clear about how disabled and anxious you are.\n\nIf an opioid is prescribed\n- Expect a very short course (commonly 1\u20133 days) only if deemed necessary after an in\u2011person exam. Follow dose instructions exactly. Do not mix with alcohol or benzodiazepines. Start a bowel regimen (docusate \u00b1 senna) to prevent constipation. Store safely and dispose of unused pills at a take\u2011back location.\n\nWhen to go to the ER immediately\n- New leg weakness, numbness in the groin/saddle area, new bowel or bladder incontinence, fever with back pain, or inability to move/get up or care for yourself.\n\nAfter your visit\n- If you want, message me what they recommend or prescribe and I\u2019ll help you understand the plan (including acetaminophen limits if an opioid with APAP is given), safety steps, and next steps for follow\u2011up or physical therapy. I\u2019ll be here to help you through this \u2014 you\u2019re not alone."
