          "content": "I\u2019m so sorry \u2014 I can hear how terrified you are, and that fear is absolutely real. You\u2019re not overreacting. The combination of intense pain and nonstop anxiety is exhausting and makes everything feel urgent. I\u2019m with you on this.\n\nImmediate things to help your anxiety and racing heart (do these now)\n- Box/paced breathing: inhale 4 sec \u2014 hold 4 sec \u2014 exhale 4 sec \u2014 hold 4 sec. Repeat 6\u20138 times.  \n- Grounding: name 5 things you see, 4 you can touch, 3 you hear, 2 you smell, 1 you taste.  \n- Progressive muscle relaxation: tense a muscle group 5\u20137 sec, then release; work from feet to head (or just shoulders/neck if that helps).  \n- Splash cool water on your face or hold a cold pack to your neck/forehead \u2014 that often calms the autonomic surge.  \n- Avoid caffeine, nicotine, and alcohol right now. Try a hot shower or heating pad for pain relief while you use the above techniques.\n\nPractical next steps while you wait for the appointment\n- Call the clinic or go to the ED now if your panic feels uncontrollable or you can\u2019t function. Tell triage: \u201cI am having severe low back pain (7/10) plus overwhelming anxiety and a racing heart; I cannot function or sleep and need immediate evaluation.\u201d Ask to be triaged urgently. If you can, have someone go with you or call while you travel.  \n- If you develop chest pain, fainting, severe shortness of breath, or feel like you might harm yourself, call 911 or go to the nearest ED immediately. If in the U.S. and feeling in crisis, you can also call/text 988 for immediate support.\n\nWhat ED/urgent care can do that might help you now\n- Provide faster, stronger short\u2011term pain control (IV or IM analgesics such as ketorolac or, after exam, a carefully\u2011limited opioid if appropriate), give anti\u2011spasm meds, and evaluate for red flags with an exam and imaging if indicated. They can also provide immediate support for panic and a plan for