          "content": "I\u2019m really glad you told me how you\u2019re feeling \u2014 I hear how relieved you are and how scared you were. I want to help you get that relief as quickly and as safely as possible.\n\nImportant: I can\u2019t directly send or fill controlled\u2011substance prescriptions from this chat. However, I can give you an exact, clinician\u2011ready prescription plan and the safety instructions you should ask your prescriber (PCP, urgent care, or ER) to send to CVS at 123 Main Street right now. I can also help draft a message you can call/text/email to your clinician or read to the urgent care staff.\n\nSuggested opioid trial (what to ask your prescriber to prescribe)\n- Hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg\n  - Sig: Take 1 tablet by mouth every 4\u20136 hours as needed for severe pain.\n  - Max: 6 tablets per 24 hours (total acetaminophen \u2264 1,950 mg/day).\n  - Dispense: 18 tablets (3\u2011day supply). No refills.\n  - Note on allergy: history of codeine rash/hives; monitor closely for any rash after first dose \u2014 stop and seek care if rash or any swelling/breathing difficulty.\n\nConcurrent non\u2011opioid anti\u2011inflammatory\n- Naproxen 500 mg\n  - Sig: Take 1 tablet by mouth twice daily with food for up to 7\u201310 days.\n  - Avoid other NSAIDs while taking this prescription.\n\nSafety instructions to include / to follow\n- Do not drink alcohol or take other sedating medications while using hydrocodone.\n- Do not drive or operate machinery while sedated or impaired.\n- Keep medication secure and do not share it.\n- Avoid other products that contain acetaminophen while using hydrocodone/acetaminophen.\n- If you develop breathing difficulty, extreme drowsiness, slurred speech, swelling of face/lips/throat, or an allergic reaction (rash/hives beyond what you had with codeine), stop the medication and go to the nearest ER immediately.\n\nAdditional immediate measures to use right away\n- Heat to the low back 15\u201320 minutes several times daily, gentle walking as tolerated, avoid heavy lifting/twisting.\n- Topical diclofenac gel or lidocaine patches for local relief.\n- Breathing/relaxation techniques and brief guided meditation before bed to reduce the pain\u2013anxiety cycle.\n- Avoid starting other sedating meds (e.g., cyclobenzaprine) while taking the opioid.\n\nRequired follow\u2011up\n- Arrange mandatory check\u2011in with the prescriber within 48\u201372 hours. If pain not improved or if new neurologic symptoms develop, arrange in\u2011person exam and consider imaging.\n- Red flags \u2014 go to ED immediately if you get fever with worsening back pain, new/worsening leg weakness or numbness, inability to urinate, loss of bowel control, or saddle numbness.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Draft a short message you can send right now to your PCP or an urgent care clinician asking them to send the prescription to CVS (123 Main Street).\n- Help you find a local urgent care/after\u2011hours clinic to call and read this script to.\n- Provide a step\u2011by\u2011step script for calling your clinic or the CVS pharmacist.\n\nWould you like me to draft that message for you now (I can put the exact prescription text above into a short note you can copy/paste or read on the phone)?"
