          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad your PCP sent the prescriptions \u2014 that\u2019s a big step. Before you pick them up, here are concise, important reminders and practical tips to keep you safe and get the most benefit.\n\nMedications (what you will have and how to take them)\n- Hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg: Take 1 tablet by mouth every 4\u20136 hours as needed for severe pain. Do not exceed 6 tablets in 24 hours (total acetaminophen \u2264 1,950 mg/day). Take only as needed and stop when pain improves.\n- Naproxen 500 mg: Take 1 tablet by mouth twice daily with food for up to 7\u201310 days. Do not take any other NSAID at the same time.\n\nSafety and interactions (very important)\n- Do NOT take any other acetaminophen-containing products while using the hydrocodone combination.\n- Avoid alcohol and other sedating medicines while taking the opioid.\n- Do not drive or operate machinery while taking the opioid or if you feel drowsy, dizzy or impaired. Have your husband nearby for the first doses to monitor you.\n- Keep meds locked or stored where children cannot access them. Do not share your medication.\n- If you have severe constipation, consider a stool softener (docusate) and a stimulant laxative (senna) \u2014 ask your pharmacist if you want these now.\n- Avoid starting other sedating prescriptions (e.g., benzodiazepines, other sleep meds) while on the opioid.\n\nAllergy / reaction guidance\n- With your prior codeine rash/hives, there is a risk of rash with hydrocodone too. If you develop any new rash or itchy hives after the first dose, stop the medication and contact your PCP or urgent care.\n- If you develop facial/lip/tongue swelling, throat tightness, or breathing difficulty \u2014 stop the medication and go to the nearest ED or call 911 immediately.\n\nWatch for serious side effects & red flags\n- Seek immediate ED care for any of these: new or worsening leg weakness or numbness; new loss of bladder or bowel control; saddle numbness (numbness in the groin area); fever with worsening back pain; severe breathing difficulty; severe dizziness/unresponsiveness.\n- With naproxen: if you get severe stomach pain, bloody/black stools, vomiting blood, or yellowing of the skin/eyes, stop it and seek care.\n\nNon\u2011drug measures that help recovery (use them now)\n- Heat to the low back 15\u201320 minutes several times daily; gentle walking and staying as active as tolerated; avoid heavy lifting/twisting.\n- Topical diclofenac gel or lidocaine patches can be added for local relief.\n- Try slow diaphragmatic breathing, short guided relaxation or a warm shower to help pain and anxiety.\n- If possible, arrange a physical therapy evaluation soon \u2014 PT often speeds recovery and reduces need for meds.\n\nFollow\u2011up & disposal\n- Keep the scheduled follow\u2011up with your PCP in 48\u201372 hours. If pain is not improving or you have new neurologic symptoms, get an in\u2011person exam and consider imaging.\n- Dispose of unused opioid medication safely \u2014 return to a pharmacy take\u2011back, community drop box, or use a drug disposal pouch. If none available, mix with unpalatable material (coffee grounds) and throw in the trash, out of reach of children/pets.\n\nWhen to call me or your PCP sooner\n- Any new rash, trouble breathing, extreme drowsiness, confusion, or worsening pain despite taking the meds; or any of the red-flag neurologic or infectious symptoms listed above.\n\nSafe trip to the pharmacy \u2014 ask the pharmacist:\n- For the hydrocodone prescription they may ask ID; confirm dosing and ask about a bowel regimen for constipation.\n- If you want, pick up an OTC stool softener (docusate) and a mild laxative (senna) to prevent opioid constipation.\n\nI\u2019m here if anything changes or if you want me to help draft a short note for the pharmacist or urgent\u2011care staff. Take care on your way to CVS, and lean on your husband for monitoring during the first doses \u2014 you did the right thing getting help."
