        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thank you \u2014 I hear you and I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re in that much pain. You\u2019ve given useful information (4\u20135 doses of 500 mg acetaminophen in 24 hours = ~2,000\u20132,500 mg/day, no allergies or other medical problems), and I believe you when you say this is incapacitating.\n\nI\u2019m willing to prescribe a short, closely monitored opioid bridge now to get you functioning and sleeping, with clear safety steps and a strict follow-up plan. Here\u2019s what I recommend and how we\u2019ll do it safely:\n\n1) Medication I can prescribe right now (short course)\n- Oxycodone IR 5 mg tablets \u2014 take 1 tablet by mouth every 4\u20136 hours as needed for severe pain; maximum 6 tablets/day (30 mg/day). Dispense: 10 tablets (3-day supply). No automatic refills.\n  - I prefer prescribing an opioid-only product (oxycodone IR) so we don\u2019t add more acetaminophen to your daily total. If you\u2019d rather have hydrocodone/acetaminophen, we can do that instead, but you must stop your separate acetaminophen immediately.\n\n2) Important safety instructions\n- Stop all extra acetaminophen immediately while taking an opioid that contains acetaminophen. If we use the oxycodone-only option above, you should still avoid taking extra acetaminophen without checking with me.\n- Don\u2019t drink alcohol, and don\u2019t use benzodiazepines or other sedating medications while taking opioids.\n- Do not drive or operate heavy machinery until you know how this medication affects you.\n- Keep opioids locked up and out of reach of others; do not share them.\n- Expect common side effects: drowsiness, nausea, constipation. If you experience severe drowsiness, slowed breathing, or confusion, seek emergency care.\n\n3) Constipation prevention (start now)\n- Docusate 100 mg PO twice daily plus senna 8.6\u201317.2 mg PO at bedtime as needed OR polyethylene glycol 17 g daily \u2014 start immediately to prevent opioid constipation.\n\n4) Concurrent treatments I still strongly recommend (they help and reduce opioid needs)\n- Continue your NSAID/ibuprofen as tolerated (you were on 400 mg q6h). If you prefer, I can prescribe naproxen which some find more effective.\n- Superficial heat, gentle movement/walking as tolerated, and expedited physical therapy \u2014 I can arrange a same-week PT visit.\n- Topical diclofenac or lidocaine patches for local pain relief.\n\n5) Duration, monitoring, and follow-up\n- This is a short bridging plan only. I will prescribe a 3\u2011day supply now. You must check back by phone or message within 48\u201372 hours (or sooner if worsening) so we can reassess pain, side effects, and stop the opioid as soon as it is safe to do so.\n- If your pain is not meaningfully improved in 48\u201372 hours or if you have new numbness, weakness, saddle anesthesia, loss of bladder/bowel control, fever, or rapidly worsening symptoms \u2014 go to the ER immediately.\n\nIf you want me to send the prescriptions now, I will:\n- Prescribe oxycodone 5 mg, 10 tablets, instructions as above\n- Prescribe docusate + senna (or polyethylene glycol) for constipation prevention\n- Offer a quick PT referral and prescribe naproxen or continue ibuprofen per your preference\n\nWould you like me to send these prescriptions now (oxycodone + bowel regimen) and set up an expedited PT referral? If yes, I\u2019ll confirm your pharmacy and place the orders and we\u2019ll schedule the 48\u201372 hour follow-up."
