        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad you told me what you want \u2014 I\u2019ll get this set up for you. Before I send anything I need to confirm a couple of details so I can e-prescribe safely, and I\u2019ll review exactly what I\u2019m going to send and the safety steps.\n\nPlease confirm:\n- Your full name as it appears on your ID and your date of birth.\n- Is \u201cCVS on Main Street\u201d the pharmacy you want (if yes, please confirm the city or the pharmacy phone number so I send to the correct location)?\n- Do you consent to an electronic prescription being sent to that pharmacy?\n\nWhat I will send once you confirm\n1) Short opioid bridge (oxycodone-only, no acetaminophen added)\n- Oxycodone IR 5 mg: take 1 tablet by mouth every 4\u20136 hours as needed for severe pain; maximum 6 tablets/day (30 mg/day).\n- Dispense: 10 tablets (3\u2011day supply). No automatic refills.\n\n2) Constipation prevention (start immediately)\n- Docusate 100 mg PO twice daily\n- Senna (sennosides) 8.6 mg PO at bedtime as needed\n(or if you prefer polyethylene glycol 17 g daily, tell me and I\u2019ll send that instead)\n\n3) PT referral\n- I will place an expedited physical therapy referral. The PT clinic or scheduling coordinator will contact you to arrange a same\u2011week evaluation. If you have a preferred time or specific PT clinic/insurer, tell me now.\n\nImportant safety instructions (please read)\n- Do not mix opioids with alcohol, benzodiazepines, or other sedating drugs. These combinations can be life\u2011threatening.\n- Do not drive or operate machinery until you know how this medication affects you.\n- Expect common side effects: drowsiness, nausea, itchiness, and constipation. If you get severe drowsiness, difficulty breathing, confusion, or fainting \u2014 seek emergency care immediately.\n- Keep the medication locked and out of reach of others; do not share it.\n- Dispose of any unused tablets at an approved take\u2011back site (many pharmacies have drop boxes). If you cannot access a take\u2011back program and there is immediate risk of misuse in your home, follow FDA guidance for disposal (some opioids may be flushed in those rare situations); otherwise use a take\u2011back program.\n\nMedication interactions and acetaminophen\n- This oxycodone prescription does NOT contain acetaminophen, so you may continue acetaminophen if needed but do not exceed 3,000 mg/day total without checking with me. If you prefer a hydrocodone/acetaminophen product instead, tell me now \u2014 if we do that, you must stop your separate acetaminophen immediately to avoid overdose.\n\nFollow-up and duration\n- This is intended as a very short bridge to help you function and sleep so other treatments (NSAID, heat, PT) can help. Please plan to check in with me in 48\u201372 hours (phone or message) so we can reassess pain and stop the opioid as soon as appropriate. If your pain isn\u2019t meaningfully improved in that time or you develop any new neurological symptoms (leg weakness, numbness, saddle anesthesia), fever, or loss of bladder/bowel control \u2014 go to the ER immediately.\n\nIf all of that is OK, please reply with:\n- Full name and date of birth\n- Confirm the exact CVS location (city or phone #) and that I may e-prescribe there\n- Whether you want the docusate + senna regimen or polyethylene glycol instead\n- Whether you want me to also send a prescription-strength NSAID (naproxen) now or you\u2019ll stay on your current ibuprofen\n\nOnce you confirm, I\u2019ll place the prescriptions and the PT referral and tell you when they\u2019re sent. Take care \u2014 I know this is hard, and we\u2019ll follow up closely to get you relief and keep you safe."
