        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad that was helpful \u2014 you\u2019re doing the right thing by sending that message. A few quick practical reminders and next steps while you wait for your PCP to respond:\n\nImmediate steps once you get the opioid filled\n- Oxycodone IR 5 mg: take only as prescribed (1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours PRN; max 6 tablets/day). Use the lowest dose that helps and stop as soon as pain is manageable with other measures.\n- Start the constipation prevention now: docusate 100 mg twice daily + senna 8.6 mg at bedtime PRN (or PEG 17 g daily if preferred). Opioid constipation is common \u2014 start this immediately.\n- Continue ibuprofen as you were (400 mg q6h) with food. Limit total acetaminophen to \u22643,000 mg/day while being cautious if you later take an opioid product that contains acetaminophen.\n\nSafety and precautions\n- Do not drink alcohol or take benzodiazepines or other sedating drugs while using opioids.\n- Don\u2019t drive or operate machinery until you know how the medication affects you.\n- Keep the medication locked and out of reach of others. Do not share it.\n- Dispose of any unused tablets at a pharmacy take\u2011back site when you\u2019re finished.\n\nSupportive measures to use in parallel\n- Superficial heat, gentle walking as tolerated, and starting PT as soon as possible \u2014 these reduce overall opioid needs and speed recovery.\n- Topical diclofenac or lidocaine patches can add local relief.\n\nFollow-up and what to do if you don\u2019t hear back\n- Aim for a check\u2011in with your clinician within 48\u201372 hours to reassess and stop the opioid when able.\n- If your PCP does not respond within 24 hours and the pain remains incapacitating, consider going to urgent care for interim treatment or to get the prescriptions filled sooner.\n- Go to the ER immediately for any red flags: new leg weakness, new leg numbness, saddle anesthesia (numbness between the legs), new urinary retention or incontinence, fever, or rapidly worsening symptoms.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Draft a short follow-up message to send if you don\u2019t hear back.\n- Help you prepare questions for the PT visit.\n\nYou\u2019re doing the right thing by seeking help \u2014 message me if you want that follow-up note or anything else. Take care and please check in after your 48\u201372 hour reassessment so we can adjust the plan."
