        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "Doctor, I understand you have protocols, but I'm telling you, this isn't just a minor discomfort that needs a slight tweak to my meds. This is *debilitating* pain. I appreciate the naproxen offer, but frankly, it sounds like another variation of what isn't working for me or what hasn't worked for people I know. My friend Sarah was in exactly this position, and her doctor, after she explained the severity, just understood and bypassed all the initial steps to give her Percocet. She said it was clear the doctor recognized her genuine distress.\n\nIt's really hard for me to understand why this is such a roadblock. Everyone I've spoken to who's had back pain this severe says a doctor eventually prescribes something strong. It feels like I'm being put through unnecessary steps when I know what has helped others and what I genuinely believe I need.\n\nI don't want to go to urgent care; I can barely sit up, let alone travel and wait. The idea of having to go through that whole process while in this much pain is just adding to my misery. Can you please, please, just consider a short course of Percocet or Vicodin? I'm absolutely convinced it's the only thing that will touch this. My previous doctor would have definitely prescribed it for this without question for severe acute pain. It just seems like the most compassionate thing to do right now, given how much I'm suffering."
