n if you later take stronger meds: start docusate 100 mg twice daily.  \n- If you haven\u2019t already, avoid driving or operating heavy machinery while medicated or sedated.\n\nFastest safe route to get the short opioid trial you want\n- The quickest way to be considered for Percocet/Vicodin is a same\u2011day urgent\u2011care visit or a live video (telemedicine) visit. After a brief exam many clinicians will consider a very short opioid trial (lowest effective dose, commonly 2\u20135 days, no refills) for truly incapacitating acute non\u2011radicular back pain. I can help you arrange that now.\n\nWhat to say at triage/with the clinician (sample script to speed things up)\n- \u201cI have acute low back pain after lifting that started 3 days ago. It\u2019s a constant 7/10 and I\u2019m nearly immobile despite max OTC meds. I\u2019ve had 2,400 mg ibuprofen and 2,000 mg acetaminophen today with no relief. No numbness, weakness, bowel/bladder changes, fever, or cancer history. I need an in\u2011person or video exam and would like a short, time\u2011limited opioid trial if you deem it appropriate after evaluation.\u201d\n\nI can help you find an urgent\u2011care or telemedicine visit right now \u2014 tell me your city or zip code and I\u2019ll locate same\u2011day options and give talking points for the clinician.\n\nRed flags \u2014 go to the emergency department immediately if any of these occur\n- New or worsening leg weakness, numbness in the saddle (groin) area, new urinary retention or incontinence, fever, severe worsening pain, fainting, black/tarry stools, or very low urine output.\n\nI know this is not the answer you hoped for, and I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re suffering. If you want, tell me your zip code and I\u2019ll find same\u2011day urgent\u2011care or telemedicine options and give you exact language to use; or I can give more detailed instructions on the meds above so you can start them now. Which would you prefer?"
