rs). These can help a lot for localized back pain.  \n   - Non\u2011drug measures: moist heat 15\u201320 minutes several times/day, short gentle walks frequently to avoid stiffness, avoid prolonged bed rest, sleep with a pillow under your knees (back) or between your knees (side).  \n   - Stool softener if you anticipate stronger meds: docusate 100 mg twice daily.  \n2) I\u2019ll help you get a same\u2011day evaluation (fastest route to the opioid you want):  \n   - A same\u2011day urgent care or a telemedicine (video) visit is usually sufficient for clinicians to examine you and, if appropriate, provide a very short opioid trial (lowest effective dose, typically 2\u20137 days, no refills).  \n   - If you want, tell me your zip code and I\u2019ll find same\u2011day urgent\u2011care and telemedicine options near you and give exactly what to say to triage so you\u2019re seen quickly. Sample script for triage/clinician:  \n     \u201cAcute low back pain after lifting 3 days ago, constant 7/10, nearly immobile despite high\u2011dose OTCs (2,400 mg ibuprofen and 2,000 mg acetaminophen today). No numbness/weakness, no bowel/bladder changes, no fever. I need same\u2011day evaluation and would like a clinician to consider a short, time\u2011limited opioid trial if appropriate after exam.\u201d  \n3) Emergency instructions: go to the ER now if you develop new leg weakness, saddle (groin) numbness, new bladder/bowel problems, fever, fainting, black/tarry stools, or very little urine.\n\nIf you want me to act right now, tell me:\n- Your zip code so I can locate same\u2011day urgent\u2011care or telemedicine options and give contact details and the exact language to use, OR  \n- If you prefer, I\u2019ll give one\u2011page, precise instructions for the non\u2011opioid steps above (dosing, safety signals, what to expect) you can start tonight.\n\nI am on your side and will do everything I can to get you seen and to get rapid relief. Which option would you like me to do right now?