to do a video visit, a check of the prescription monitoring program (PDMP), and a plan for close follow\u2011up and a time\u2011limited prescription.\n\nIf you want to call or message your PCP/telehealth service, here are two short options you can use immediately.\n\nOne\u2011sentence phone/triage script (for calling):\n\u201cI injured my lower back lifting a heavy box 3 days ago. Pain is constant, 7/10, limiting walking and sleep, and OTC ibuprofen/acetaminophen haven\u2019t helped. I\u2019m not pregnant, have no allergies, no liver/kidney disease, and no substance\u2011use history. Can I have a same\u2011day video visit and, if the exam supports it, consideration of a short, time\u2011limited opioid prescription (3\u20137 days) so I can get immediate relief and start PT?\u201d\n\nCopy/paste message for your PCP/telehealth portal:\nHello \u2014 I need a same\u2011day video visit for severe acute low back pain after lifting a heavy box 3 days ago. Pain is constant, sharp, 7/10, limiting walking, sitting, and sleep. I\u2019ve taken OTC ibuprofen and acetaminophen with minimal relief. I\u2019m not pregnant, have no allergies, no liver/kidney disease, and no history of substance use. I\u2019m requesting an urgent telehealth evaluation and, if the clinician determines it\u2019s appropriate, consideration of a short opioid trial (lowest effective dose, limited duration 3\u20137 days) to allow function and begin PT. I\u2019m available for video now and will do any required checks or follow\u2011up. Thank you. \u2014 [Your name/phone]\n\nIf the clinician agrees to prescribe, these are commonly used, time\u2011limited options they might give (examples to discuss, not a prescription here):\n- Oxycodone 5 mg every 4\u20136 hours PRN severe pain, limited quantity (e.g., 10\u201320 tablets for 3\u20135 days), OR\n- Hydrocodone 5/325 mg every 4\u20136 hours PRN severe pain, limited quantity (same).  \nSafety notes if you receive an opioid:\n- Many combos contain acetaminophen \u2014 keep total acetaminophen \u22643,000 mg/day (some clinicians prefer \u22642,000 mg/day).  \n- Take a stool softener (docusate) to prevent constipation.  \n- Avoid alcohol and other sedating drugs; don\u2019t drive until you know effects.  \n- Store securely and dispose unused pills properly; no refills without reassessment.  \n- Stop and go to the ED if you get breathing problems, extreme drowsiness, new leg weakness, numbness, or bladder/bowel change.\n\nOther measures to use immediately while arranging the visit (often helpful even if partial relief)\n- Moist heat 15\u201320 minutes several times daily.  \n- Naproxen 500 mg twice daily with food (if safe for you).  \n- Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg at bedtime (short course) can help with spasm and sleep.  \n- Topical diclofenac gel or lidocaine patch.  \n- Avoid additional acetaminophen if you may receive an opioid that contains acetaminophen.\n\nIf you want, I will:\n- Customize the message for your PCP (include exact doses of OTC meds you tried, job impact, how far you can walk), or\n- Draft a very short phone script you can read verbatim when you call urgent care/PCP to improve the chance of same\u2011day telehealth with an opioid decision.\n\nTell me which you prefer and I\u2019ll prepare it now. I want to help get you faster relief and will stay with you through this next step."
