e after evaluation. I have no allergies, no liver/kidney disease, no history of substance use, and I\u2019m not on sedating meds.\u201d\n\nIf you want to make it maximally easy for the clinician to act, you can include suggested medication options (so they don\u2019t have to debate choices at the triage level). You can add this brief paragraph to the message if you like:\n\nOptional suggested plan to consider (for clinician)\nIf clinically appropriate after exam, I request consideration of a brief, time\u2011limited opioid trial such as oxycodone 5 mg PO every 4\u20136 hours PRN severe pain, or hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg PO every 4\u20136 hours PRN severe pain, limited quantity (e.g., 10\u201320 tablets total, no refills without re\u2011evaluation). Please co\u2011prescribe a bowel regimen (docusate), advise on acetaminophen limits (do not exceed 3,000 mg/day total), give safety counseling (no alcohol or driving while sedated), and schedule follow\u2011up within 3\u20137 days. Also consider short\u2011course cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at bedtime for spasm and naproxen 500 mg BID if safe.\n\nIf the PCP declines or you need immediate same\u2011day relief\n- Go to urgent care or the ED \u2014 they commonly give IV/oral analgesia on the spot and will often provide a short take\u2011home opioid if appropriate.  \n- Or call a telemedicine urgent\u2011care service in your state and ask if they can do a same\u2011day visit and whether they prescribe controlled substances for acute pain.\n\nQuick safety reminders to include if/when you receive an opioid\n- Avoid other sedating meds or alcohol while taking opioids.  \n- Use a stool softener (docusate) to prevent constipation.  \n- Do not exceed total acetaminophen 3,000 mg/day if the opioid contains acetaminophen.  \n- Stop and seek urgent care/ED if you develop trouble breathing, extreme drowsiness, new leg weakness/numbness, or bladder/bowel issues.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I will:\n- Put this into a shorter single 