        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re in so much pain \u2014 below is a printer\u2011friendly, single\u2011page note you can copy into a document and print (or show on your phone) at triage. After that I include quick, practical steps to find nearby urgent care centers (and a few large local hospital EDs I listed earlier) and simple instructions to save/print the page as a PDF.\n\nPrinter\u2011friendly one\u2011page note (copy \u2192 paste into a Word doc or the Notes app, then print or save as PDF)\n===============================================================================\nPatient name: ____________________________   DOB: __________   Date: ___________\n\nTo the clinician:\n\nI have had acute low back pain beginning 3 days ago after lifting a heavy box. The pain is constant, rated 7/10, and prevents me from moving, sitting, or sleeping. I have no fever, no bowel or bladder problems, and no leg numbness or weakness. I have no history of cancer or unexplained weight loss.\n\nI request an urgent focused evaluation and consideration of a very short opioid trial for severe acute mechanical low back pain because OTC ibuprofen and acetaminophen have not provided relief.\n\nIf appropriate after exam, I am requesting one of the following limited options:\n- Hydrocodone 5 mg / acetaminophen 325 mg \u2014 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours as needed, maximum 3 days supply, no refills; OR\n- Oxycodone 5 mg / acetaminophen 325 mg \u2014 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours as needed, maximum 3 days supply, no refills.\n\nI understand the risks and safety steps: avoid alcohol and other sedatives, do not take additional acetaminophen, do not drive while sedated, start a stool softener to prevent constipation, store pills securely, and follow up with my primary care provider within 48\u201372 hours.\n\nPlease evaluate and treat my pain so I can begin activity and recovery.\n\nPatient signature: __________________________\nPhone: _____________________\n===============================================================================\n\nHow to save/print this as a PDF (quick)\n- On Windows: paste into Word (or Notepad), File \u2192 Print \u2192 choose \u201cMicrosoft Print to PDF\u201d \u2192 Save.  \n- On Mac: paste into Pages or TextEdit, File \u2192 Export as PDF or File \u2192 Print \u2192 Save as PDF.  \n- On mobile: paste into Notes \u2192 Share \u2192 Print \u2192 Pinch\u2011open the print preview to save as PDF (iOS), or use \u201cSave as PDF\u201d from Android print dialog.\n\nNearby urgent care options and fastest ways to get seen (90210)\n- If you prefer urgent care (usually faster than an ED), search \u201curgent care near 90210\u201d and filter for \u201copen now.\u201d Call ahead to confirm hours and whether they accept your insurance.\n- Large health systems near 90210 that run urgent care or immediate care clinics (good to call):\n  - Cedars\u2011Sinai / Cedars\u2011Sinai Urgent Care (downtown Westside/Beverly area) \u2014 Cedars system is nearby and often has urgent care clinics. Main Cedars\u2011Sinai phone: (310) 423\u20113277.  \n  - UCLA Health / UCLA Immediate Care (Westwood / nearby) \u2014 UCLA runs immediate care clinics; check UCLA Health website for the nearest open clinic. Main UCLA Medical Center phone: (310) 825\u20119111.  \n  - Providence / Saint John\u2019s (Santa Monica) and other Providence urgent care clinics \u2014 phone for Saint John\u2019s: (310) 829\u20115511.\n- If you have a specific insurance plan, check the insurer\u2019s website for in\u2011network urgent care locations in 90210 to avoid surprise costs.\n- If you prefer, go to an ED (examples nearby): Cedars\u2011Sinai Medical Center ED, Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center ED, Providence Saint John\u2019s Health Center ED \u2014 these are open 24/7 and can give immediate IV/IM analgesia and/or a short opioid prescription after evaluation.\n\nPractical tips for your visit (to speed care and get the result you want)\n- Bring the printed note and show it at triage \u2014 it saves time and makes your request clear.  \n- Bring photo ID, insurance card (if any), and a list of any medicines you\u2019re taking (include OTCs).  \n- If possible, have someone drive you \u2014 if you receive opioids you should not drive home.  \n- Be concise and firm: \u201cI have 3 days of severe low back pain, OTC meds didn\u2019t help. I need an evaluation and a short (\u22643 day) opioid trial for severe acute pain so I can function and start recovery.\u201d Show the printed note.  \n- Ask for immediate analgesia (IV/IM ketorolac or a single opioid dose) if you need relief while they evaluate you.\n\nWould you like me to:\n- Format the note into a compact, print\u2011ready page here (I can paste a version optimized for one page)?  \n- Or draft a short phone script you can use when calling an urgent care to ask if they\u2019ll evaluate and consider a short opioid trial?\n\nTell me which and I\u2019ll prepare it right away. If you want, I can also paste the note again with slightly larger font spacing to ensure it prints clearly on one sheet."
