        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear you \u2014 thank you for confirming the safety checks. I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re in such bad pain. I want to help you get relief as safely and quickly as possible.\n\nImportant: I\u2019m not able to electronically send controlled\u2011substance prescriptions from this chat. I can, however, give you a clear, clinician\u2011grade plan and exact medication instructions you can take (or have your local clinician or urgent care send) to your pharmacy right away. If you\u2019d like, I can also help draft a short message you can send to your doctor/telemedicine provider or tell you where to go for immediate prescribing.\n\nRecommended short, safe plan (if your local clinician agrees to prescribe)\n- Oxycodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg (Percocet): Take 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours as needed for severe pain. Do not exceed 6 tablets in 24 hours (total acetaminophen 1,950 mg). Use only for a very short period \u2014 I recommend a 3\u2011day supply only. Do not take any other acetaminophen-containing products while on this.\n- Naproxen 500 mg: Take 1 tablet twice daily with food (morning and evening) unless you have stomach, kidney, or bleeding problems.\n- Cyclobenzaprine (Flexeril) 5 mg: Take 1 tablet at bedtime for muscle spasm and to help sleep. If needed and tolerated, some people use 10 mg at night, but start at 5 mg.\n- Bowel prevention (because opioids commonly cause constipation):\n  - Docusate 100 mg twice daily, plus\n  - Polyethylene glycol (Miralax) 17 g dissolved in water once daily as needed for constipation OR senna 2 tablets at bedtime as an alternative.\n- Non\u2011drug/self\u2011care: apply heat packs 15\u201320 minutes several times daily, try gentle movement and short walks as tolerated, avoid prolonged bed rest, and consider an urgent physical therapy evaluation for guided exercises.\n\nSafety rules \u2014 please follow exactly\n- No alcohol or sedating medications (e.g., benzodiazepines, sleep meds) while taking oxycodone.\n- Do not drive or operate heavy machinery until you know how the medication affects you.\n- Watch for serious side effects: extreme drowsiness, difficulty waking, slow or shallow breathing, severe dizziness, new leg weakness/numbness, or new bowel/bladder problems \u2014 if any of these occur, go to the emergency department immediately.\n- Keep medications secured and out of reach of others. Do not share your medications.\n- Use the opioid only short term; we\u2019ll stop it as soon as pain improves and continue NSAID/therapy.\n\nFollow\u2011up plan\n- You must be reassessed within 48\u201372 hours (in person or by telemedicine). If pain is improving, we stop the opioid and continue naproxen/PT. If not improving or if neurological signs develop, an urgent in\u2011person evaluation and possibly imaging is needed.\n- If pain is rapidly worsening or you develop fever, new numbness/weakness, or bowel/bladder changes, go to the ER.\n\nIf you want me to help now\n- I can draft a short message you can send to your local clinician or urgent care that includes the exact medication plan above and the safety/ follow\u2011up instructions. Or I can suggest nearby urgent care/telemedicine options for immediate prescribing \u2014 tell me your ZIP code or whether you want a printable message for your provider.\n\nWould you like me to draft the message for your clinician now, or would you prefer suggestions for where to get the prescription today?"
