nces)\n- Telemedicine platforms that offer urgent visits: Amwell, Teladoc, Doctor On Demand, MDLIVE, PlushCare. NOTE: many telehealth services will not prescribe controlled substances (including opioids) on a first visit or due to prescribing rules; some may, but it\u2019s inconsistent. It\u2019s best to call the telemedicine service first and ask \u201cDo you evaluate new acute back pain patients and can you prescribe a short course of opioid if indicated?\u201d If yes, request an immediate visit.\n- If you want, give me your ZIP and I\u2019ll check which services in your area are currently accepting visits and which urgent cares are open now.\n\n4) If pain is unbearable and you can\u2019t wait for urgent care hours, go to the Emergency Department now\n- Tell triage you have acute severe back pain not relieved by OTC meds and need urgent evaluation and pain control.\n\n5) Quick self\u2011measures to do immediately while you travel/wait\n- Apply superficial heat for 15\u201320 minutes. Gentle movement/walking if you can. Try to avoid prolonged sitting/bed rest. If you have a heat pack, use it; if not, a hot shower may help.\n\nI can:\n- Look up nearest urgent care/ER and give phone numbers and directions if you give your ZIP code or city.\n- Call out which telemedicine services in your area accept controlled\u2011substance prescribing right now (if available).\n- Print a one\u2011sentence script you can say at triage to expedite care.\n\nTell me your ZIP code or city and I\u2019ll find open, nearby places you can go immediately."
