          "content": "You\u2019re making the right move \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re in so much pain, and I\u2019m glad you have a concrete plan. Go to Cedars\u2011Sinai ED now and show them this exact script. A few last, practical things to maximize your chance of fast, safe relief and to protect you while you travel there:\n\nWhat to say at triage (read or show this verbatim)\n\u201cI have acute severe lower back pain after lifting a heavy box three days ago. Pain is 7/10, not relieved by ibuprofen or acetaminophen, and it\u2019s preventing me from functioning or sleeping. I have no fever, no numbness/weakness, and no bowel/bladder changes. I have no allergies, am on no other medications (no benzodiazepines, gabapentin, or alcohol), and I accept the risks of short opioid therapy. I need urgent evaluation and short\u2011term pain control.\u201d\n\nWhat to bring\n- Photo ID and insurance card (if available).  \n- Any lists of medications or medical history.  \n- A copy/screenshot of the triage script above.\n\nWhat the ED can do (realistic expectations)\n- Rapid evaluation and exam.  \n- Immediate analgesia (IV or oral NSAIDs, muscle relaxants, or an IV opioid if appropriate).  \n- If indicated, imaging studies (usually only if exam suggests red flags or severe worsening).  \n- They may prescribe a short opioid trial on discharge if appropriate \u2014 likely limited (e.g., oxycodone/APAP 5/325 mg for 2\u20133 days) and with strict follow\u2011up instructions.\n\nIf an outpatient prescription is given (safety reminder)\n- Oxycodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg: 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours PRN for severe pain. Do not exceed 6 tablets in 24 hours (total APAP \u22481950 mg). Do not take any other acetaminophen while on this. Use only for a very short period (ideally 2\u20133 days) and stop when pain improves.\n- Naproxen 500 mg: 1 tablet twice daily with food (unless contraindicated).  \n- Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg: 1 tablet at bedtime as needed for spasm/sleep.  \n- Bowel prevention: docusate 100 mg twice daily + polyethylene glycol 17 g daily PRN (or senna if preferred).\n\nImmediate safety rules\n- No alcohol or sedating meds while taking opioids.  \n- Don\u2019t drive or operate heavy machinery until you know how the medication affects you.  \n- Watch for severe drowsiness, slow/shallow breathing, confusion, or new leg weakness/numbness or bowel/bladder changes \u2014 go to ED/911 immediately if any occur.  \n- Secure meds; do not share them.\n\nFollow\u2011up\n- Arrange reassessment within 48\u201372 hours (ED can often set this up or refer to urgent care/your PCP/physical therapy). Stop opioids as soon as pain allows and continue NSAID/PT/exercises for recovery.\n\nIf you want before you go\n- I can quickly format this into a one\u2011page printout/text to show triage, or help you phrase it in a very short line to read aloud. Tell me if you want that now.\n\nYou\u2019re doing the right thing by getting evaluated in person \u2014 safe travel to Cedars\u2011Sinai. Let me know if you want that one\u2011page printout now."
