        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re dealing with this level of back pain. Thanks for the clear details \u2014 that helps a lot. A few quick questions so I can make safe recommendations:\n- Any allergies to medications?\n- Any medical problems (stomach ulcers, kidney disease, high blood pressure, heart disease, liver disease, glaucoma) or current prescriptions (especially blood thinners, SSRIs/SNRIs, or MAO inhibitors)?\n- Any prior episodes of back pain or recent pregnancy?\n\nWhat I\u2019m thinking and recommending now\n- Your history (acute onset lifting, no red-flag symptoms like fever, bowel/bladder problems, progressive neurologic loss, or cancer history) fits acute non\u2011radicular low back pain. Routine imaging and opioids are not recommended right now.\n- Opioids such as Percocet or Vicodin are generally avoided for this situation because they\u2019re usually not more helpful long term, carry significant side effects and addiction risk, and aren\u2019t first-line for nonradicular low back pain.\n\nSafe and effective next steps you can start today\n1. Non\u2011drug measures (often helpful)\n   - Superficial heat (heating pad) to the low back for 15\u201320 minutes several times daily.\n   - Gradual activity as tolerated \u2014 avoid prolonged bed rest. Gentle walking and light stretching.\n   - Consider massage or spinal manipulation if you have access to a trusted provider.\n2. Pharmacologic options (if no contraindications)\n   - A prescription NSAID is reasonable: naproxen 500 mg PO initially then 500 mg every 12 hours with food (or ibuprofen prescription-strength). Use shortest effective course (often 7\u201314 days).\n   - If muscle spasm is prominent, a short course of a muscle relaxant (e.g., cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at night) can help sleep and reduce spasm for several days up to 2 weeks.\n   - Topical NSAID gel (diclofenac) over the painful area can add benefit with lower systemic risk.\n3. If pain doesn\u2019t improve\n   - If you\u2019re not noticeably better in about 2 weeks, or if pain is limiting function a lot, we can arrange physical therapy and reconsider options.\n   - Imaging (X\u2011ray/MRI) is usually not needed unless red flags develop or symptoms persist/worsen.\n\nWhen to seek urgent care or come in sooner\n- New weakness or numbness in legs, trouble walking\n- New bladder or bowel incontinence\n- Fever, unexplained weight loss, or severe unrelenting night pain\n- Worsening pain despite the above measures\n\nIf you confirm no allergies or contraindications and tell me your current meds/medical history, I can suggest specific drug(s) and doses and send a prescription if appropriate. I understand wanting stronger relief \u2014 we can use the measures above and reassess quickly to keep you safe and get you moving more comfortably."
