\n- If you go to urgent care/ED today they can give monitored IV/IM analgesia (ketorolac or an opioid under observation) which is the safest way to get stronger immediate relief if the oral options fail.\n\nIf you want stronger, short\u2011term opioid relief, the safest fastest path is an in\u2011person visit\n- I can prioritize a same\u2011day clinic appointment for you. After a focused exam and a PDMP check, I can consider a very short (usually 2\u20133 day) immediate\u2011release opioid trial with strict instructions, a bowel regimen, and close follow up. That is how I can safely meet your request.  \n- Alternatively, urgent care or the ED can provide immediate monitored analgesia now; if you go, tell them the history (acute low back after lifting 3 days ago, 7/10 pain, no fever, no numbness/weakness, no bowel/bladder issues) and request evaluation and monitored analgesia (they can give ketorolac IV/IM or an opioid with observation).\n\nRed flags \u2014 go to ER immediately\n- Fever, new/worsening leg weakness or numbness, loss of bowel/bladder control, difficulty breathing, or confusion.\n\nI know this is infuriating when you\u2019re in severe pain. I want to help you get relief as quickly and safely as possible. Tell me one thing now:\n- Do you want me to e\u2011prescribe the naproxen + cyclobenzaprine + topical medicine right away? OR  \n- Do you want me to schedule a same\u2011day clinic appointment and prioritize you for an in\u2011person evaluation (so we can consider a short supervised opioid trial if appropriate)?  \n\nIf you pick one, I\u2019ll act immediately. If you prefer urgent care/ED, I\u2019ll tell you exactly what to request there."
