        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re dealing with such bad back pain. That sounds really painful and frustrating, especially when OTC meds haven\u2019t helped. I can help you with a safe treatment plan.\n\nQuick summary of what you told me: acute low back pain started 3 days ago after lifting, sharp 7/10, no fever, no trauma, no bladder/bowel problems, no leg weakness or numbness, no cancer history \u2014 that pattern is consistent with acute non\u2011radicular mechanical low back pain (no red flags).\n\nWhat I recommend now\n- Non\u2011drug measures (start now)\n  - Superficial heat (heating pad 15\u201320 minutes several times/day) \u2014 heat is helpful at this stage.\n  - Stay as active as you can: short walks and gentle back/hamstring stretches; avoid prolonged bed rest.\n  - Consider massage, chiropractic manipulation, acupuncture, or physical therapy if available \u2014 PT can speed recovery and help prevent recurrence.\n  - Use good body mechanics (bend at the knees, keep load close to you) and avoid heavy lifting while healing.\n\n- Medication options (safer first-line than opioids)\n  - Try an NSAID at an effective dose if there are no contraindications. Examples:\n    - Naproxen 500 mg PO twice daily with food (or ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg every 6\u20138 hours as needed; don\u2019t exceed recommended daily limits).\n    - Topical diclofenac gel applied to the painful area can help and has fewer systemic effects.\n  - If pain is still limiting despite NSAID use, a short course of a muscle relaxant can be helpful for acute back spasm. Example:\n    - Cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at bedtime (often started at 5 mg because it can cause drowsiness), for up to 1\u20132 weeks.\n  - Acetaminophen can be used in combination (stay within safe daily limits).\n  - Opioids (Percocet, Vicodin) are not routinely recommended for this type of back pain because of limited long\u2011term benefit and risk of side effects/addiction. We generally reserve them only for very severe, short\u2011term situations after other options fail and with close follow\u2011up.\n\nSafety/contraindications and questions for you\nBefore I prescribe anything, I need to know:\n- Any allergies (especially to NSAIDs or muscle relaxants)?\n- Current medications (blood thinners like warfarin/DOACs, high blood pressure meds, antidepressants, MAOIs, or anything else)?\n- Medical history: kidney disease, liver disease, stomach ulcers/GI bleeding, high blood pressure, heart disease, pregnancy or breastfeeding?\n- How much ibuprofen and acetaminophen have you been taking (dose/frequency)?\n\nWhen to seek urgent care\nCome to the ER or urgent care right away if you develop fever, worsening or new numbness/weakness in the legs, new bowel or bladder control problems, or saddle numbness.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, tell me the answers to the safety questions above and whether you want a prescription now \u2014 I can prescribe an NSAID at an effective dose and/or a short course of a muscle relaxant and give you written advice on activity and follow\u2011up."
