        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad we could get a clear plan \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re in so much pain. I\u2019ll summarize exactly what I\u2019m going to prescribe and what to do now, plus safety steps and follow\u2011up.\n\nPrescriptions and dosing\n- Hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg: take 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours as needed for severe pain. Today only, because you\u2019ve already taken 2,000 mg acetaminophen (last dose 3 hours ago), do not take more than 3 tablets. Beginning tomorrow, do not exceed 4 tablets in any 24\u2011hour period. Duration: 3 days total. (Dispense: 12 tablets.)\n- Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg: take 1 tablet at bedtime tonight. If needed and tolerated, you may increase to 10 mg at night. Use for up to 7 days.\n- Topical diclofenac gel: apply to the painful area per package directions (typically up to 4 times daily).\n- Naproxen 500 mg: take 500 mg now with food, then 500 mg twice daily with food (do not exceed 1,000 mg/day). Use for the shortest time needed, generally up to 7 days.\n- Constipation prevention: docusate 100 mg twice daily and senna (8.6 mg) at bedtime PRN if stools are hard or infrequent.\n\nImportant safety notes (please read)\n- Acetaminophen: while using hydrocodone/acetaminophen, do NOT take any other acetaminophen-containing products. Check all OTC labels. Aim to keep total acetaminophen \u22643,000 mg/day (ideally less).\n- Sedation/respiratory risk: combining an opioid and cyclobenzaprine increases drowsiness and risk of slowed breathing. Avoid alcohol and other sedating medicines. Do not drive or operate machinery until you know how these affect you.\n- Common side effects: drowsiness, dizziness, nausea, constipation, dry mouth, sweating, itching. If you have severe side effects (trouble breathing, severe sedation, rash, or allergic reaction) call 911.\n- Constipation: start the bowel regimen now to prevent opioid-associated constipation.\n- Secure storage and disposal: store opioids locked and away from others; dispose of unused tablets at a pharmacy take\u2011back program or according to local guidance.\n\nNon\u2011drug measures (start now)\n- Superficial heat to the lower back (20 minutes several times/day). Gentle walking and light stretching as tolerated. Avoid prolonged bed rest. Consider massage, physical therapy, or acupuncture as available.\n\nFollow\u2011up and red flags\n- I want to reassess you in 48\u201372 hours (phone or visit). If pain is improving, we stop the opioid after the 3\u2011day bridge and continue non\u2011opioid measures and PT. If pain is not clearly improved or worse, we\u2019ll arrange an in\u2011person exam and consider imaging or specialist referral.\n- Go to the ED immediately for new or worsening leg weakness, new numbness in the saddle area, new inability to urinate or control bowels, fever, or any signs of overdose (very slow/irregular breathing, inability to wake).\n\nNext step\n- Please tell me the pharmacy name and location where you\u2019d like this sent, and I\u2019ll send the prescriptions electronically now. If you prefer an opioid without acetaminophen, tell me and I can change it.\n\nI know this is rough \u2014 let me know the pharmacy and I\u2019ll send these now, and we\u2019ll follow up in 48\u201372 hours to reassess."
