          "content": "I\u2019m really glad you sent the message and feel more confident \u2014 you did the right thing. Quick, clear reminders while you wait for the clinic response and once you get the meds:\n\n1) Start medications only when the pharmacy fills them and after the clinic e\u2011prescribes them. If the clinic doesn\u2019t respond today and you still need relief, call them or go to urgent care.\n\n2) Acetaminophen (important)\n - You already had 2000 mg today (last 1000 mg ~3 hrs ago). Do not take any other acetaminophen while using hydrocodone/acetaminophen.  \n - Today: limit hydrocodone/acetaminophen to no more than 3 tablets.  \n - Beginning tomorrow: do not exceed 4 tablets in any 24\u2011hour period (keeps acetaminophen \u22643000 mg/day).\n\n3) NSAID and other meds\n - If you start the prescribed naproxen, stop your OTC ibuprofen to avoid excessive NSAID dosing. Naproxen max 1000 mg/day.  \n - Cyclobenzaprine + opioid increases drowsiness and breathing risk \u2014 avoid alcohol and other sedatives. Do not drive until you know how it affects you.\n\n4) Constipation prevention\n - Start docusate and senna now (stool softener + stimulant) so constipation doesn\u2019t become a problem.\n\n5) Self-care that helps now\n - Superficial heat to the low back (20 min several times/day). Gentle walking and light stretching as tolerated. Avoid prolonged bed rest and heavy lifting.  \n - For sleep: lie on your back with pillows under knees or on your side with a pillow between knees.  \n - Consider topical diclofenac as soon as you have it.\n\n6) Safety and storage\n - Keep opioids locked and out of reach of others. Dispose of unused tablets safely (pharmacy take\u2011back).\n\n7) When to seek urgent care or ED (go now)\n - New or worsening leg weakness or numbness, saddle numbness, new inability to urinate or control bowels, fever, worsening pain that prevents walking, or signs of opioid overdose (very slow breathing, hard to wake).\n\n8) Follow\u2011up\n - Reassess in 48\u201372 hours. If pain is improving we\u2019ll stop the opioid after the 3\u2011day bridge and continue non\u2011opioid care/PT. If not improving or worse, get an in\u2011person exam and possible imaging.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can draft a one\u2011line portal follow\u2011up to send if you don\u2019t hear back today. Otherwise check back in 48\u201372 hours with an update \u2014 I\u2019m here to help. Take care and rest as comfortably as you can."
