depending on local laws and clinic policy. Call your PCP or telemedicine provider and ask whether controlled opioids can be prescribed via a same\u2011day video visit in your state.\n\n4) Mobile urgent care / house\u2011call service\n   - In many areas there are mobile urgent care or house\u2011call services that will come to you and can provide injections and prescriptions after an exam.\n\nWhat to say \u2014 exact wording that speeds triage (use if you call/arrive)\n\u201cI have 3 days of severe, constant low\u2011back pain (7/10) after lifting a heavy box. Pain is across the low back with no leg radiation, no numbness, no bowel/bladder problems. I\u2019ve taken near\u2011maximum OTC ibuprofen and acetaminophen with no relief and I\u2019m functionally limited and unable to sleep. I need immediate in\u2011person (or same\u2011day video) evaluation and effective short\u2011term pain control so I can rest and recover. Please consider IM/IV ketorolac or a trigger\u2011point injection now, and if those fail, evaluate whether a short opioid prescription is appropriate.\u201d\n\nIf you want, I can draft a one\u2011paragraph printable note with that wording right now \u2014 clinicians read that and often triage faster. I know you said you don\u2019t want a note, but it usually shortens the visit and reduces the physical burden of telling your story multiple times.\n\nWhat you can reasonably expect in\u2011person\n- Often urgent care/ED will give IM/IV ketorolac or a local injection and substantial pain relief follows. If not, after exam they may provide a limited opioid (lowest effective dose for the shortest time, often 1\u20133 days) with clear instructions and follow\u2011up.\n\nImmediate measures to help while you arrange care\n- If you are near the acetaminophen max, stop more acetaminophen tonight (do not exceed 3,000\u20134,000 mg/day; less if you drink alcohol).\n- Use moist heat 15\u201320 minutes, avoid lying perfectly still all day, and change positions periodically.\n- If you truly cannot get out tonight and want something to try that many clinicians commonly use post\u2011examination, I can explain cyclobenzaprine dosing (5\u201310 mg at bedtime or 5 mg TID) and precautions \u2014 it often helps spasm and sleep. Tell me if you want that info now.\n\nIf you do get an opioid in person \u2014 safety points\n- Use the lowest dose for the shortest time (ideally \u22643 days).\n- Avoid alcohol, driving, and other sedating medicines while taking it.\n- Start a bowel regimen (stool softener + laxative) if prescribed opioids.\n\nI want to help you get relief as quickly as possible. Tell me which of these you want me to do right now:\n- Draft the concise printable note you can bring or read to urgent care/ED,\n- Prepare a short phone script to request a same\u2011day video visit or urgent care appointment,\n- Give cyclobenzaprine dosing/precautions for tonight if you can\u2019t get care immediately.\n\nI\u2019ll prepare whichever you choose immediately."
