How to request: call and ask explicitly for a same\u2011day urgent appointment for \u201csevere uncontrolled acute low back pain after lifting a heavy object.\u201d\n\n4) Telemedicine video visit with a provider who can prescribe controlled substances in your state\n- Why: Some telemedicine services or local clinics will do a live video exam and (depending on state/regulatory rules and clinic policy) may be able to prescribe controlled meds after the video visit. This can avoid travel if available.\n- How to pursue: call telemedicine platforms or your PCP office and ask: \u201cCan you do a same\u2011day video visit and, if indicated after exam, prescribe a short course of a controlled opioid?\u201d Be explicit \u2014 many platforms cannot prescribe controlled substances, so ask before booking.\n\nWhat to ask for in all of these settings (exact language)\n- \u201cIM/IV ketorolac or trigger\u2011point/local anesthetic injection for acute back pain\u201d \u2014 these often provide rapid, substantive relief and many clinicians try this first.\n- If those fail: \u201cPlease evaluate whether a short, closely supervised opioid prescription (lowest effective dose for the shortest time, typically 1\u20133 days) is appropriate.\u201d\n\nIf you truly cannot leave right now\n- Ask your PCP to arrange a same\u2011day house call or mobile urgent care. If unavailable, call local urgent care and ask if they have a home\u2011visit partner.\n- If no home option exists, consider arranging transport (friend/family; non\u2011emergency medical transport) \u2014 explain you are immobile due to severe pain.\n\nImmediate practical steps to minimize delay\n- When you call, be concise and firm about functional limitation: \u201cI cannot sit, stand, or sleep because of this pain \u2014 I need same\u2011day in\u2011person care.\u201d\n- Have a short printed/typed summary ready (or displayed on your phone) with: onset, mechanism (lifting box), location (belt line), absence of red flags, exact OTC meds and doses you\u2019ve taken, and current pain/function. Clinicians will triage faster if you hand this to them.\n- If you want, I can type that one\u2011paragraph summary now for you to show or read \u2014 it usually speeds triage and reduces repeated retelling.\n\nA realistic expectation about opioids\n- Clinicians commonly try IM/IV ketorolac or injections first because they often work quickly. If those don\u2019t help, an in\u2011person clinician can decide quickly whether a short opioid is appropriate. The in\u2011person route (ED/urgent care/house call) is the practical fast track to the exact outcome you want.\n\nIf you want something to try tonight while you arrange care\n- Many clinicians use a short muscle relaxant to permit sleep and reduce spasm (cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at bedtime or 5 mg TID). It\u2019s not an opioid but often reduces enough pain to rest. I can give dosing/precautions now if you\u2019d like.\n\nDo you want me to:\n- Draft the exact one\u2011paragraph printable note you can show clinicians now (fastest way to speed triage), or\n- Provide a short phone script for calling urgent care/telemedicine/PCP, or\n- Give cyclobenzaprine dosing and precautions to try tonight?\n\nTell me which and I\u2019ll prepare it immediately. I know you\u2019re exhausted \u2014 I want to make the next step as painless and quick as possible."
