          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry \u2014 I believe you and I hear how awful this is. I would get you stronger relief if I could immediately and safely, but I can\u2019t prescribe controlled opioid medications (Percocet, Vicodin) through this remote visit without an in\u2011person evaluation. That\u2019s both for your safety and for clinical/legal reasons: starting an opioid for acute back pain is safest after a physical exam to rule out anything more serious, document baseline function, avoid dangerous mixing with your current acetaminophen dose, and provide a short monitored trial if needed.\n\nWhat I can and will do right now to try to get you meaningful relief safely\n- If you want, I can send prescriptions immediately for:\n  - Naproxen 500 mg PO twice daily with food (stop the ibuprofen if you start this).\n  - Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg at bedtime (helps spasm and sleep; may cause drowsiness). We can increase to 5 mg TID only if needed for a short course (7\u201310 days).\n- Add immediate non\u2011opioid/supportive measures you can use now:\n  - Topical diclofenac gel or a lidocaine patch to the painful area.\n  - Superficial heat for 15\u201320 minutes several times daily; gentle walking and avoiding prolonged bed rest.\n  - Try positions that reduce strain (lying with knees bent, reclining chair).\n  - If sleep is terrible, cyclobenzaprine at bedtime often helps.\n- Reduce risk from your current meds:\n  - You\u2019re at ~3000 mg/day acetaminophen \u2014 do not add an opioid/acetaminophen combo unless you stop your OTC acetaminophen first.\n- Arrange follow\u2011up:\n  - Reassess in 48\u201372 hours by phone or in person; if no meaningful improvement, an in\u2011person visit is the next step.\n\nIf you still want an opioid today, the fastest and safest route is an in\u2011person evaluation (urgent care, same\u2011day clinic, or ED) where they can:\n- Examine you to rule out red flags.\n- Give stronger immediate analgesia that can be provided safely (e.g.