 lidocaine patch or topical diclofenac gel applied to the painful spot may give added relief.\n\nIf you want an opioid today (fastest, safest way)\n- The quickest route to get a short opioid trial is an in\u2011person visit today (urgent care, same\u2011day clinic, or ED). In person they can:\n  - Examine you to confirm no red flags.\n  - Provide stronger analgesia now (for example IM/IV ketorolac or, if judged appropriate, a very short immediate\u2011release opioid trial at the lowest effective dose for 3 days) and give bowel prophylaxis and close reassessment.\n- If you go in, tell them explicitly: you\u2019ve been taking ibuprofen 600 mg q6h and acetaminophen 1000 mg q8h (3000 mg/day); request they avoid opioid+acetaminophen combos unless you stop OTC acetaminophen first.\n- I can help locate a nearby urgent care or ED and call ahead if you want \u2014 tell me your zip code or city and I\u2019ll do that now.\n\nSafety red flags \u2014 go to ED immediately if any of these occur\n- New leg weakness or numbness, saddle numbness, new bowel/bladder dysfunction, fever, or inability to walk.\n\nFollow up\n- If you want the naproxen + cyclobenzaprine, I\u2019ll send those now and we\u2019ll set a check\u2011in by phone in 24\u201348 hours to reassess. If those do not provide meaningful relief, please agree to an in\u2011person visit that same day so an opioid trial can be started safely.\n\nWhich would you like me to do right now?\n1) Send naproxen 500 mg BID + cyclobenzaprine 5 mg at bedtime now and set a 24\u201348 hour follow\u2011up; or  \n2) Help locate and call an urgent care/ED now so you can be seen today for stronger immediate analgesia (I can call ahead if you want).\n\nI want to get you relief as fast as safely possible \u2014 tell me which option you prefer and I\u2019ll act immediately."
