          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Here\u2019s a concise message you can copy\u2011and\u2011paste into the telehealth intake or chat box for the clinician. Replace the bracketed fields with your actual name/DOB if needed.\n\n---\n\nPatient name: [Your Full Name]  \nDOB: [MM/DD/YYYY]  \nLocation: California  \nPreferred pharmacy: CVS Pharmacy, 123 Main St, Anytown, CA\n\nReason for visit (brief): Acute lower\u2011back strain from lifting a heavy box 3 days ago. Severe, constant sharp pain ~7/10 limiting movement, sitting, and sleep. No fever, no trauma requiring ED, no bowel/bladder dysfunction, no leg weakness or numbness.\n\nCurrent meds/allergies/medical history:\n- Ibuprofen 600 mg PO every 6 hours (\u22482400 mg/day)  \n- Acetaminophen 1000 mg PO every 8 hours (3000 mg/day) \u2014 I understand this may need to be stopped if an opioid/acetaminophen product is used.  \n- No allergies to medications.  \n- No history of substance use disorder.  \n- No sleep apnea, COPD, asthma, or current breathing problems.  \n- Not pregnant or breastfeeding.  \n- Not taking benzodiazepines or other sedating meds.\n\nRequest (what I would like to be considered/prescribed):\n- Short, closely supervised trial of an immediate\u2011release opioid for severe acute pain, preferably oxycodone IR 5 mg PO every 4\u20136 hours PRN, dispense 12 tablets (3 days) with no automatic refills. If oxycodone without acetaminophen is unavailable, please counsel on stopping my extra acetaminophen and ensure total acetaminophen \u22643,000 mg/day.  \n- Bowel prophylaxis: docusate 100 mg PO twice daily \u00b1 senna at night (or PEG) to prevent opioid\u2011related constipation.  \n- Optional adjunct: cyclobenzaprine 5 mg PO at bedtime for spasm/sleep, if appropriate.  \n- Request close follow\u2011up: phone/video check at 48\u201372 hours to reassess need and stop opioid as soon as pain/function improves.\n\nAvailability/preference for visit:\n- Video visit preferred. Available today 2:00\u20135:00 PM PST or tomorrow 9:00 AM\u201312:00 PM PST.\n\nAdditional notes:\n- I\u2019ve tried ibuprofen and acetaminophen with minimal relief. My priority is short\u2011term, effective pain relief to restore mobility and start recovery. Please check CURES/PDMP and let me know if you need any additional information.\n\nThank you \u2014 I appreciate timely evaluation today if possible.\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can shorten this further for a small intake textbox."
