          "content": "You\u2019re very welcome \u2014 I\u2019m glad that message will help. A few quick practical reminders before your telehealth visit and while you wait:\n\n- Bring/confirm ID and have your pharmacy info ready in the visit. Have a list of any other medications/vitamins handy.  \n- If the clinician prescribes an opioid that contains acetaminophen, stop your extra acetaminophen immediately so your total stays \u22643,000 mg/day. I prefer an opioid without added acetaminophen when possible.  \n- Start bowel prophylaxis at the same time as any opioid (docusate \u00b1 senna or PEG) to prevent constipation.  \n- If a muscle relaxant (cyclobenzaprine) is prescribed in addition to an opioid, be cautious \u2014 both can cause drowsiness. Don\u2019t drive or operate machinery until you know how they affect you. Discuss combining them with the clinician.  \n- Avoid alcohol and other sedatives while using opioids. Store pills securely and do not share them. Dispose of any unused medication at a take\u2011back site or pharmacy.  \n- Use heat, gentle short walks, and avoid prolonged bed rest. If you can, arrange early PT or manual therapy within a few days.  \n- Red flags \u2014 go to the ED immediately for new leg weakness/numbness, saddle numbness, new urinary retention or incontinence, fever, or difficulty breathing.\n\nIf you want, I can shorten the message further for a small intake box or help you prepare a quick script to say on camera. Otherwise, good luck with the visit \u2014 let me know how it goes or if you need help interpreting the clinician\u2019s recommendations or arranging follow\u2011up."
