        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re in so much pain \u2014 I believe you, and I want to get you safer, faster relief while minimizing harms.\n\nA few quick points about opioids vs other options\n- Evidence and current guidelines do not recommend routinely using opioids (Percocet, Vicodin) for uncomplicated acute low back pain. Opioids give only modest short\u2011term pain relief but carry real risks (sedation, constipation, nausea, dependence, overdose).\n- That said, in selected patients with severe pain that is not controlled with first\u2011line measures, a very short, closely managed opioid trial can sometimes be considered. It should only be done after screening for risk factors, giving clear limits, and pairing it with nonopioid treatments and close follow\u2011up.\n\nWhat I recommend we do right away (safe first steps that often help)\n- Prescription NSAID (if no contraindications): naproxen 500 mg twice daily with food (or ibuprofen 600 mg every 6\u20138 hours).\n- Short course of a muscle relaxant for spasm/sleep: cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at bedtime (or 5 mg TID) for up to 1\u20132 weeks.\n- Topical option: diclofenac gel applied to the sore area, if you prefer fewer systemic effects.\n- Nonpharmacologic measures: heat packs several times daily, keep moving gently (short walks), avoid prolonged bed rest, and consider massage or spinal manipulation/PT as available.\n- If you\u2019re already taking acetaminophen, be sure total acetaminophen does not exceed 3,000 mg/day (preferably 3 g).\n\nIf you still want an opioid after trying the above\nI will consider a very short, limited opioid prescription only if:\n1) you have tried/agree to start the above NSAID \u00b1 muscle relaxant, and\n2) you do not have risk factors such as active substance use disorder, recent heavy opioid use, or untreated severe depression/ suicide risk.\n\nIf we proceed, a typical safe approach is:\n- A very short course of an immediate\u2011release opioid (for example, hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg or oxycodone 5 mg) as needed, limited to 3 days\u2019 supply, lowest effective dose, with explicit instructions to avoid other acetaminophen and to stop if unacceptable side effects occur.\n- Bowel prophylaxis (e.g., docusate + senna) and warnings about sedation \u2014 do not drive or operate machinery and avoid alcohol.\n- Close follow\u2011up within 48\u201372 hours to reassess pain, function, and side effects. No automatic refills.\n\nBefore I prescribe anything stronger: quick screening questions\n1. Any history of substance use disorder, alcohol dependence, or prior opioid dependence?\n2. Any current medications (esp. benzodiazepines, other sedatives, blood thinners)?\n3. Any stomach ulcers, kidney disease, liver disease, heart disease, or high blood pressure?\n4. Are you pregnant or breastfeeding?\n5. Any history of reaction/allergy to opioids, NSAIDs, or muscle relaxants?\n\nTell me the answers to those and whether you want to start the naproxen + cyclobenzaprine plan now or pursue a short opioid trial after screening. I\u2019ll get you a plan and follow\u2011up so we can get you moving and sleeping again."
        },
