        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Thanks \u2014 and I\u2019m really sorry this is so painful. I appreciate the clear answers about your meds and medical history. Based on what you\u2019ve told me, here\u2019s a safe, specific plan I will send and how to use it.\n\nPlan I will prescribe now\n1) Hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg \u2014 take 1 tablet every 6 hours as needed for severe pain.\n   - Important dosing limits and acetaminophen safety: you told me you already took 1000 mg at 8:00 and 1000 mg at 14:00 (total 2000 mg acetaminophen today). Because of that, please limit hydrocodone/acetaminophen to a maximum of 3 tablets today (3 \u00d7 325 mg = 975 mg acetaminophen), to keep your total acetaminophen today at or below ~3000 mg. \n   - After today, do not take any other products containing acetaminophen while using this medication, and do not exceed 4 tablets in any 24\u2011hour period (max 1300 mg acetaminophen from the tablets; total acetaminophen across all products should stay \u22643000 mg/day). \n   - Supply: 3\u2011day prescription (I will send 9 tablets unless you want a different amount).\n\n2) Naproxen 500 mg PO twice daily with food (stop taking OTC ibuprofen while on naproxen).\n   - Take with food to reduce stomach upset. Do not combine with other NSAIDs.\n\n3) Bowel prophylaxis (because opioids commonly cause constipation)\n   - Docusate sodium 100 mg PO twice daily, plus senna 8.6 mg PO at bedtime as needed.\n\nAdjunct measures (start now)\n- Superficial heat to the low back (hot pack 15\u201320 minutes several times/day).\n- Gentle movement and short walks as tolerated; avoid prolonged bed rest.\n- If you have trouble sleeping from spasm, consider cyclobenzaprine 5 mg at bedtime (caution: adds sedation; avoid driving while taking this with the opioid). Let me know if you want this added.\n\nSafety instructions (please read and follow)\n- Do not drink alcohol or take sedatives/benzodiazepines while using the opioid. Avoid driving or operating heavy machinery until you know how it affects you.\n- Expect constipation \u2014 start the stool regimen above now.\n- Stop the opioid as soon as pain is controlled and you can move comfortably. No automatic refills \u2014 we will reassess.\n- Keep medication in a secure place. Dispose of any unused tablets safely.\n- Call 911 or go to the ER right away for new numbness/weakness in the legs, loss of bladder/bowel control, severe shortness of breath, severe drowsiness or difficulty waking, or a high fever.\n\nFollow-up\n- I want to reassess you in 48\u201372 hours (phone or video) to check pain, function, side effects, and to make a plan to taper and stop the opioid quickly as pain improves. I will schedule that or you can message me a good time.\n- If your pain is not clearly improving after 48\u201372 hours despite this plan, or if new red\u2011flag symptoms develop, we\u2019ll arrange an in\u2011person exam and consider imaging or further workup.\n\nBefore I send the prescriptions\n- Confirm your preferred pharmacy name and location so I can e\u2011prescribe.\n- Do you want cyclobenzaprine added at bedtime for spasm/sleep?\n- Any questions or concerns about the instructions above?\n\nI know this is a hard time \u2014 I\u2019ll get the prescription sent as soon as you confirm your pharmacy and whether you want the muscle relaxant."
