          "content": "Safe travels to the pharmacy \u2014 and you\u2019re very welcome. Quick final reminders before you pick up and start the meds.\n\nMedications and key dosing limits\n- Hydrocodone/acetaminophen 5/325 mg: 1 tablet PO every 6 hours as needed for severe pain. Because you already took 2000 mg acetaminophen today, limit this med to a maximum of 3 tablets today (\u2248975 mg acetaminophen) so your total acetaminophen today \u22483000 mg. On subsequent days do not take other acetaminophen products while using this med and do not exceed 4 tablets/day (aim to keep total acetaminophen \u22643000 mg/day).\n- Naproxen 500 mg: 1 tablet PO twice daily with food. Stop OTC ibuprofen while taking naproxen.\n- Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg: 1 tablet PO at bedtime PRN for spasm/sleep. Can cause drowsiness; avoid driving while taking it, especially if you also use the opioid.\n- Constipation prophylaxis: docusate 100 mg PO twice daily + senna 8.6 mg PO at bedtime PRN \u2014 start now.\n\nNon\u2011drug measures\n- Superficial heat 15\u201320 minutes several times/day.\n- Gentle walking and light activity as tolerated; avoid prolonged bed rest.\n- Use a pillow between knees when sleeping if helpful.\n\nSafety precautions (very important)\n- Do NOT drink alcohol or take benzodiazepines/sedatives with the opioid or cyclobenzaprine.\n- Expect drowsiness/dizziness \u2014 do not drive or operate heavy machinery until you know how you react.\n- Keep meds secured and dispose of unused tablets safely.\n- No automatic opioid refills \u2014 we will reassess at follow\u2011up and stop/taper as pain improves.\n\nWhen to seek immediate care/ER\n- New or worsening leg numbness or weakness, inability to urinate or loss of bowel/bladder control, new high fever, severe shortness of breath, severe drowsiness/unresponsiveness, or pain that keeps worsening despite the meds \u2014 go to the ED or call 911.\n\nFollow\u2011up\n- I will call you tomorrow (Friday) between 2:00\u20134:00 PM CST at the