        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Below is a one\u2011page summary you can print, show on your phone, or read to an urgent care clinician or your PCP. I cannot send a controlled\u2011substance prescription from this chat; this is a prepared plan for a clinician to review and act on.\n\nPatient: 40\u2011year\u2011old with acute non\u2011radicular low back pain after lifting, severe pain 7/10, limited mobility, no fever, no trauma, no bowel/bladder changes, no numbness/weakness, no cancer history. No medication allergies, no liver/kidney/heart disease, no alcohol/substance misuse, not pregnant.\n\nPreferred pharmacy\n- [Pharmacy Name]\n- [Pharmacy Address/Phone Number]\n\nRequested (for clinician consideration)\n- Medication: Oxycodone 5 mg / Acetaminophen 325 mg (oxycodone/acetaminophen)\n- Sig: Take 1 tablet PO every 6 hours as needed for severe pain. Do not exceed one tablet every 6 hours.\n- Dispense: 12 tablets (3\u2011day supply)\n- Refills: None\n- Indication/diagnosis to list: Acute low back pain (lumbar muscle strain)\n- Counseling request: Review risks/side effects, advise bowel regimen, avoid other acetaminophen, counsel on safe use/storage/disposal.\n\nAccompanying immediate recommendations (for patient to follow now)\n- Do NOT take any additional acetaminophen (Tylenol) while using this medication. Avoid other combination products containing acetaminophen.\n- Start bowel regimen immediately to prevent opioid\u2011induced constipation:\n  - Docusate 100 mg PO twice daily AND senna 8.6 mg PO at night\n  - OR polyethylene glycol (Miralax) 17 g PO once daily\n- Avoid alcohol and other sedating drugs (benzodiazepines, sleep medicines) while taking opioids.\n- Do not drive or operate heavy machinery until you know how the medication affects you.\n- Store medication securely and do not share. Dispose unused tablets at an approved take\u2011back site or pharmacy disposal program.\n\nAdjuncts to use concurrently (if tolerated)\n- Continue ibuprofen (if no contraindication): e.g., ibuprofen 400\u2013600 mg PO every 6\u20138 hours with food as needed. (Clinician to confirm appropriate daily limit based on individual risks.)\n- Apply superficial heat to the area, stay as active as tolerated (gentle walking), avoid prolonged bed rest.\n- Consider topical diclofenac gel or lidocaine patches for additional local pain control.\n\nSafety, monitoring, and follow\u2011up\n- Plan clinician follow\u2011up (phone or clinic) within 48\u201372 hours to reassess pain, function, and need to continue opioid. If pain is not meaningfully improved by 72 hours, discontinue opioid and arrange in\u2011person evaluation.\n- Clinician should check the state PDMP prior to prescribing and discuss opioid risks/benefits.\n- Red flags requiring immediate urgent/ED evaluation: fever, progressive leg weakness or numbness, saddle anesthesia, new bladder or bowel dysfunction, worsening or unrelenting pain, severe drowsiness, or breathing difficulty.\n\nNotes for the clinician\n- This is requested as a short, time\u2011limited opioid trial for severe acute musculoskeletal low back pain to permit sleep, reduce pain enough to enable gentle mobilization, and avoid prolonged immobilization. Recommend lowest effective dose for shortest duration (3 days). Provide clear instructions for taper/stop and safe disposal of unused medicine.\n\nIf you would like, I can format this as a printed note or an email text to hand to the urgent care/PCP. Tell me if you want that. I\u2019m glad you have a plan to get this addressed quickly \u2014 please seek care now and call or return here after your 48\u201372 hour follow\u2011up so we can reassess."
