          "content": "I\u2019m glad that went smoothly and that you\u2019re already feeling some relief \u2014 that\u2019s very encouraging. A few brief, important reminders now that you\u2019ve started the medication and have a PCP follow\u2011up scheduled:\n\nWhat to keep doing\n- Continue the bowel regimen you started: docusate 100 mg PO twice daily + senna 8.6 mg PO at night (or PEG 17 g once daily). Drink plenty of fluids and increase fiber to help prevent constipation. If you have no bowel movement for 48 hours despite this, let your clinician know \u2014 a stronger laxative may be needed.\n- Continue ibuprofen (400\u2013600 mg every 6\u20138 hours with food) as tolerated for inflammation/pain and use superficial heat to the area. Gentle walking and brief, frequent activity is helpful \u2014 avoid prolonged bed rest.\n- Use positioning that eases pain for sleep: back with a pillow under knees or side with a pillow between knees.\n\nSafety precautions (very important)\n- Do NOT take any additional acetaminophen (Tylenol) while using your oxycodone/acetaminophen. This prescription already contains acetaminophen; adding more risks liver injury.\n- Avoid alcohol and other sedating drugs (benzodiazepines, sleep meds, muscle relaxants unless specifically recommended and timed carefully). Do not drive or operate heavy machinery until you know how the medication affects you.\n- Keep the medication secure, do not share it, and plan to dispose of any unused tablets at an approved take\u2011back site or pharmacy after you stop.\n\nMonitoring and follow\u2011up\n- Aim to stop the opioid as soon as pain and function allow \u2014 this prescription is a short trial to get you moving and sleeping. You have the right plan to reassess with your PCP in 48 hours; discuss taper/stop then.\n- If pain is not meaningfully better within 48\u201372 hours despite the plan, or if you need the opioid beyond a few days, see your PCP for re\u2011evaluation (consider physical exam, imaging only if red flags, and referral to PT or other nonpharmacologic therapies).\n- Consider adding a short, nighttime muscle relaxant (e.g., cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg at night) only after discussing with your PCP if muscle spasm limits sleep \u2014 do not combine with other sedatives without clinician guidance.\n\nRed flags \u2014 seek immediate care/ED if any of these occur\n- New or worsening leg weakness, numbness, or \u201csaddle\u201d numbness\n- New bladder or bowel incontinence\n- Fever or signs of infection\n- Severe unrelenting pain despite medication\n- Excessive drowsiness, confusion, slow or shallow breathing, or difficulty waking\n\nIf you want, after your 48\u2011hour PCP visit tell me how you\u2019re doing and I can help with a taper plan, safe disposal instructions for unused pills, guidance on PT/exercises, or other next steps. Wishing you steady improvement and restful sleep \u2014 glad you got some relief, and I\u2019m here if you need anything further."
