        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m really glad you\u2019re feeling better and that you\u2019re already moving a bit more \u2014 that\u2019s exactly the goal. A few concise, important points to keep you safe and make the most of this short course.\n\nWhat to do over the next 48 hours\n- Use the oxycodone/acetaminophen only as needed for severe pain and try to reduce frequency as pain allows. Aim to stop it as soon as you can manage sleep and basic activity without it.  \n- Continue ibuprofen (400\u2013600 mg every 6\u20138 hours with food) as tolerated and keep up the bowel regimen (docusate + senna or PEG) until bowel function is normal.  \n- Avoid alcohol and other sedating drugs; don\u2019t drive or operate machinery until you know how the medication affects you.  \n- Apply superficial heat to the painful area (20 minutes several times a day) and do short, frequent walks rather than long rest periods.\n\nTapering / stopping the opioid\n- For a short, time\u2011limited course like this (3 days), most people can stop abruptly when pain is controlled and do not require a formal taper.  \n- If you end up using the medicine daily beyond 5\u20137 days or feel you\u2019re using it more than intended, contact your PCP for a taper plan. A clinician can arrange a gradual dose reduction and support to avoid withdrawal.  \n- If you notice any withdrawal symptoms (anxiety, body aches, sweating, yawning, runny nose, tremor), contact your PCP or urgent care.\n\nNext steps for recovery\n- Keep your PCP follow\u2011up in 48 hours to reassess pain, stop the opioid if appropriate, and discuss PT referral. Early, guided physical therapy or a home exercise program speeds recovery: pelvic tilts, knee\u2011to\u2011chest, gentle trunk rotations, and hamstring stretches are usually helpful. I can write a brief PT request or give specific home exercise instructions if you\u2019d like.  \n- Consider topical options (diclofenac gel or lidocaine patch) for added local pain relief.\n\nDisposal of unused pills\n- Return unused tablets to a pharmacy take\u2011back program if possible. If no take\u2011back is available, mix them with unpalatable material (coffee grounds, kitty litter), place in a sealed container, and discard in household trash per local guidance. Do not flush unless the medication label or local guidance specifically says to do so.\n\nRed flags (return to ED/urgent care immediately)\n- New or worsening leg weakness or numbness, saddle numbness, new bladder/bowel incontinence, fever, severe unrelenting pain, or slow/shallow breathing or extreme drowsiness.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, after your PCP visit tell me what they recommend and I\u2019ll help with a taper plan, PT exercises tailored to your exam, or safe disposal wording for any leftover pills. Very glad you\u2019ve got some relief \u2014 keep me posted on how you\u2019re doing."
