        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I\u2019m glad this will help. Below is a clear, printable \u201cprescription recommendation\u201d note you can bring to an urgent care clinic, primary care office, or telemedicine visit. It is written for the treating clinician to review, complete, and sign \u2014 it is not itself a legal prescription.\n\nPlease print or copy this text and bring it with you.\n\n------------------------------\nPatient name: ___________________________   DOB: _______________   Date: _______________\n\nClinical summary (patient report):\n- 40\u2011year\u2011old with acute low back pain after lifting heavy box 3 days ago.\n- Pain severe (7/10), limits movement, sitting, and sleep.\n- No major trauma, no fever, no bowel/bladder dysfunction, no leg weakness or numbness.\n- Tried OTC ibuprofen up to 800 mg q6h and acetaminophen up to 1000 mg q6h for 3 days without adequate relief.\n- No history of substance use disorder. No known drug allergies.\n\nPatient request:\n- Patient requests a short, time\u2011limited opioid trial (Percocet preferred) for severe acute back pain to restore function and sleep. Patient consents to safety measures and follow\u2011up.\n\nSuggested clinician actions (for consideration)\n1) Review PDMP prior to prescribing.\n2) Confirm patient understanding of risks/benefits, safe use, and plan for follow\u2011up (48\u201372 hours).\n\nSuggested short opioid trial (if clinician agrees)\n- Medication (example): Oxycodone 5 mg / acetaminophen 325 mg (Percocet)\n  - Sig: Take 1 tablet PO every 6 hours PRN for severe pain.\n  - Max: 4 tablets per 24 hours.\n  - Dispense: 12 tablets (3\u2011day supply). No refills without reassessment.\n  - Note: Consider alternative hydrocodone/acetaminophen if preferred.\n\nImportant safety instructions to give patient (must counsel)\n- Stop all other acetaminophen immediately if prescribing combination opioid/acetaminophen product. Do not exceed total acetaminophen per prescriber\u2019s guidance (commonly \u22643,000\u20133,250 mg/day).\n- Avoid alcohol while taking opioid or acetaminophen.\n- Do not combine with benzodiazepines or other sedating medications.\n- Do not drive or operate heavy machinery until effects known.\n- Store securely and dispose of unused tablets at an approved take\u2011back site.\n- Start stool softener now: Docusate 100 mg PO twice daily (or as directed).\n\nFollow\u2011up and monitoring\n- Reassess in 48\u201372 hours (phone or telehealth). Stop opioid when pain is tolerable with non\u2011opioid measures.\n- Limit total duration to 3 days initially; extend to a maximum of 7 days only after in\u2011person reassessment and clear benefit.\n- Document PDMP check and counseling.\n\nConcurrent non\u2011opioid measures to recommend\n- Superficial heat 15\u201320 minutes several times daily.\n- Gentle activity/walking as tolerated; avoid prolonged bed rest and heavy lifting.\n- Sleep position: pillow under knees (supine) or between knees (side\u2011lying).\n- Consider PT referral, spinal manipulation, acupuncture, or massage as available.\n- If avoiding opioids, consider: Naproxen 500 mg PO twice daily with food + cyclobenzaprine 5\u201310 mg PO at bedtime for short course.\n\nWarning signs prompting urgent evaluation / ED\n- New or worsening leg weakness or numbness\n- Saddle anesthesia (groin/perineal numbness)\n- New bowel or bladder incontinence or retention\n- Fever, signs of infection\n- Severe respiratory depression or extreme sedation while medicated\n\nClinician signature: ___________________________   Date: _______________\nClinician phone: ___________________________\n\n------------------------------\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can also prepare a single-page PDF formatted for printing. Would you like that?"
