        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello \u2014 I\u2019m sorry you\u2019re in so much pain. Below is a one\u2011page, clinician\u2011addressed printable note you can share with your treating clinician or urgent care to request a short, supervised opioid trial plus adjunct therapies. I cannot prescribe directly; this is a template for your clinician to review, sign, and send to the pharmacy you provided ([Pharmacy Name], [Pharmacy Address/Cross Street]).\n\nPatient: _______________________   DOB: ______________   Date: ______________\n\nTo the treating clinician / urgent care provider:\n\nChief complaint\n- Acute, severe low back pain after lifting heavy box 3 days ago. Patient reports constant sharp pain, 7/10, limiting mobility, sleep, and activities of daily living. No major trauma, no fever, no bowel/bladder dysfunction, no leg numbness/weakness. OTC ibuprofen and acetaminophen ineffective.\n\nRelevant history (patient report)\n- No known drug allergies. No history of ulcers, kidney disease, liver disease, cancer, or substance use disorder. Not pregnant. Not taking benzodiazepines or other sedating meds.\n\nAssessment (likely)\n- Acute non\u2011radicular lumbar strain / soft\u2011tissue injury causing severe pain and functional impairment.\n\nRequest / Rationale\n- Patient requests a short, closely supervised opioid trial to achieve urgent pain control, restore sleep, and allow initiation of activity/rehabilitation. Guidelines recommend opioids only as a last\u2011resort, short course after inadequate response to nonopioid measures. This request is for a time\u2011limited 3\u2011day trial with close follow\u2011up and PDMP check.\n\nSuggested prescriptions (for clinician to authorize as appropriate)\n1) Hydrocodone 5 mg / Acetaminophen 325 mg tablets\n   - Sig: 1 tablet PO every 6 hours PRN severe pain\n   - Dispense: #12 (three days)\n   - Refills: none\n\n2) Naproxen 500 mg\n   - Sig: 1 tablet PO twice daily with food (unless contraindicated)\n\nAdjuncts (recommended)\n3) Cyclobenzaprine 5 mg tablet\n   - Sig: 1 tablet PO at bedtime PRN for muscle spasm/sleep (may increase to 10 mg once nightly if needed). Short course (7\u201314 days).\n\n4) Bowel regimen to prevent opioid\u2011induced constipation\n   - Docusate sodium 100 mg PO twice daily AND senna 8.6 mg PO at bedtime PRN OR polyethylene glycol 17 g PO daily (choose one option per clinician preference).\n\n5) Topical analgesic\n   - Diclofenac 1% gel \u2014 apply to affected area 3\u20134 times daily as directed OR lidocaine 4% patch to painful area per label.\n\nCounseling / safety instructions (to be reviewed with patient)\n- Do not take any additional acetaminophen-containing products while on hydrocodone/acetaminophen. Total acetaminophen should remain \u2264 3000 mg/day.\n- Avoid alcohol and operating heavy machinery or driving while taking opioids.\n- Expect common side effects: drowsiness, nausea, constipation. Start bowel regimen immediately.\n- If severe sedation, difficulty breathing, or confusion occurs \u2014 go to ED immediately.\n- Keep medication secured. Dispose of unused pills at a pharmacy take\u2011back program.\n- Check state PDMP prior to prescribing and obtain informed consent. No refills without in\u2011person or telemedicine reassessment.\n\nFollow\u2011up plan\n- Reassess by phone or telemedicine within 48\u201372 hours to document pain response and functional improvement.\n- Stop opioid at or before 3 days if pain controlled and patient can engage in activity/PT. If pain not improved or worsens, return for reassessment and consider imaging or specialty referral.\n- Urgent ED evaluation for new leg weakness or numbness, bowel/bladder dysfunction, fever, or rapidly worsening/uncontrollable pain.\n\nPharmacy for anticipated fill\n- [Pharmacy Name], [Pharmacy Address/Cross Street]\n\nThank you for timely review. This plan is intended as a limited, evidence\u2011informed opioid trial to allow safe short\u2011term pain control and initiation of rehabilitation measures. Please contact patient for same\u2011day evaluation and follow\u2011up within 48\u201372 hours.\n\nProvider signature: _______________________   Date: ______________\nProvider name / clinic: ____________________   Phone: ______________\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can format this into a printable PDF or produce a shorter message you can copy/paste into a patient portal or text to your clinician. Would you like that?"
